,"morph":"He,Td:Ncmsa"},{"type":"text","text":"׃\n\n"}]}', 'בַּ⁠יּ֣וֹם הַ⁠ה֗וּא יִֽהְיֶה֙ עַל־מְצִלּ֣וֹת הַ⁠סּ֔וּס קֹ֖דֶשׁ לַֽ⁠יהוָ֑ה וְ⁠הָיָ֤ה הַ⁠סִּירוֹת֙ בְּ⁠בֵ֣ית יְהוָ֔ה כַּ⁠מִּזְרָקִ֖ים לִ⁠פְנֵ֥י הַ⁠מִּזְבֵּֽחַ׃');
INSERT INTO verses (book, chapter, verse, bible_version, content_json, plain_text) VALUES ('ZEC', 14, 21, 'UHB', '{"verseObjects":[{"text":"וְ֠⁠הָיָה","tag":"w","type":"word","lemma":"הָיָה","strong":"c:H1961","morph":"He,C:Vqq3ms"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"כָּל","tag":"w","type":"word","lemma":"כֹּל","strong":"H3605","morph":"He,Ncmsc"},{"type":"text","text":"־"},{"text":"סִ֨יר","tag":"w","type":"word","lemma":"סִיר","strong":"H5518a","morph":"He,Ncbsa"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"בִּ⁠ירוּשָׁלִַ֜ם","tag":"w","type":"word","lemma":"יְרוּשָׁלִַ͏ם","strong":"b:H3389","morph":"He,R:Np"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"וּ⁠בִֽ⁠יהוּדָ֗ה","tag":"w","type":"word","lemma":"יְהוּדָה","strong":"c:b:H3063","morph":"He,C:R:Np"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"קֹ֚דֶשׁ","tag":"w","type":"word","lemma":"קֹדֶשׁ","strong":"H6944","morph":"He,Ncmsa"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"לַ⁠יהוָ֣ה","tag":"w","type":"word","lemma":"יְהֹוָה","strong":"l:H3068","morph":"He,R:Np"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"צְבָא֔וֹת","tag":"w","type":"word","lemma":"צָבָא","strong":"H6635b","morph":"He,Ncbpa"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"וּ⁠בָ֨אוּ֙","tag":"w","type":"word","lemma":"בּוֹא","strong":"c:H0935","morph":"He,C:Vqq3cp"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"כָּל","tag":"w","type":"word","lemma":"כֹּל","strong":"H3605","morph":"He,Ncmsc"},{"type":"text","text":"־"},{"text":"הַ⁠זֹּ֣בְחִ֔ים","tag":"w","type":"word","lemma":"זָבַח","strong":"d:H2076","morph":"He,Td:Vqrmpa"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"וְ⁠לָקְח֥וּ","tag":"w","type":"word","lemma":"לָקַח","strong":"c:H3947","morph":"He,C:Vqq3cp"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"מֵ⁠הֶ֖ם","tag":"w","type":"word","lemma":"","strong":"m","morph":"He,R:Sp3mp"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"וּ⁠בִשְּׁל֣וּ","tag":"w","type":"word","lemma":"בָּשַׁל","strong":"c:H1310","morph":"He,C:Vpq3cp"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"בָ⁠הֶ֑ם","tag":"w","type":"word","lemma":"","strong":"b","morph":"He,R:Sp3mp"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"וְ⁠לֹא","tag":"w","type":"word","lemma":"לֹא","strong":"c:H3808","morph":"He,C:Tn"},{"type":"text","text":"־"},{"text":"יִהְיֶ֨ה","tag":"w","type":"word","lemma":"הָיָה","strong":"H1961","morph":"He,Vqi3ms"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"כְנַעֲנִ֥י","tag":"w","type":"word","lemma":"כְּנַעַנִי","strong":"H3669b","morph":"He,Ngmsa"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"ע֛וֹד","tag":"w","type":"word","lemma":"עוֹד","strong":"H5750","morph":"He,D"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"בְּ⁠בֵית","tag":"w","type":"word","lemma":"בַּיִת","strong":"b:H1004b","morph":"He,R:Ncmsc"},{"type":"text","text":"־"},{"text":"יְהוָ֥ה","tag":"w","type":"word","lemma":"יְהֹוָה","strong":"H3068","morph":"He,Np"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"צְבָא֖וֹת","tag":"w","type":"word","lemma":"צָבָא","strong":"H6635b","morph":"He,Ncbpa"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"בַּ⁠יּ֥וֹם","tag":"w","type":"word","lemma":"יוֹם","strong":"b:H3117","morph":"He,Rd:Ncmsa"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"הַ⁠הֽוּא","tag":"w","type":"word","lemma":"הוּא","strong":"d:H1931","morph":"He,Td:Pp3ms"},{"type":"text","text":"׃\n"}]}', 'וְ֠⁠הָיָה כָּל־סִ֨יר בִּ⁠ירוּשָׁלִַ֜ם וּ⁠בִֽ⁠יהוּדָ֗ה קֹ֚דֶשׁ לַ⁠יהוָ֣ה צְבָא֔וֹת וּ⁠בָ֨אוּ֙ כָּל־הַ⁠זֹּ֣בְחִ֔ים וְ⁠לָקְח֥וּ מֵ⁠הֶ֖ם וּ⁠בִשְּׁל֣וּ בָ⁠הֶ֑ם וְ⁠לֹא־יִהְיֶ֨ה כְנַעֲנִ֥י ע֛וֹד בְּ⁠בֵית־יְהוָ֥ה צְבָא֖וֹת בַּ⁠יּ֥וֹם הַ⁠הֽוּא׃');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('yx6e', 'ZEC', 0, 0, 'front:intro', NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, '# Introduction to Zechariah\n\n## Part 1: General Introduction\n\n### Outline of the Book of Zechariah\n\n1. Zechariah calls the returning nation of Israel to repent and return to Yahweh ([1:1–6](../01/01.md))\n1. The eight night visions ([1:7–6:8](../01/07.md))\n    * Yahweh sends his messengers throughout the whole earth ([1:7–17](../01/07.md))\n    * Four horns and four craftsmen ([1:18–21](../01/18.md))\n    * The measuring line ([2:1–13](../02/01.md))\n    * The priest in filthy clothes ([3:1–10](../03/01.md))\n    * The golden lampstand olive trees ([4:1–14](../04/01.md))\n    * The flying scroll ([5:1–4](../05/01.md))\n    * The woman in a basket ([5:5–11](../05/05.md))\n    * Four chariots ([6:1–8](../06/01.md))\n1. A crown for the high priest ([6:9–15](../06/09.md))\n1. Questions about fasting ([7:1–8:23](../07/01.md))\n1. Yahweh judges the nations and saves his people ([9:1–11:17](../09/01.md))\n1. Final message ([12:1–14:21](../12/01.md))\n    * Yahweh will finally defeat Israel’s enemies ([12:1–9](../12/01.md))\n    * Israel mourns for the one they pierced ([12:10–14](../12/10.md))\n    * Yahweh purifies Israel and removes false prophets ([13:1–6](../13/01.md))\n    * Yahweh comes as king ([14:1–21](../14/01.md))\n\n### What is the Book of Zechariah about?\n\nZechariah wrote to the people of Judah who returned from being exiled in Babylon. The people of Judah continued to sin, as their ancestors did before they went into exile. Zechariah called the people to repent and to obey Yahweh. And he called them to renew the covenant with Yahweh. Zechariah also prophesied about the Messiah and about Israel finally being victorious over her enemies. (See: [[rc://*/tw/dict/bible/kt/covenant]])\n\n### How should the title of this book be translated?\n\nThis book traditionally has been titled “Zechariah” or “The Book of Zechariah.” Translators may decide to call it the “The Book About Zechariah” or “The Sayings of Zechariah.” (See: [[rc://*/ta/man/translate/translate-names]])\n\n### Who wrote the Book of Zechariah?\n\nThe prophet Zechariah wrote this book between 520 and 518 B.C.\n\n## Part 2: Important Religious and Cultural Concepts\n\n### Did Zechariah prophesy before Ezra, Nehemiah, and Haggai?\n\nZechariah prophesied before the time of Ezra and Nehemiah. He prophesied at the same time as Haggai and continued after Haggai.\n\n## Part 3: Important Translation Issues\n\n### What is the meaning of the term “Israel”?\n\nThe name “Israel” is used in many different ways in the Bible. Jacob was a son of Isaac. God changed Jacob’s name to Israel. The descendants of Jacob became a nation also called Israel. Eventually, the nation of Israel split into two kingdoms. The northern kingdom was named Israel. The southern kingdom was named Judah. Zechariah uses the term “Israel” to refer to both the nation of Israel and the northern kingdom of Israel.\n\n### What imagery does Zechariah use in reference to the Messiah?\n\nZechariah presented the Messiah as both a king and a shepherd. Zechariah said that the Messiah would come and deliver his people. However, the Messiah would also be pierced ([12:10](../12/10.md)) and struck with the sword ([13:7](../13/07.md)). (See: [[rc://*/tw/dict/bible/kt/christ]])\n\n### What does the phrase “that day” mean?\n\nZechariah often spoke of the last days by using the phrase “that day” or “in that day.” When referring to a future “day,” the translator should be aware that the author may be speaking about the last days. (See: [[rc://*/tw/dict/bible/kt/lastday]])');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('qki3', 'ZEC', 1, 0, '1:intro', NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, '# Zechariah 1 General Notes\n\n## Structure and Formatting\n\nThis chapter is written in prose mainly with imagery used throughout to portray Zechariah’s vision given by the Lord.\n\nSome translations prefer to set apart quotations. The ULT and many other English translations set lines 1:3–6, 14–17, which are extended quotations, farther to the right on the page than the rest of the text.\n\n## Religious and Cultural Concepts in This Chapter\n\n### Visions\n\nThis book contains a number of visions given to Zechariah, so the images are not ones Zechariah actually saw but were given to him in a vision or dream. It is important for each of these visions to keep their meanings and not be interpreted to mean any specific thing.\n\n## Translation Issues in This Chapter\n\n### Date\n\nZechariah uses two separate dates in this first chapter. When compared to the book of Haggai, Zechariah’s prophecy was proclaimed just a few weeks after Haggai. However, they prophesied in two different places: Haggai was in Jerusalem and Zechariah was somewhere outside of Jerusalem. (See: [[rc://*/tw/dict/bible/kt/prophet]])');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('c5as', 'ZEC', 1, 1, '1:1', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-idiom', 'הָיָ֣ה דְבַר־יְהוָ֗ה אֶל־זְכַרְיָה֙', 1, 'Zechariah is using **the word of Yahweh came to Zechariah** as a common expression of the culture to mean “Yahweh communicated a message to Zechariah.” If this phrase does not have that meaning for your readers, you could use a comparable expression from your language that does have that meaning, or you could state the meaning plainly. Alternate translation: [Yahweh spoke his message to Zechariah] or [Yahweh gave his message to Zechariah]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('bra8', 'ZEC', 1, 1, '1:1', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-newevent', 'בַּ⁠חֹ֨דֶשׁ֙ הַ⁠שְּׁמִינִ֔י בִּ⁠שְׁנַ֥ת שְׁתַּ֖יִם לְ⁠דָרְיָ֑וֶשׁ', 1, 'Zechariah is using the phrase **In the eighth month, in the second year of Darius** to introduce a new event in the story (in this case, the very beginning). Use a word, phrase, or other method in your language that is natural for introducing a new event.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('kog5', 'ZEC', 1, 2, '1:2', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-poetry', 'קָצַ֧ף & קָֽצֶף', 1, 'Yahweh is using a construction in which a verb and its object come from the same root. You may be able to use the same construction in your language to express the meaning here. Alternatively, your language may have another way of saying this. Alternate translation: [was extremely angry]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('x9ar', 'ZEC', 1, 3, '1:3', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metaphor', 'שׁ֣וּבוּ אֵלַ֔⁠י', 1, 'Here Yahweh is speaking as if the people’s relationship with him were a place that they had physically left and could physically come back to. Your language may have a comparable expression that you can use in your translation, or you could state the meaning plainly. Alternate translation: [Be faithful to me again] or [Renew your commitment to me]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('lw80', 'ZEC', 1, 3, '1:3', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metaphor', 'וְ⁠אָשׁ֣וּב אֲלֵי⁠כֶ֔ם', 1, 'Here Yahweh is speaking as if his renewed favor toward the people were a physical movement back to them. Your language may have a comparable expression that you can use in your translation, or you could state the meaning plainly. Alternate translation: [and I will be favorable to you again] or [and I will bless you again]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('hm40', 'ZEC', 1, 3, '1:3', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-quotations', 'וְ⁠אָמַרְתָּ֣ אֲלֵ⁠הֶ֗ם כֹּ֤ה אָמַר֙ יְהוָ֣ה צְבָא֔וֹת', 1, 'If it would be clearer in your language, you could translate this so that there is not a quotation within a quotation. Alternate translation: [And you shall tell them that Yahweh of Armies says this]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('gc9s', 'ZEC', 1, 3, '1:3', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-quotations', 'נְאֻ֖ם יְהוָ֣ה צְבָא֑וֹת', 1, 'The term **the declaration of Yahweh of Armies** introduces a parenthetical affirmation of the source of this direct quotation. In your translation, use a natural way of indicating the authoritative source of direct quotations in your language. It may not be necessary to represent this term explicitly.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('xoxv', 'ZEC', 1, 3, '1:3', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/grammar-connect-condition-hypothetical', 'שׁ֣וּבוּ אֵלַ֔⁠י & וְ⁠אָשׁ֣וּב אֲלֵי⁠כֶ֔ם', 1, 'Here, **Return to me** introduces the first part of a possible condition. Yahweh will only do the thing in the second part, **and I will return to you**, if this condition happens. Use a natural form in your language for introducing a condition that could happen. Alternate translation: [If you return to me, then I will return to you]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('i8gr', 'ZEC', 1, 4, '1:4', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-doublet', 'מִ⁠דַּרְכֵי⁠כֶ֣ם הָ⁠רָעִ֔ים וּמַֽעַלְלֵיכֶ֖ם הָֽ⁠רָעִ֑ים', 1, 'The terms **evil ways** and **evil deeds** mean similar things. Yahweh is using the two terms together for emphasis. If it would be clearer for your readers, you could express the emphasis with a single phrase. Alternate translation: [from all of your evil conduct]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('j8bs', 'ZEC', 1, 4, '1:4', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metaphor', 'מִ⁠דַּרְכֵי⁠כֶ֣ם הָ⁠רָעִ֔ים', 1, 'Yahweh is speaking of how the ancestors lived as if that were a **way** or path that they were walking along. If it would be helpful in your language, you could state the meaning plainly. Alternate translation: [from your evil behavior]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('dluc', 'ZEC', 1, 4, '1:4', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/grammar-connect-logic-contrast', 'וְ⁠לֹ֥א שָׁמְע֛וּ וְ⁠לֹֽא־הִקְשִׁ֥יבוּ', 1, 'Yahweh uses the word **But** here to indicate a contrast between what the former prophets told the ancestors to do and what the ancestors actually did. In your translation, indicate this contrast in a way that is natural in your language. Alternate translation: [However, they did not hear, and they did not pay attention]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('khup', 'ZEC', 1, 4, '1:4', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-quotations', 'לֵ⁠אמֹ֗ר כֹּ֤ה אָמַר֙ יְהוָ֣ה צְבָא֔וֹת', 1, 'If it would be clearer in your language, you could translate this so that there is not a quotation within a quotation. Alternate translation: [and told them that Yahweh of Armies had said to]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('ukxb', 'ZEC', 1, 4, '1:4', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-doublet', 'וְ⁠לֹ֥א שָׁמְע֛וּ וְ⁠לֹֽא־הִקְשִׁ֥יבוּ אֵלַ֖⁠י', 1, 'The terms **did not hear** and **did not pay attention** mean similar things. Yahweh is using the two terms together for emphasis. If it would be clearer for your readers, you could express the emphasis with a single phrase. Alternate translation: [But they completely refused to obey me]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('h3us', 'ZEC', 1, 5, '1:5', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-rquestion', 'וְ⁠הַ֨⁠נְּבִאִ֔ים הַ⁠לְ⁠עוֹלָ֖ם יִֽחְיֽוּ', 1, 'Yahweh is using the question form to emphasize that the prophets also died. If a speaker of your language would not use the question form for that purpose, you could translate this as a statement or as an exclamation. Alternate translation: [And the prophets did not live forever either.]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('nx2k', 'ZEC', 1, 5, '1:5', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-rquestion', 'אֲבֽוֹתֵי⁠כֶ֖ם אַיֵּה־הֵ֑ם', 1, 'Yahweh is using the question form to emphasize that the ancestors are dead. If a speaker of your language would not use the question form for that purpose, you could translate this as a statement or as an exclamation. Alternate translation: [Your fathers are no longer alive.]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('c5ci', 'ZEC', 1, 6, '1:6', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/grammar-connect-logic-contrast', 'אַ֣ךְ דְּבָרַ֣⁠י וְ⁠חֻקַּ֗⁠י', 1, 'Yahweh uses the word **But** here to indicate a contrast between the mortality of the fathers and prophets and the enduring effect of God’s words and statutes. In your translation, indicate this contrast in a way that is natural in your language. Alternate translation: [However, my words and my statutes]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('rfrk', 'ZEC', 1, 6, '1:6', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-rquestion', 'הֲ⁠ל֥וֹא הִשִּׂ֖יגוּ אֲבֹתֵי⁠כֶ֑ם', 1, 'Yahweh is using the question form to emphasize that his words certainly did overtake the ancestors. If a speaker of your language would not use the question form for that purpose, you could translate this as a statement or as an exclamation. Alternate translation: [they certainly overtook your fathers.]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('ipxv', 'ZEC', 1, 6, '1:6', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-pronouns', 'וַ⁠יָּשׁ֣וּבוּ וַ⁠יֹּאמְר֗וּ', 1, 'The pronoun **they** refers to the ancestors, not to the words and statutes mentioned earlier in the verse. It may be helpful to clarify this for your readers. Alternate translation: [And your ancestors repented and said]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('diwt', 'ZEC', 1, 6, '1:6', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metaphor', 'כִּ⁠דְרָכֵ֨י⁠נוּ֙ וּ⁠כְ⁠מַ֣עֲלָלֵ֔י⁠נוּ', 1, 'The ancestors are speaking of how they lived as if that were a **way** or path that they were walking along. If it would be helpful in your language, you could state the meaning plainly. Alternate translation: [according to how we behaved and according to what we did]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('xt7o', 'ZEC', 1, 6, '1:6', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-personification', 'דְּבָרַ֣⁠י וְ⁠חֻקַּ֗⁠י & הִשִּׂ֖יגוּ אֲבֹתֵי⁠כֶ֑ם', 1, 'Yahweh is speaking of **my words and my statutes** as if they were living things that could pursue and catch people. If it would be helpful in your language, you could state the meaning plainly. Alternate translation: [my words and my statutes, … did they not come true for your fathers]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('sup8', 'ZEC', 1, 7, '1:7', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-newevent', 'בְּ⁠יוֹם֩ עֶשְׂרִ֨ים וְ⁠אַרְבָּעָ֜ה', 1, 'Zechariah is using the phrase **On the twenty-fourth day** to introduce a new event in the story. Use a word, phrase, or other method in your language that is natural for introducing a new event.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('c2wo', 'ZEC', 1, 7, '1:7', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-idiom', 'הָיָ֣ה דְבַר־יְהוָ֗ה אֶל־זְכַרְיָה֙', 1, 'Zechariah is using **the word of Yahweh came to Zechariah** as a common expression of the culture to mean “Yahweh communicated a message to Zechariah.” If this phrase does not have that meaning for your readers, you could use a comparable expression from your language that does have that meaning, or you could state the meaning plainly. Alternate translation: [Yahweh spoke his message to Zechariah] or [Yahweh gave his message to Zechariah]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('g6xm', 'ZEC', 1, 8, '1:8', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-newevent', 'רָאִ֣יתִי הַ⁠לַּ֗יְלָה וְ⁠הִנֵּה', 1, 'Zechariah is using the phrase **I saw in the night, and behold** to introduce a new event in the story. Use a word, phrase, or other method in your language that is natural for introducing a new event.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('pjw4', 'ZEC', 1, 10, '1:10', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-quotations', 'וַ⁠יַּ֗עַן & וַ⁠יֹּאמַ֑ר', 1, 'The terms **answered and said** together introduce a direct quotation. In your translation, use a natural way of introducing direct quotations in your language. It may not be necessary to represent both terms explicitly.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('t5x5', 'ZEC', 1, 10, '1:10', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-pronouns', 'אֵ֚לֶּה', 1, 'The pronoun **These** refers to the horses and their riders that Yahweh sent to patrol the earth. It may be helpful to clarify this for your readers. Alternate translation: [These horses and riders]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('h0e7', 'ZEC', 1, 11, '1:11', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-pronouns', 'וַֽ⁠יַּעֲנ֞וּ', 1, 'The pronoun **they** refers to the horse riders who had been patrolling the earth, described in verse 8. It may be helpful to clarify this for your readers. Alternate translation: [And the riders answered]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('bau4', 'ZEC', 1, 11, '1:11', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-quotations', 'וַֽ⁠יַּעֲנ֞וּ & וַ⁠יֹּאמְר֖וּ', 1, 'The terms **answered** and **said** together introduce a direct quotation. In your translation, use a natural way of introducing direct quotations in your language. It may not be necessary to represent both terms explicitly.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('txlq', 'ZEC', 1, 11, '1:11', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-personification', 'כָל־הָ⁠אָ֖רֶץ יֹשֶׁ֥בֶת וְ⁠שֹׁקָֽטֶת', 1, 'The riders are speaking of **all of the earth** as if it were a living thing that could sit down and be quiet. If it would be helpful in your language, you could state the meaning plainly. Alternate translation: [all the peoples of the earth are peaceful and calm]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('wiu2', 'ZEC', 1, 12, '1:12', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-rquestion', 'עַד־מָתַ֗י אַתָּה֙ לֹֽא־תְרַחֵ֣ם אֶת־יְרוּשָׁלִַ֔ם וְ⁠אֵ֖ת עָרֵ֣י יְהוּדָ֑ה אֲשֶׁ֣ר זָעַ֔מְתָּה זֶ֖ה שִׁבְעִ֥ים שָׁנָֽה', 1, 'The angel of Yahweh is using the question form to urgently plead with God to show mercy. If a speaker of your language would not use the question form for that purpose, you could translate this as a statement or as an exclamation. Alternate translation: [Please have compassion on Jerusalem and the cities of Judah with which you have been indignant these 70 years now!]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('qqqe', 'ZEC', 1, 12, '1:12', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'יְרוּשָׁלִַ֔ם וְ⁠אֵ֖ת עָרֵ֣י יְהוּדָ֑ה', 1, 'Here, **Jerusalem and on the cities of Judah** represents the people who live in those places. If it would be helpful in your language, you could use an equivalent expression or plain language. Alternate translation: [on the people of Jerusalem and the people of the cities of Judah]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('kclp', 'ZEC', 1, 13, '1:13', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-abstractnouns', 'דְּבָרִ֖ים נִחֻמִֽים', 1, 'If your language does not use an abstract noun for the idea of **comfort**, you could express the same idea in another way. Alternate translation: [words that comforted him]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('ts6n', 'ZEC', 1, 14, '1:14', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-quotations', 'קְרָ֣א לֵ⁠אמֹ֔ר כֹּ֥ה אָמַ֖ר יְהוָ֣ה צְבָא֑וֹת', 1, 'If it would be clearer in your language, you could translate this so that there is not a quotation within a quotation. Alternate translation: [Proclaim that Yahweh of Armies says this]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('wq0u', 'ZEC', 1, 14, '1:14', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-poetry', 'קִנֵּ֧אתִי & קִנְאָ֥ה גְדוֹלָֽה', 1, 'Yahweh is using a construction in which a verb and its object come from the same root. You may be able to use the same construction in your language to express the meaning here. Alternatively, your language may have another way of saying this. Alternate translation: [I have been very zealous]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('j6qc', 'ZEC', 1, 14, '1:14', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-abstractnouns', 'קִנְאָ֥ה גְדוֹלָֽה', 1, 'If your language does not use an abstract noun for the idea of **jealousy**, you could express the same idea in another way. Alternate translation: [indeed very jealous]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('gpa3', 'ZEC', 1, 15, '1:15', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-abstractnouns', 'לְ⁠רָעָֽה', 1, 'If your language does not use an abstract noun for the idea of **the evil**, you could express the same idea in another way. Alternate translation: [to do what was harmful]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('rzoy', 'ZEC', 1, 15, '1:15', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/grammar-connect-logic-contrast', 'אֲשֶׁ֤ר אֲנִי֙ קָצַ֣פְתִּי מְּעָ֔ט וְ⁠הֵ֖מָּה עָזְר֥וּ לְ⁠רָעָֽה', 1, 'Yahweh uses the word **but** here to indicate a contrast between the limited extent of his anger and the excessive harm the nations inflicted. In your translation, indicate this contrast in a way that is natural in your language. Alternate translation: [for I was angry only a little, yet they made the harm far worse]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('kzc5', 'ZEC', 1, 15, '1:15', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-pronouns', 'אֲנִ֣י קֹצֵ֔ף & אֲנִי֙ קָצַ֣פְתִּי', 1, 'The pronoun **I** is repeated for emphasis in both clauses. You could translate Yahweh’s emphasis with a phrase that conveys strong personal involvement in your language. Alternate translation: [I myself am angry…I myself was angry]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('l7xo', 'ZEC', 1, 15, '1:15', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-poetry', 'וְ⁠קֶ֤צֶף גָּדוֹל֙ אֲנִ֣י קֹצֵ֔ף', 1, 'Yahweh is using a construction in which a verb and its object come from the same root. You may be able to use the same construction in your language to express the meaning here. Alternatively, your language may have another way of saying this. Alternate translation: [And I am very, very angry]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('zppi', 'ZEC', 1, 16, '1:16', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/grammar-connect-logic-result', 'לָ⁠כֵ֞ן', 1, 'The term translated as **Therefore** indicates that what follows is a result of what came before. Use a connector in your language that makes this clear. Alternate translation: [Because of this]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('nthf', 'ZEC', 1, 16, '1:16', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metaphor', 'שַׁ֤בְתִּי לִ⁠ירוּשָׁלִַ֨ם֙ בְּֽ⁠רַחֲמִ֔ים', 1, 'Here Yahweh is speaking as if his renewed favor toward Jerusalem were a physical journey back to the city. Your language may have a comparable expression that you can use in your translation, or you could state the meaning plainly. Alternate translation: [I have again shown favor to Jerusalem with mercy] or [I have once again been gracious to Jerusalem]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('qmxv', 'ZEC', 1, 16, '1:16', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-abstractnouns', 'בְּֽ⁠רַחֲמִ֔ים', 1, 'If your language does not use an abstract noun for the idea of **compassions**, you could express the same idea in another way. Alternate translation: [while acting mercifully to her people]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('txk2', 'ZEC', 1, 16, '1:16', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-activepassive', 'בֵּיתִ⁠י֙ יִבָּ֣נֶה בָּ֔⁠הּ', 1, 'The expression **My house will be built in her** is a passive verbal form. If it would be unnatural to use that form, you could express the idea in active form or in another way that is natural in your language. If you need to say who does the action, the context indicates that it is the people of Jerusalem. Alternate translation: [the people will build my house in her]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('lmp8', 'ZEC', 1, 16, '1:16', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-activepassive', 'וְקָ֥ו יִנָּטֶ֖ה עַל־יְרוּשָׁלִָֽם', 1, 'The expression **a measuring line will be stretched out over Jerusalem** is a passive verbal form. If it would be unnatural to use that form, you could express the idea in active form or in another way that is natural in your language. If you need to say who does the action, the context indicates that it is the builders. Alternate translation: [and the builders will stretch out a measuring line over Jerusalem]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('x0hx', 'ZEC', 1, 16, '1:16', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/translate-unknown', 'וְקָ֥ו', 1, 'A **measuring line** is a kind of rope or cord that builders stretch out to measure distances when constructing or planning a building or city. If your readers would not be familiar with what a measuring line is, you could use the name of a similar thing that your readers would recognize, or you could use a more general term. Alternate translation: [and a measuring rope]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('ptep', 'ZEC', 1, 17, '1:17', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'עָרַ֖⁠י', 1, 'Here, **My cities** represents the people who live in those cities. If it would be helpful in your language, you could use an equivalent expression or plain language. Alternate translation: [The people living in my cities]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('vr1k', 'ZEC', 1, 17, '1:17', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-quotemarks', 'קְרָ֣א לֵ⁠אמֹ֗ר', 1, 'There are three levels of quotation here. The angel of Yahweh is speaking to Zechariah (level 1) and telling him to proclaim a message (level 2), which itself quotes what Yahweh of Armies says (level 3). Use the appropriate punctuation in your language to mark these levels of quotation. Alternatively, you could translate this so that there is not a third-level quotation.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('q1av', 'ZEC', 1, 17, '1:17', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-abstractnouns', 'מִ⁠טּ֑וֹב', 1, 'If your language does not use an abstract noun for the idea of **goodness**, you could express the same idea in another way. Alternate translation: [from good things]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('ia3g', 'ZEC', 1, 18, '1:18', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-newevent', 'וָ⁠אֶשָּׂ֥א אֶת־עֵינַ֖⁠י וָ⁠אֵ֑רֶא', 1, 'Zechariah is using the phrase **And I lifted up my eyes and I saw** to introduce a new event in the story. Use a word, phrase, or other method in your language that is natural for introducing a new event.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('sk90', 'ZEC', 1, 18, '1:18', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-idiom', 'וָ⁠אֶשָּׂ֥א אֶת־עֵינַ֖⁠י', 1, 'Zechariah is using **And I lifted up my eyes** as a common expression of the culture to mean “I looked” or “I directed my attention.” If this phrase does not have that meaning for your readers, you could use a comparable expression from your language that does have that meaning, or you could state the meaning plainly. Alternate translation: [And I looked up] or [And I directed my gaze upward]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('e06j', 'ZEC', 1, 19, '1:19', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'הַ⁠קְּרָנוֹת֙ אֲשֶׁ֣ר זֵר֣וּ אֶת־יְהוּדָ֔ה', 1, 'Here, **the horns** represents the military power of the nations that attacked God’s people. If it would be helpful in your language, you could use an equivalent expression or plain language. Alternate translation: [the powerful nations that scattered the people of Judah]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('i9tz', 'ZEC', 1, 19, '1:19', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'יְהוּדָ֔ה אֶת־יִשְׂרָאֵ֖ל וִ⁠ירוּשָׁלָֽם', 1, 'Here, **Judah, Israel, and Jerusalem** represents the people who lived in those nations and that city. If it would be helpful in your language, you could use an equivalent expression or plain language. Alternate translation: [the people of Judah, the people of Israel, and the people of Jerusalem]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('bbtm', 'ZEC', 1, 21, '1:21', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-pronouns', 'אֵ֥לֶּה & אֵ֣לֶּה הַ⁠קְּרָנ֞וֹת & וַ⁠יָּבֹ֤אוּ אֵ֨לֶּה֙', 1, 'The word **These** is used three times in this verse with two different referents. The first and third **these** refers to the craftsmen. The second **these** refers to the horns, that is, the powerful nations. It may be helpful to clarify this for your readers. Alternate translation: [are these craftsmen … These horns are the nations … And these craftsmen have come]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('mw4a', 'ZEC', 1, 21, '1:21', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/grammar-connect-logic-result', 'וַ⁠יָּבֹ֤אוּ אֵ֨לֶּה֙ לְ⁠הַחֲרִ֣יד אֹתָ֔⁠ם', 1, 'The term translated as **And** here indicates that what follows is the result or purpose of what came before. The craftsmen have come in order to terrify the nations that scattered Judah. Use a connector in your language that makes this clear. Alternate translation: [So these have come to terrify them]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('fthm', 'ZEC', 1, 21, '1:21', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'קַרְנ֣וֹת הַ⁠גּוֹיִ֗ם', 1, 'Here, **the horns of the nations** represents the military power of those nations. If it would be helpful in your language, you could use an equivalent expression or plain language. Alternate translation: [the armies of the nations]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('fpd0', 'ZEC', 1, 21, '1:21', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'אֶ֥רֶץ יְהוּדָ֖ה', 1, 'Here, **the land of Judah** represents the people who live there. If it would be helpful in your language, you could use an equivalent expression or plain language. Alternate translation: [against the people of Judah]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('i8z5', 'ZEC', 1, 21, '1:21', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-idiom', 'כְּ⁠פִי', 1, 'The angel is using **according to the mouth of** as a common expression of the culture to mean “so that.” If this phrase does not have that meaning for your readers, you could use a comparable expression from your language that does have that meaning, or you could state the meaning plainly. Alternate translation: [to the extent that]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('acua', 'ZEC', 1, 21, '1:21', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-idiom', 'אִישׁ֙ לֹא־נָשָׂ֣א רֹאשׁ֔⁠וֹ', 1, 'The angel is using **has not lifted up his head** as a common expression of the culture to mean “no one was able to resist or act with confidence.” If this phrase does not have that meaning for your readers, you could use a comparable expression from your language that does have that meaning, or you could state the meaning plainly. Alternate translation: [no one was able to resist them] or [no one dared to oppose them]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('ke1g', 'ZEC', 1, 21, '1:21', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'הַ⁠נֹּשְׂאִ֥ים קֶ֛רֶן אֶל־אֶ֥רֶץ יְהוּדָ֖ה', 1, 'Here, **lifting up a horn** represents exercising aggressive military power. If it would be helpful in your language, you could use an equivalent expression or plain language. Alternate translation: [the ones using their military power against the land of Judah]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('j9a8', 'ZEC', 2, 0, '2:intro', NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, '# Zechariah 2 General Notes\n\n## Structure and Formatting\n\nThis chapter is introduced in prose with imagery used in the rest of the chapter to portray Zechariah’s third vision about measuring lines given by the Lord.\n\nSome translations prefer to set apart quotations. The ULT and many other English translations set the lines of 2:4–13, which are extended quotations, farther to the right on the page than the rest of the text.\n\n## Religious and Cultural Concepts in This Chapter\n\n### Visions\n\nThis book contains a number of visions given to Zechariah so the images are not ones Zechariah actually saw but were given to him in a vision or dream. It is important for each of these visions to keep their meanings and not be interpreted to mean any specific thing. Please be careful to translate each of the terms in your language.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('jrdm', 'ZEC', 2, 1, '2:1', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-idiom', 'וָ⁠אֶשָּׂ֥א עֵינַ֛⁠י', 1, 'The expression **I lifted up my eyes** was a common expression meaning “I looked up” or “I looked intently.” If this expression does not communicate well in your language, you could use an equivalent expression or state the meaning plainly. Alternate translation: [I looked up]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('bfoo', 'ZEC', 2, 1, '2:1', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-idiom', 'וְ⁠הִנֵּה־אִ֑ישׁ', 1, 'The word **behold** here alerts the reader to pay attention to the surprising information that follows. Your language may have a comparable expression that you could use here. Alternate translation: [and there was a man]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('nzl3', 'ZEC', 2, 1, '2:1', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-possession', 'חֶ֥בֶל מִדָּֽה', 1, 'Zechariah is using the possessive form to describe a **rope** that is used for **measuring**. If it would be helpful in your language, you could express the idea behind the possessive form with an equivalent phrase. Alternate translation: [a string for measuring]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('sc5p', 'ZEC', 2, 1, '2:1', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-newevent', 'וָ⁠אֶשָּׂ֥א עֵינַ֛⁠י וָ⁠אֵ֖רֶא וְ⁠הִנֵּה', 1, 'The phrase **And I lifted up my eyes and saw, and behold** is a way that Zechariah introduces each new vision in his book. Your language may have its own way of introducing a new vision or important event in a narrative.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('pehe', 'ZEC', 2, 3, '2:3', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-idiom', 'וְ⁠הִנֵּ֗ה הַ⁠מַּלְאָ֛ךְ', 1, 'The word **behold** here alerts the reader to pay attention to the surprising information that follows. Your language may have a comparable expression that you could use here. Alternate translation: [and suddenly the angel]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('j41m', 'ZEC', 2, 3, '2:3', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-pronouns', 'לִ⁠קְרָאתֽ⁠וֹ', 1, 'The pronoun **him** refers to the angel who had been speaking with Zechariah, not to the man with the measuring line. If it would be helpful in your language, you could state that more clearly. Alternate translation: [to meet the interpreting angel]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('l0oe', 'ZEC', 2, 4, '2:4', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-pronouns', 'וַ⁠יֹּ֣אמֶר אֵלָ֔⁠ו', 1, 'Here, **he** refers to the second angel, and **him** refers to the angel who had been speaking with Zechariah. If it would be helpful in your language, you could state that more clearly. Alternate translation: [And the second angel said to the first angel]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('n8uj', 'ZEC', 2, 4, '2:4', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-pronouns', 'הַ⁠נַּ֥עַר הַלָּ֖ז', 1, 'The phrase **that young man** likely refers to the man with the measuring line from verse 1. If it would be helpful in your language, you could state that more clearly. Alternate translation: [the young man who was going to measure Jerusalem]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('hf11', 'ZEC', 2, 4, '2:4', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-merism', 'אָדָ֛ם וּ⁠בְהֵמָ֖ה', 1, 'The second angel is referring to all living creatures by naming two broad categories, **man** and **beast**. If it would be helpful in your language, you could use an equivalent expression or plain language. Alternate translation: [people and animals of every kind]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('zddw', 'ZEC', 2, 4, '2:4', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-quotations', 'לֵ⁠אמֹ֑ר', 1, 'The word **saying** introduces a quotation. Use a natural form for introducing a quotation in your language.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('eld8', 'ZEC', 2, 4, '2:4', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metaphor', 'פְּרָזוֹת֙ תֵּשֵׁ֣ב יְרוּשָׁלִַ֔ם', 1, 'The second angel is speaking of **Jerusalem** as if it would be like **open areas** without walls, meaning the city will have so many inhabitants that people will overflow beyond its walls. If this image does not communicate well in your language, you could express the meaning plainly. Alternate translation: [Jerusalem will be like an unwalled city]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('i0st', 'ZEC', 2, 4, '2:4', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-abstractnouns', 'מֵ⁠רֹ֥ב אָדָ֛ם וּ⁠בְהֵמָ֖ה', 1, 'If it would be helpful in your language, you could express the idea behind the abstract noun **multitude** in another way. Alternate translation: [the many people and animals]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('ihuq', 'ZEC', 2, 4, '2:4', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-quotesinquotes', 'רֻ֗ץ דַּבֵּ֛ר אֶל־הַ⁠נַּ֥עַר הַלָּ֖ז לֵ⁠אמֹ֑ר', 1, 'If it would be helpful in your language, you could translate this so that there is not a quotation within a quotation. For example, you could express the inner quotation as an indirect quotation.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('uh4y', 'ZEC', 2, 5, '2:5', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-pronouns', 'וַ⁠אֲנִ֤י אֶֽהְיֶה־לָּ⁠הּ֙', 1, 'Here, the pronoun **I** is repeated for emphasis. Yahweh is emphasizing his personal commitment to protect Jerusalem. If it would be helpful in your language, you could express the emphasis in another way. Alternate translation: [And I, even I, will be for her]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('zgd9', 'ZEC', 2, 5, '2:5', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-abstractnouns', 'נְאֻם־יְהוָ֔ה', 1, 'If it would be helpful in your language, you could express the idea behind the abstract noun **declaration** in another way. Alternate translation: [Yahweh declares]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('wc2m', 'ZEC', 2, 5, '2:5', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metaphor', 'ח֥וֹמַת אֵ֖שׁ סָבִ֑יב', 1, 'Yahweh is speaking of his protection of Jerusalem as if he were **a wall of fire all around** it, meaning he will powerfully protect the city on every side. If this image does not communicate well in your language, you could express the meaning plainly. Alternate translation: [a powerful defense all around]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('i9yg', 'ZEC', 2, 5, '2:5', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-abstractnouns', 'וּ⁠לְ⁠כָב֖וֹד אֶֽהְיֶ֥ה בְ⁠תוֹכָֽ⁠הּ', 1, 'If it would be helpful in your language, you could express the idea behind the abstract noun **glory** in another way. Alternate translation: [to show how glorious I am, I will be in her midst]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('hash', 'ZEC', 2, 5, '2:5', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-pronouns', 'בְ⁠תוֹכָֽ⁠הּ', 1, 'Here, **her** refers to Jerusalem. If it would be helpful in your language, you could state that more clearly. Alternate translation: [in the midst of Jerusalem]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('nsfo', 'ZEC', 2, 6, '2:6', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-exclamations', 'ה֣וֹי ה֗וֹי', 1, 'The exclamation **Woe! Woe!** is repeated for emphasis to express urgency and warning. If your language has its own way of expressing an urgent warning, you could use it here. Alternate translation: [Listen! Listen!]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('nevk', 'ZEC', 2, 6, '2:6', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'מֵ⁠אֶ֥רֶץ צָפ֖וֹן', 1, 'Yahweh is using **the land of the north** to refer to Babylon, since the Babylonians came from the north to invade Judah. If it would be helpful in your language, you could state the meaning plainly. Alternate translation: [from the land of Babylon]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('mbfc', 'ZEC', 2, 6, '2:6', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-abstractnouns', 'נְאֻם־יְהוָ֑ה', 1, 'If it would be helpful in your language, you could express the idea behind the abstract noun **declaration** in another way. Alternate translation: [this is what Yahweh says]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('d2v5', 'ZEC', 2, 6, '2:6', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-simile', 'כְּ⁠אַרְבַּ֞ע רוּח֧וֹת הַ⁠שָּׁמַ֛יִם פֵּרַ֥שְׂתִּי אֶתְ⁠כֶ֖ם', 1, 'Yahweh compares the way he scattered his people to the way **the four winds of the heavens** blow in every direction. If this comparison does not communicate well in your language, you could express the meaning plainly. Alternate translation: [I have scattered you to every part of the earth]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('lsvu', 'ZEC', 2, 7, '2:7', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-exclamations', 'ה֥וֹי צִיּ֖וֹן', 1, 'The exclamation **Woe** expresses an urgent call. If your language has its own way of expressing an urgent call, you could use it here. Alternate translation: [Listen, Zion!]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('dc87', 'ZEC', 2, 7, '2:7', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'צִיּ֖וֹן', 1, 'Here, **Zion** represents the people who live in Jerusalem. Yahweh is calling the exiled people of Jerusalem to escape from Babylon. If it would be helpful in your language, you could state that plainly. Alternate translation: [you people of Zion]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('u50y', 'ZEC', 2, 7, '2:7', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-idiom', 'בַּת־בָּבֶֽל', 1, 'Yahweh is using **the daughter of Babylon** as a common expression to refer to the people of Babylon. If this expression does not communicate well in your language, you could use an equivalent expression or state the meaning plainly. Alternate translation: [the people of Babylon]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('amlu', 'ZEC', 2, 8, '2:8', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-quotations', 'כִּ֣י כֹ֣ה אָמַר֮ יְהוָ֣ה צְבָאוֹת֒', 1, 'The phrase **For thus says Yahweh of Armies** introduces an indirect quotation of what Yahweh says. In your translation, use a natural way of introducing indirect quotations in your language.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('udc2', 'ZEC', 2, 8, '2:8', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-abstractnouns', 'אַחַ֣ר כָּב֔וֹד שְׁלָחַ֕⁠נִי', 1, 'If your language does not use an abstract noun for the idea of **glory**, you could express the same idea in another way. Alternate translation: [in order to glorify himself, he has sent me]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('jllf', 'ZEC', 2, 8, '2:8', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-pronouns', 'שְׁלָחַ֕⁠נִי', 1, 'The pronoun **he** refers to Yahweh, while the pronoun **me** refers to the prophetic speaker. It may be helpful to clarify this for your readers. Alternate translation: [Yahweh has sent me, his prophet]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('ybix', 'ZEC', 2, 8, '2:8', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-idiom', 'הַ⁠נֹּגֵ֣עַ בָּ⁠כֶ֔ם נֹגֵ֖עַ בְּ⁠בָבַ֥ת עֵינֽ⁠וֹ', 1, 'Yahweh is using **the one touching you is touching the apple of his eye** as a common expression of the culture to mean “harming you is harming what is most precious to him.” If this phrase does not have that meaning for your readers, you could use a comparable expression from your language that does have that meaning, or you could state the meaning plainly. Alternate translation: [the one who harms you harms what he treasures most]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('tb52', 'ZEC', 2, 9, '2:9', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-idiom', 'הִנְ⁠נִ֨י מֵנִ֤יף', 1, 'Yahweh is using **behold** as a common expression of the culture to get the attention of his listeners and to emphasize what he is about to say. If this phrase does not have that meaning for your readers, you could use a comparable expression from your language that does have that meaning, or you could state the meaning plainly. Alternate translation: [indeed, I am waving] or [look, I am about to wave]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('ifnx', 'ZEC', 2, 9, '2:9', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'מֵנִ֤יף אֶת־יָדִ⁠י֙ עֲלֵי⁠הֶ֔ם', 1, 'Here, **my hand** represents Yahweh’s power to punish. If it would be helpful in your language, you could use an equivalent expression or state the meaning plainly. Alternate translation: [I am about to strike them with my power]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('tx0a', 'ZEC', 2, 9, '2:9', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-pronouns', 'יְהוָ֥ה צְבָא֖וֹת שְׁלָחָֽ⁠נִי', 1, 'The pronoun **me** refers to the prophetic speaker. This statement is outside Yahweh’s direct speech. It may be helpful to clarify this for your readers. Alternate translation: [Yahweh of Armies has sent me, his prophet]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('pb0b', 'ZEC', 2, 10, '2:10', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-doublet', 'רָנִּ֥י וְ⁠שִׂמְחִ֖י', 1, 'The terms **Sing** and **rejoice** mean similar things. Yahweh is using the two terms together for emphasis. If it would be clearer for your readers, you could express the emphasis with a single phrase. Alternate translation: [Celebrate with great joy]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('ove1', 'ZEC', 2, 10, '2:10', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-idiom', 'בַּת־צִיּ֑וֹן', 1, 'Yahweh is using **daughter of Zion** as a common expression of the culture to refer to the people of Jerusalem. If this phrase does not have that meaning for your readers, you could use a comparable expression from your language that does have that meaning, or you could state the meaning plainly. Alternate translation: [people of Zion]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('b7b1', 'ZEC', 2, 10, '2:10', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-idiom', 'הִנְ⁠נִי־בָ֛א', 1, 'Yahweh is using **behold** as a common expression of the culture to get the attention of his listeners and to emphasize what he is about to say. If this phrase does not have that meaning for your readers, you could use a comparable expression from your language that does have that meaning, or you could state the meaning plainly. Alternate translation: [indeed, I am coming] or [look, I am coming]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('g8nz', 'ZEC', 2, 10, '2:10', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-abstractnouns', 'נְאֻם־יְהוָֽה', 1, 'If your language does not use an abstract noun for the idea of **declaration**, you could express the same idea in another way. Alternate translation: [this is what Yahweh has declared]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('c8xx', 'ZEC', 2, 11, '2:11', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-pronouns', 'וְ⁠יָדַ֕עַתְּ כִּי־יְהוָ֥ה צְבָא֖וֹת שְׁלָחַ֥⁠נִי אֵלָֽיִ⁠ךְ', 1, 'Here the pronoun **you** is singular and refers to the people of Zion, and the pronoun **me** refers to the prophetic speaker. It may be helpful to clarify this for your readers. Alternate translation: [And you, people of Zion, will know that Yahweh of Armies has sent me, his prophet, to you]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('t68o', 'ZEC', 2, 11, '2:11', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-explicit', 'וְ⁠נִלְווּ֩ גוֹיִ֨ם רַבִּ֤ים אֶל־יְהוָה֙', 1, 'By **join themselves to Yahweh**, Zechariah means become worshipers of Yahweh. You could indicate this explicitly in your translation if that would be helpful to your readers. Alternate translation: [And people from many nations will worship Yahweh like the Israelites]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('d9t9', 'ZEC', 2, 12, '2:12', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-abstractnouns', 'אַדְמַ֣ת הַ⁠קֹּ֑דֶשׁ', 1, 'If your language does not use an abstract noun for the idea of **holiness**, you could express the same idea in another way. Alternate translation: [the holy land]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('cc8c', 'ZEC', 2, 12, '2:12', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/translate-unknown', 'וְ⁠נָחַ֨ל & אֶת־יְהוּדָה֙ חֶלְק֔⁠וֹ', 1, 'The word translated as **will inherit** means to take formal, permanent possession of something as one’s rightful property. It does not imply that a previous owner has died. If the word you use for **will inherit** would give your readers that wrong impression, you could use a more general term. Alternate translation: [will claim Judah as his possession]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('lsq9', 'ZEC', 2, 13, '2:13', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-exclamations', 'הַ֥ס', 1, 'Zechariah is using the exclamation **Hush** to express a strong feeling of reverence and awe before Yahweh. There may be an equivalent word or phrase in your language that you can use in your translation to convey this feeling. If not, you could say what Zechariah was feeling. Alternate translation: [Be silent]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('r87f', 'ZEC', 2, 13, '2:13', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'כָּל־בָּשָׂ֖ר', 1, 'Here, **all flesh** represents all living people. If it would be helpful in your language, you could use an equivalent expression or plain language. Alternate translation: [all people]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('b9vm', 'ZEC', 2, 13, '2:13', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'מִ⁠פְּנֵ֣י יְהוָ֑ה', 1, 'Here, **the face of Yahweh** represents the presence of Yahweh. If it would be helpful in your language, you could use an equivalent expression or plain language. Alternate translation: [from the presence of Yahweh]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('pnl3', 'ZEC', 2, 13, '2:13', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metaphor', 'נֵע֖וֹר מִ⁠מְּע֥וֹן קָדְשֽׁ⁠וֹ', 1, 'Here Zechariah is speaking of Yahweh as if he were a person who had been sleeping and has now **been roused** to take action. Your language may have a comparable expression that you can use in your translation, or you could state the meaning plainly. Alternate translation: [he has risen to act from his holy dwelling place]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('apzd', 'ZEC', 2, 13, '2:13', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-activepassive', 'נֵע֖וֹר', 1, 'If it would be more natural in your language, you could state **he has been roused** with an active form. The context indicates that Yahweh himself is the agent of this action. Alternate translation: [he has roused himself]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('uct4', 'ZEC', 2, 13, '2:13', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-abstractnouns', 'מִ⁠מְּע֥וֹן קָדְשֽׁ⁠וֹ', 1, 'If your language does not use an abstract noun for the idea of **holiness**, you could express the same idea in another way. Alternate translation: [from his holy dwelling place]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('wttt', 'ZEC', 3, 0, '3:intro', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '# Zechariah 3 Introduction\n\n## Structure and Formatting\n\nThis chapter presents Zechariah’s fourth night vision: a heavenly courtroom scene in which Joshua the [[rc://*/tw/dict/bible/kt/priest]] stands before the [[rc://*/tw/dict/bible/kt/angel]] of Yahweh while the adversary accuses him (vv.1–5), followed by a prophetic oracle about “the Branch” and the removal of [[rc://*/tw/dict/bible/kt/iniquity]] (vv.6–10).\n\n## Religious and Cultural Concepts in This Chapter\n\n### Clothing as a Symbol of Moral State\n\nFilthy garments represent sin and defilement, while clean garments and a clean turban represent [[rc://*/tw/dict/bible/kt/purify|purification]] and restored priestly authority.\n\n## Translation Issues in This Chapter\n\n### Nested Quotation Structure\n\nVerses 7–10 contain three levels of quotation: the angel of Yahweh quotes Yahweh of Armies, whose speech includes both a conditional promise and a messianic oracle.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('c49v', 'ZEC', 3, 1, '3:1', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-newevent', 'וַ⁠יַּרְאֵ֗⁠נִי', 1, 'Zechariah is using the word translated as **And** to introduce a new event in the story. Use a word, phrase, or other method in your language that is natural for introducing a new event.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('y41l', 'ZEC', 3, 1, '3:1', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-pronouns', 'וַ⁠יַּרְאֵ֗⁠נִי', 1, 'The pronoun **he** could refer to 1) Yahweh. It may be helpful to clarify this for your readers. Alternate translation: [Yahweh made me see], or 2) the angel that was speaking to Zechariah. Alternate translation: [The angel made me see]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('u4y1', 'ZEC', 3, 1, '3:1', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-participants', 'יְהוֹשֻׁ֨עַ֙ & הַ⁠גָּד֔וֹל', 1, 'Zechariah is introducing **Joshua the high priest** as a new participant in the story. Your language may have its own way of introducing new participants that you can use in your translation. Alternate translation: [a man named Joshua who served as the high priest]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('kdg5', 'ZEC', 3, 1, '3:1', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'עֹמֵ֕ד לִ⁠פְנֵ֖י מַלְאַ֣ךְ יְהוָ֑ה', 1, 'Here, **to the face of** represents “in the presence of.” If it would be helpful in your language, you could use an equivalent expression or plain language. Alternate translation: [standing in the presence of the angel of Yahweh]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('xbes', 'ZEC', 3, 1, '3:1', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-participants', 'וְ⁠הַ⁠שָּׂטָ֛ן', 1, 'Zechariah is introducing **the adversary** as a new participant in the story. Your language may have its own way of introducing new participants that you can use in your translation. Alternate translation: [and a being who was an adversary]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('id6k', 'ZEC', 3, 2, '3:2', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-123person', 'יִגְעַ֨ר יְהוָ֤ה בְּ⁠ךָ֙ הַ⁠שָּׂטָ֔ן וְ⁠יִגְעַ֤ר יְהוָה֙ בְּ⁠ךָ֔ הַ⁠בֹּחֵ֖ר בִּ⁠ירֽוּשָׁלִָ֑ם', 1, 'Yahweh is speaking of himself in the third person as **Yahweh**. If it would be helpful in your language, you could translate this in the first person. Alternate translation: [May I, Yahweh, rebuke you, the adversary, and may I, Yahweh who is choosing Jerusalem, rebuke you]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('ysar', 'ZEC', 3, 2, '3:2', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-parallelism', 'יִגְעַ֨ר יְהוָ֤ה בְּ⁠ךָ֙ הַ⁠שָּׂטָ֔ן וְ⁠יִגְעַ֤ר יְהוָה֙ בְּ⁠ךָ֔ הַ⁠בֹּחֵ֖ר בִּ⁠ירֽוּשָׁלִָ֑ם', 1, 'These two phrases **May Yahweh rebuke you, the adversary** and **may Yahweh who is choosing Jerusalem rebuke you** mean basically the same thing. The second emphasizes the meaning of the first by repeating the same idea with different words. If it would be helpful to your readers, you could combine them and express the emphasis in another way. Alternate translation: [Certainly, may Yahweh rebuke you, the adversary]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('d4t2', 'ZEC', 3, 2, '3:2', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metaphor', 'א֖וּד מֻצָּ֥ל מֵ⁠אֵֽשׁ', 1, 'Yahweh is speaking as if Joshua were **a firebrand rescued from the fire**. He means that Joshua has been barely saved from destruction. Your language may have a comparable expression that you can use in your translation, or you could state the meaning plainly. Alternate translation: [one who has been barely saved from destruction]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('o55m', 'ZEC', 3, 2, '3:2', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-activepassive', 'א֖וּד מֻצָּ֥ל מֵ⁠אֵֽשׁ', 1, 'The expression **rescued** is a passive verbal form. If it would be unnatural to use that form, you could express the idea in active form or in another way that is natural in your language. Alternate translation: [a firebrand that God rescued from the fire]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('p2h4', 'ZEC', 3, 2, '3:2', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-imperative3p', 'יִגְעַ֨ר יְהוָ֤ה בְּ⁠ךָ֙ הַ⁠שָּׂטָ֔ן וְ⁠יִגְעַ֤ר יְהוָה֙ בְּ⁠ךָ֔ הַ⁠בֹּחֵ֖ר בִּ⁠ירֽוּשָׁלִָ֑ם', 1, 'Yahweh is expressing what he desires to happen to the adversary. See the discussion in the introduction to this book about this form of speech and follow the decision of your team of how a speaker will express in this context what he wants someone to do. Alternate translation: [I rebuke you, the adversary, and I, Yahweh who is choosing Jerusalem, rebuke you]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('c2rm', 'ZEC', 3, 2, '3:2', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-rquestion', 'הֲ⁠ל֧וֹא זֶ֦ה א֖וּד מֻצָּ֥ל מֵ⁠אֵֽשׁ', 1, 'Yahweh is using the question form to emphasize that Joshua has indeed been rescued from destruction. If a speaker of your language would not use the question form for that purpose, you could translate this as a statement or as an exclamation. Alternate translation: [Surely this is a firebrand rescued from the fire!]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('yrzd', 'ZEC', 3, 3, '3:3', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metaphor', 'הָיָ֥ה לָבֻ֖שׁ בְּגָדִ֣ים צוֹאִ֑ים', 1, 'Zechariah is speaking as if Joshua’s sinfulness were **filthy garments** that he was wearing. Your language may have a comparable expression that you can use in your translation, or you could state the meaning plainly. Alternate translation: [filthy clothes signifying sin and guilt] or [was deeply sinful]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('tt2a', 'ZEC', 3, 3, '3:3', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'וְ⁠עֹמֵ֖ד לִ⁠פְנֵ֥י הַ⁠מַּלְאָֽךְ', 1, 'Here, **to the face of** represents “in the presence of.” If it would be helpful in your language, you could use an equivalent expression or plain language. Alternate translation: [standing in the presence of the angel]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('qglz', 'ZEC', 3, 3, '3:3', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-background', 'וִ⁠יהוֹשֻׁ֕עַ הָיָ֥ה לָבֻ֖שׁ בְּגָדִ֣ים צוֹאִ֑ים וְ⁠עֹמֵ֖ד לִ⁠פְנֵ֥י הַ⁠מַּלְאָֽךְ', 1, 'Zechariah is providing background information to help readers understand what happens next in the story. In your translation, introduce this information in a way that would be natural in your own language and culture.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('ww6m', 'ZEC', 3, 4, '3:4', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-pronouns', 'וַ⁠יַּ֣עַן וַ⁠יֹּ֗אמֶר', 1, 'The pronoun **he** refers to the angel of Yahweh. It may be helpful to clarify this for your readers. Alternate translation: [And the angel of Yahweh answered and said]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('nves', 'ZEC', 3, 4, '3:4', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-pronouns', 'וַ⁠יֹּ֣אמֶר אֵלָ֗י⁠ו', 1, 'The pronoun **he** refers to the angel of Yahweh, and **him** refers to Joshua. It may be helpful to clarify this for your readers. Alternate translation: [And the angel of Yahweh said to Joshua]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('soz2', 'ZEC', 3, 4, '3:4', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'הָ⁠עֹמְדִ֤ים לְ⁠פָנָי⁠ו֙', 1, 'Here, **to the face of** represents “in the presence of.” If it would be helpful in your language, you could use an equivalent expression or plain language. Alternate translation: [those who stood before him]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('yfct', 'ZEC', 3, 4, '3:4', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-quotations', 'לֵ⁠אמֹ֔ר', 1, 'The term **saying** introduces a direct quotation. In your translation, use a natural way of introducing direct quotations in your language. It may not be necessary to represent this term explicitly.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('p0mg', 'ZEC', 3, 4, '3:4', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metaphor', 'הָסִ֛ירוּ הַ⁠בְּגָדִ֥ים הַ⁠צֹּאִ֖ים מֵ⁠עָלָ֑י⁠ו', 1, 'The angel of Yahweh is speaking as if Joshua’s sin were **filthy garments** that could be removed. He means that God is taking away Joshua’s sin. Your language may have a comparable expression that you can use in your translation, or you could state the meaning plainly. Alternate translation: [Take away Joshua’s sin from him]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('n4qn', 'ZEC', 3, 4, '3:4', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metaphor', 'רְאֵ֨ה', 1, 'The angel of Yahweh is using the term **See** as an expression to focus Joshua’s attention on what he is about to say. Your language may have a comparable expression that you can use in your translation, or you could state the meaning plainly. Alternate translation: [Pay attention!]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('s88b', 'ZEC', 3, 4, '3:4', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-abstractnouns', 'עֲוֺנֶ֔⁠ךָ', 1, 'If your language does not use an abstract noun for the idea of **iniquity**, you could express the same idea in another way. Alternate translation: [the wrong things you have done]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('npcr', 'ZEC', 3, 4, '3:4', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metaphor', 'וְ⁠הַלְבֵּ֥שׁ אֹתְ⁠ךָ֖ מַחֲלָצֽוֹת', 1, 'The angel of Yahweh is speaking as if Joshua’s restored condition were **fine clothing** that he could put on. He means that God is restoring Joshua to a state of purity and honor. Your language may have a comparable expression that you can use in your translation, or you could state the meaning plainly. Alternate translation: [and I will restore you to a state of purity and honor]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('k9ti', 'ZEC', 3, 4, '3:4', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metaphor', 'הֶעֱבַ֤רְתִּי מֵ⁠עָלֶ֨י⁠ךָ֙ עֲוֺנֶ֔⁠ךָ', 1, 'The angel of Yahweh is speaking as if Joshua’s iniquity were a physical object that could be **caused to pass away from** him. He means that God has forgiven Joshua’s sin. Your language may have a comparable expression that you can use in your translation, or you could state the meaning plainly. Alternate translation: [I have forgiven your sin] Alternate translation: [I have forgiven your sin]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('ceb6', 'ZEC', 3, 5, '3:5', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-pronouns', 'וָ⁠אֹמַ֕ר', 1, 'The pronoun **I** refers to Zechariah, who is interjecting into the vision. It may be helpful to clarify this for your readers. Alternate translation: [Then I, Zechariah, said]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('ec6s', 'ZEC', 3, 5, '3:5', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/translate-symaction', 'וַ⁠יָּשִׂימוּ֩ הַ⁠צָּנִ֨יף הַ⁠טָּה֜וֹר עַל־רֹאשׁ֗⁠וֹ וַ⁠יַּלְבִּשֻׁ֨⁠הוּ֙ בְּגָדִ֔ים', 1, 'Setting a clean turban on Joshua’s head and clothing him with garments was a symbolic action by which the angels showed that Joshua was being restored to his priestly office. If it would be helpful to your readers, you could explain the significance of this action in the text of your translation or in a footnote. Alternate translation: [they set the clean turban on his head and clothed him with garments, showing that Joshua was being restored to his priestly office]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('s1se', 'ZEC', 3, 5, '3:5', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-background', 'וּ⁠מַלְאַ֥ךְ יְהוָ֖ה עֹמֵֽד', 1, 'Zechariah is providing background information to help readers understand what happens next in the story. In your translation, introduce this information in a way that would be natural in your own language and culture.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('i2kk', 'ZEC', 3, 6, '3:6', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-quotations', 'לֵ⁠אמֹֽר', 1, 'The term **saying** introduces a direct quotation. In your translation, use a natural way of introducing direct quotations in your language. It may not be necessary to represent this term explicitly.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('vrk8', 'ZEC', 3, 7, '3:7', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-quotations', 'כֹּה־אָמַ֞ר יְהוָ֣ה צְבָא֗וֹת', 1, 'The phrase **Thus says Yahweh of Armies** introduces a direct quotation from Yahweh. In your translation, use a natural way of introducing direct quotations in your language. It may not be necessary to represent this phrase in exactly this way.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('j5al', 'ZEC', 3, 7, '3:7', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metaphor', 'תָּדִ֣ין אֶת־בֵּיתִ֔⁠י', 1, 'Yahweh is speaking of the temple of Yahweh as if it were a **house** in which he lived. Your language may have a comparable expression that you can use in your translation, or you could state the meaning plainly. Alternate translation: [will oversee my temple]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('dbez', 'ZEC', 3, 7, '3:7', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metaphor', 'וְ⁠נָתַתִּ֤י לְ⁠ךָ֙ מַהְלְכִ֔ים בֵּ֥ין הָ⁠עֹמְדִ֖ים הָ⁠אֵֽלֶּה', 1, 'Yahweh is speaking as if the privilege of coming into his presence were physical **access** to walk among the angels. Your language may have a comparable expression that you can use in your translation, or you could state the meaning plainly. Alternate translation: [and I will allow you to be near me like these angels who are standing here]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('vj6a', 'ZEC', 3, 7, '3:7', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-abstractnouns', 'וְ⁠נָתַתִּ֤י לְ⁠ךָ֙ מַהְלְכִ֔ים', 1, 'If your language does not use an abstract noun for the idea of **access**, you could express the same idea in another way. Alternate translation: [and I will allow you to be]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('aetr', 'ZEC', 3, 7, '3:7', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-poetry', 'מִשְׁמַרְתִּ֣⁠י תִשְׁמֹ֔ר', 1, 'Yahweh is using a construction in which a verb and its object come from the same root. You may be able to use the same construction in your language to express the meaning here. Alternatively, your language may have another way of saying this.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('k423', 'ZEC', 3, 7, '3:7', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-quotesinquotes', 'כֹּה־אָמַ֞ר יְהוָ֣ה צְבָא֗וֹת אִם־בִּ⁠דְרָכַ֤⁠י תֵּלֵךְ֙', 1, 'If it would be clearer in your language, you could translate this so that there is not a quotation within a quotation. Here the angel is quoting Yahweh of Armies, whose words form a second level of quotation within the angel’s speech. Alternate translation: [Yahweh of Armies has said: “If you will walk in my ways] or [Yahweh of Armies says that if you will walk in his ways]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('c2zd', 'ZEC', 3, 7, '3:7', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metaphor', 'בִּ⁠דְרָכַ֤⁠י תֵּלֵךְ֙', 1, 'Yahweh is speaking as if obeying him were **walking** along a path. Your language may have a comparable expression that you can use in your translation, or you could state the meaning plainly. Alternate translation: [you obey my commands]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('eyuj', 'ZEC', 3, 8, '3:8', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'הַ⁠יֹּשְׁבִ֣ים לְ⁠פָנֶ֔י⁠ךָ', 1, 'Here, **to the face of** represents “in the presence of.” If it would be helpful in your language, you could use an equivalent expression or plain language. Alternate translation: [who are sitting in the presence of you]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('nm06', 'ZEC', 3, 8, '3:8', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/grammar-connect-logic-reason', 'כִּֽי־אַנְשֵׁ֥י מוֹפֵ֖ת הֵ֑מָּה כִּֽי־הִנְ⁠נִ֥י', 1, 'Here, the word **for** introduces the reason why Joshua and his companions should listen. The first **for** explains that they are men of a sign, and the second **for** gives a further reason, that Yahweh is about to bring his servant, the Branch. Use a connector in your language that makes it clear that these are the reasons.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('tz9i', 'ZEC', 3, 8, '3:8', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-idiom', 'אַנְשֵׁ֥י מוֹפֵ֖ת', 1, 'Yahweh is using **men of a sign** as a common expression of the culture to mean “men whose lives serve as signs pointing to future events.” If this phrase does not have that meaning for your readers, you could use a comparable expression from your language that does have that meaning, or you could state the meaning plainly. Alternate translation: [men who are living signs pointing to what is to come]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('nzyk', 'ZEC', 3, 8, '3:8', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-idiom', 'הִנְ⁠נִ֥י מֵבִ֛יא', 1, 'Yahweh is using **behold, I am bringing** as a common expression of the culture to mean “pay attention, because I am about to bring.” If this phrase does not have that meaning for your readers, you could use a comparable expression from your language that does have that meaning, or you could state the meaning plainly. Alternate translation: [look, I am about to bring]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('gmvq', 'ZEC', 3, 8, '3:8', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metaphor', 'צֶֽמַח', 1, 'Yahweh is speaking as if the future messianic king were a **Branch** growing from a family line. Your language may have a comparable expression that you can use in your translation, or you could state the meaning plainly. Alternate translation: [the king who will come from the family line of David]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('c1wz', 'ZEC', 3, 9, '3:9', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metaphor', 'הִנֵּ֣ה הָ⁠אֶ֗בֶן אֲשֶׁ֤ר נָתַ֨תִּי֙', 1, 'Yahweh is using the term **behold** as an expression to focus his listeners’ attention on what he is about to say. Your language may have a comparable expression that you can use in your translation, or you could state the meaning plainly. Alternate translation: [Pay attention to the stone that I have set]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('ryhs', 'ZEC', 3, 9, '3:9', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'לִ⁠פְנֵ֣י יְהוֹשֻׁ֔עַ', 1, 'Here, **to the face of** represents “in front of.” If it would be helpful in your language, you could use an equivalent expression or plain language. Alternate translation: [before Joshua]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('ynoz', 'ZEC', 3, 9, '3:9', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'שִׁבְעָ֣ה עֵינָ֑יִם', 1, 'Here, **seven eyes** represents God’s complete and watchful awareness. If it would be helpful in your language, you could use an equivalent expression or plain language. Alternate translation: [are seven facets that represent God’s complete awareness of everything]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('vk0m', 'ZEC', 3, 9, '3:9', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-quotations', 'נְאֻם֙ יְהוָ֣ה צְבָא֔וֹת', 1, 'The expression **the declaration of Yahweh of Armies** is a prophetic attestation formula that affirms the authority of what is being said. In your translation, use a natural way of representing this kind of affirmation in your language. It may not be necessary to represent this expression in exactly this way.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('amc2', 'ZEC', 3, 9, '3:9', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metaphor', 'וּ⁠מַשְׁתִּ֛י אֶת־עֲוֺ֥ן הָ⁠אָֽרֶץ־הַ⁠הִ֖יא בְּ⁠י֥וֹם אֶחָֽד', 1, 'Yahweh is speaking as if the iniquity of the land were a physical object that he could **remove**. He means that he will forgive the sin of the people. Your language may have a comparable expression that you can use in your translation, or you could state the meaning plainly. Alternate translation: [I will forgive the sin of that land]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('t6pm', 'ZEC', 3, 9, '3:9', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-abstractnouns', 'עֲוֺ֥ן', 1, 'If your language does not use an abstract noun for the idea of **iniquity**, you could express the same idea in another way. See how you translated the similar expression in [3:4](../03/04.md). Alternate translation: [the wrong things that the people have done in]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('u42c', 'ZEC', 3, 9, '3:9', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-poetry', 'מְפַתֵּ֣חַ פִּתֻּחָ֗⁠הּ', 1, 'Yahweh is using a construction in which a verb and its object come from the same root. You may be able to use the same construction in your language to express the meaning here. Alternatively, your language may have another way of saying this.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('a4k7', 'ZEC', 3, 10, '3:10', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-gendernotations', 'אִ֣ישׁ לְ⁠רֵעֵ֑⁠הוּ', 1, 'The masculine term **man** has a generic sense that includes both men and women. If it would be helpful to your readers, you could use language in your translation that is clearly inclusive of both men and women. Alternate translation: [each person to their neighbor]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('wmxe', 'ZEC', 3, 10, '3:10', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metaphor', 'אֶל־תַּ֥חַת גֶּ֖פֶן וְ⁠אֶל־תַּ֥חַת תְּאֵנָֽה', 1, 'Yahweh is speaking as if the peace and prosperity of the future age were sitting **under** a **vine** and **fig tree**. This was a common image representing security and contentment. Your language may have a comparable expression that you can use in your translation, or you could state the meaning plainly. Alternate translation: [to enjoy calm prosperity together]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('hhnv', 'ZEC', 4, 0, '4:intro', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '## Structure and Formatting\n\nZechariah 4 is the fifth of eight night visions. The chapter moves from a prophetic vision (a golden lampstand with seven lamps and two olive trees) to an explanation, then to an oracle declaring that Zerubbabel will complete the temple “not by might and not by power, but by my Spirit,” and concludes with the identification of the two olive trees as those set apart to serve the Lord of all the earth.\n\n## Religious and Cultural Concepts in This Chapter\n\n### Temple Furniture as Symbol\n\nThe lampstand echoes the tabernacle menorah (Exodus 25:31–40). Seven lamps and continuous olive oil flowing through golden pipes symbolized God’s provision for continuous worship and the Spirit’s empowering presence.\n\n### Anointing and Divine Empowering\n\n”Sons of the fresh oil” is an idiom for those set apart for special service. Olive oil consecrated kings and priests; here it represents the Spirit enabling Zerubbabel and his community to complete the rebuilding work.\n\n## Translation Issues in This Chapter\n\n### Quotations\n\nVerses 6–10 contain a series of quotes where it is difficult to discern who is speaking. The ULT suggests:\n- the angel speaks from 6–10\n- the angel quotes Yahweh in the middle of verse 6 and beginning of verse 9\n- the angel prophetically quotes the people’s reaction at the end of verse 7\n- the angel, not Zechariah, is the speaker who received the word of Yahweh in verse 8\n- the “me” at the end of verse 9 refers to the angel, this is probably the most contested point, scholars are divided as to if this is Zechariah, the angel speaking to him, or the Angel of Yahweh (read as Jesus)\nIf there is a translation in your area, you may wish to follow it’s decisions regarding speakers in this section. If not, you may wish to follow the ULT.\n\n### Mountains as Obstacles\n\nVerse 7 calls a “great mountain” to become “a plain,” representing political and practical obstacles dissolving so that Zerubbabel can set the capstone in place.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('kn0c', 'ZEC', 4, 1, '4:1', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-newevent', 'וַ⁠יָּ֕שָׁב הַ⁠מַּלְאָ֖ךְ הַ⁠דֹּבֵ֣ר בִּ֑⁠י וַ⁠יְעִירֵ֕⁠נִי', 1, 'Zechariah is using the word translated as **returned** to introduce a new event in the story. Use a word, phrase, or other method in your language that is natural for introducing a new event.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('qlp3', 'ZEC', 4, 1, '4:1', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-simile', 'כְּ⁠אִ֖ישׁ אֲשֶׁר־יֵע֥וֹר מִ⁠שְּׁנָתֽ⁠וֹ', 1, 'The point of this comparison is that just as a man who is roused from his sleep is awakened suddenly, so the angel is rousing Zechariah to pay attention. If it would be helpful in your language, you could make this point explicitly. Alternate translation: [as when a man is suddenly awakened from sleep]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('q632', 'ZEC', 4, 1, '4:1', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-activepassive', 'אֲשֶׁר־יֵע֥וֹר מִ⁠שְּׁנָתֽ⁠וֹ', 1, 'The expression **is roused from his sleep** is a passive verbal form. If it would be unnatural to use that form, you could express the idea in active form or in another way that is natural in your language. Alternate translation: [who wakes from sleep]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('jrqz', 'ZEC', 4, 2, '4:2', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-possession', 'וְ⁠גֻלָּ֣הּ עַל־רֹאשָׁ֗⁠הּ', 1, 'The angel is using the possessive form to describe a **bowl** that belongs to the lampstand. If a speaker of your language would not use the possessive form for this, you could express this idea in another way. Alternate translation: [and the bowl on top of it]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('a1io', 'ZEC', 4, 2, '4:2', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metaphor', 'וְ⁠הִנֵּ֣ה', 1, 'Zechariah is using the term **behold** to focus his listeners’ attention on what he is about to say. Your language may have a comparable expression that you can use in your translation. Alternate translation: [and amazingly]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('n6ai', 'ZEC', 4, 2, '4:2', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/translate-numbers', 'וְ⁠שִׁבְעָ֤ה נֵרֹתֶ֨י⁠הָ֙ עָלֶ֔י⁠הָ שִׁבְעָ֤ה וְ⁠שִׁבְעָה֙ מֽוּצָק֔וֹת', 1, 'Translate this number according to the conventions of your own language and culture. Alternate translation: [and seven lamps on it, fourteen tubes]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('ighq', 'ZEC', 4, 3, '4:3', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-pronouns', 'עָלֶ֑י⁠הָ', NULL, 'The pronoun **it** refers to the bowl. It may be helpful to clarify this for your readers. Alternate translation: [are beside the bowl]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('ia8g', 'ZEC', 4, 4, '4:4', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-quotations', 'לֵ⁠אמֹ֑ר', 1, 'The term **saying** introduces a direct quotation. In your translation, use a natural way of introducing direct quotations in your language. It may not be necessary to represent this term explicitly.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('rx4d', 'ZEC', 4, 5, '4:5', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-quotations', 'וַ⁠יֹּ֣אמֶר', 1, 'The term **and said** introduces a direct quotation. In your translation, use a natural way of introducing direct quotations in your language. It may not be necessary to represent this term explicitly.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('uima', 'ZEC', 4, 5, '4:5', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-rquestion', 'הֲ⁠ל֥וֹא יָדַ֖עְתָּ מָה־הֵ֣מָּה אֵ֑לֶּה', NULL, 'The angel is using the question form to express that Zechariah should already know what the items mean. If a speaker of your language would not use the question form for that purpose, you could translate this as a statement or as an exclamation. Alternate translation: [You should know what these are.]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('l9to', 'ZEC', 4, 5, '4:5', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-pronouns', 'הֵ֣מָּה אֵ֑לֶּה', NULL, 'The pronoun **these** refers to the lampstand and the two olive trees. It may be helpful to clarify this for your readers. Alternate translation: [the lampstand and olive trees are]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('vpl4', 'ZEC', 4, 6, '4:6', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-possession', 'דְּבַר־יְהוָ֔ה', 1, 'The angel is using the possessive form to describe a **word** that comes from Yahweh. If a speaker of your language would not use the possessive form for this, you could express this idea in another way. Alternate translation: [the word from Yahweh]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('tez9', 'ZEC', 4, 6, '4:6', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-ellipsis', 'לֹ֤א בְ⁠חַ֨יִל֙ וְ⁠לֹ֣א בְ⁠כֹ֔חַ כִּ֣י אִם־בְּ⁠רוּחִ֔⁠י', 1, 'The angel is leaving out some of the words that in many languages a sentence would need in order to be complete. You can supply these words from the context if that would be clearer in your language. Alternate translation: [You will not accomplish this by your own might or power, but my Spirit will accomplish it]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('jq2a', 'ZEC', 4, 6, '4:6', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-quotesinquotes', 'אֵלַ⁠י֙ לֵ⁠אמֹ֔ר זֶ֚ה דְּבַר־יְהוָ֔ה אֶל־זְרֻבָּבֶ֖ל לֵ⁠אמֹ֑ר לֹ֤א', 1, 'If it would be clearer in your language, you could translate this so that there is not a quotation within a quotation. Alternate translation: [to me that this is the message from Yahweh to Zerubbabel: “Not]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('jbwc', 'ZEC', 4, 6, '4:6', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-abstractnouns', 'לֹ֤א בְ⁠חַ֨יִל֙ וְ⁠לֹ֣א בְ⁠כֹ֔חַ', 1, 'If your language does not use abstract nouns for the ideas of **might** and **power,** you could express the same ideas in other ways. Alternate translation: [Not by strength and not by force]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('udtf', 'ZEC', 4, 6, '4:6', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-doublet', 'לֹ֤א בְ⁠חַ֨יִל֙ וְ⁠לֹ֣א בְ⁠כֹ֔חַ', 1, 'The terms **might** and **power** mean similar things. The angel is using the two terms together for emphasis. If it would be clearer for your readers, you could express the emphasis with a single phrase. Alternate translation: [Not by your own strength]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('pfwz', 'ZEC', 4, 7, '4:7', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-pronouns', 'וְ⁠הוֹצִיא֙', 1, 'The pronoun **he** refers to Zerubbabel. It may be helpful to clarify this for your readers. Alternate translation: [And Zerubbabel will bring out]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('da8h', 'ZEC', 4, 7, '4:7', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-exclamations', 'חֵ֥ן חֵ֖ן לָֽ⁠הּ', NULL, 'The angel is using a phrase that expresses a strong feeling, joy. There may be an equivalent word or phrase in your language that you can use in your translation to convey this feeling. If not, you could say what the angel was feeling, or you could say what caused him to feel joyful. Alternate translation: [What joy! Let joy be upon it!]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('y9ga', 'ZEC', 4, 7, '4:7', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-abstractnouns', 'חֵ֥ן חֵ֖ן', 1, 'If your language does not use an abstract noun for the idea of **grace,** you could express the same idea in another way. Alternate translation: [Blessed! Blessed!]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('r25o', 'ZEC', 4, 7, '4:7', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-doublet', 'חֵ֥ן', 1, 'The angel is repeating forms **grace** in order to intensify his expression of the idea that it conveys. If your language can repeat words for intensification, it would be appropriate to do that here in your translation. If not, your language may have another way of expressing the intensification. Alternate translation: [How favored indeed!]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('vfwa', 'ZEC', 4, 7, '4:7', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-synecdoche', 'לָֽ⁠הּ', NULL, 'The pronoun **it** refers to the top stone or the temple. The angel is using the top stone to represent the completed temple. It may be helpful to clarify this for your readers. Alternate translation: [to the top stone] or [to the temple]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('qs31', 'ZEC', 4, 7, '4:7', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-rquestion', 'מִֽי־אַתָּ֧ה הַֽר־הַ⁠גָּד֛וֹל לִ⁠פְנֵ֥י זְרֻבָּבֶ֖ל', 1, 'The angel is using the question form to emphasize that the mountain obstacle will be removed. If a speaker of your language would not use the question form for that purpose, you could translate this as a statement or as an exclamation. Alternate translation: [You are nothing, great mountain, before Zerubbabel]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('ako3', 'ZEC', 4, 7, '4:7', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-quotesinquotes', 'תְּשֻׁא֕וֹת חֵ֥ן חֵ֖ן לָֽ⁠הּ', NULL, 'If it would be clearer in your language, you could translate this so that there is not a quotation within a quotation. Alternate translation: [while people call out blessings on it]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('glle', 'ZEC', 4, 7, '4:7', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metaphor', 'מִֽי־אַתָּ֧ה הַֽר־הַ⁠גָּד֛וֹל לִ⁠פְנֵ֥י זְרֻבָּבֶ֖ל לְ⁠מִישֹׁ֑ר', 1, 'Here the angel is speaking as if the great mountain were a person standing in the way. Your language may have a comparable expression that you can use in your translation, or you could state the meaning plainly. Alternate translation: [What are you, great obstacle, before Zerubbabel? You will no longer block him!]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('ldqt', 'ZEC', 4, 7, '4:7', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-apostrophe', 'מִֽי־אַתָּ֧ה הַֽר־הַ⁠גָּד֛וֹל לִ⁠פְנֵ֥י זְרֻבָּבֶ֖ל לְ⁠מִישֹׁ֑ר', 1, 'The angel is speaking to the great mountain that he knows cannot hear him. He is doing this to communicate to the people listening to him that he feels very strongly about how the obstacles before Zerubbabel will be removed. If it would be helpful in your language, you could translate these words as if the angel were speaking directly to the people about the mountain. Alternate translation: [Now about this great mountain in front of Zerubbabel, it will become a plain.]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('ccxv', 'ZEC', 4, 8, '4:8', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-possession', 'דְבַר־יְהוָ֖ה', 1, 'See how you translated the similar expression in [4:6](../04/06.md). Alternate translation: [the word from Yahweh]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('hhp1', 'ZEC', 4, 8, '4:8', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-quotations', 'לֵ⁠אמֹֽר', 1, 'The term “saying” introduces a direct quotation. In your translation, use a natural way of introducing direct quotations in your language. It may not be necessary to represent this term explicitly.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('mz1u', 'ZEC', 4, 9, '4:9', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'יְדֵ֣י זְרֻבָּבֶ֗ל יִסְּד֛וּ הַ⁠בַּ֥יִת הַ⁠זֶּ֖ה וְ⁠יָדָ֣י⁠ו תְּבַצַּ֑עְנָה', 1, 'Here, **hands** represents the work and effort of a person. If it would be helpful in your language, you could use an equivalent expression or plain language. Alternate translation: [Zerubbabel’s work has founded this house, and his work will complete it.]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('qwbr', 'ZEC', 4, 9, '4:9', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-pronouns', 'וְ⁠יָ֣דַעְתָּ֔', 1, 'The pronoun **you** refers to Zerubbabel. It may be helpful to clarify this for your readers. Alternate translation: [And you, Zerubbabel, will know]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('r1ee', 'ZEC', 4, 9, '4:9', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-yousingular', 'אֲלֵי⁠כֶֽם', 1, 'The word **you** is plural here because Yahweh is addressing the people, so use the plural form in your translation if your language marks that distinction.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('a50t', 'ZEC', 4, 9, '4:9', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-pronouns', 'שְׁלָחַ֥⁠נִי אֲלֵי⁠כֶֽם', 1, 'The pronoun **me** could refer to 1) the angel speaking to Zechariah. It may be helpful to clarify this for your readers. Alternate translation: [has sent his angelic messenger to you] 2) to Zechariah. Alternate translation: [has sent me, Zechariah, to you]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('s4lw', 'ZEC', 4, 10, '4:10', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-possession', 'לְ⁠י֣וֹם קְטַנּוֹת֒', 1, 'Yahweh is using the possessive form to describe a **day** that is characterized by small things. If a speaker of your language would not use the possessive form for this, you could express this idea in another way. Alternate translation: [the day when small things happen]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('hhfv', 'ZEC', 4, 10, '4:10', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-rquestion', 'מִ֣י בַז֮ לְ⁠י֣וֹם קְטַנּוֹת֒', 1, 'Yahweh is using the question form to emphasize that no one should despise small beginnings. If a speaker of your language would not use the question form for that purpose, you could translate this as a statement or as an exclamation. Alternate translation: [no one should despise the day of small things!]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('slwq', 'ZEC', 4, 10, '4:10', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-pronouns', 'וְ⁠שָׂמְח֗וּ וְ⁠רָא֞וּ', 1, 'The pronoun **they** refers to the people. It may be helpful to clarify this for your readers. Alternate translation: [And the people will be glad and will see]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('p47e', 'ZEC', 4, 10, '4:10', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-explicit', 'הָאֶ֧בֶן הַבְּדִ֛יל', 1, 'A **stone of tin** refers to a metal or stone weight tied to a line and hung down from the top of a wall to make sure it is perfectly straight up and down. The common term for this is “plumb line” as in the UST. If your readers would not be familiar with what a plumb line is, you could use the name of a similar thing that your readers would recognize, or you could use a more general term. Alternate translation: [a measuring string] or [a device that proves that the building was constructed properly]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('iegl', 'ZEC', 4, 10, '4:10', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-pronouns', 'שִׁבְעָה־אֵ֑לֶּה', 1, 'The pronoun **These** refers to the seven lamps. It may be helpful to clarify this for your readers. Alternate translation: [These seven lamps]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('fwoa', 'ZEC', 4, 10, '4:10', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'עֵינֵ֣י יְהוָ֔ה', 1, 'Here, **eyes** represents the awareness and watchfulness of a person. If it would be helpful in your language, you could use an equivalent expression or plain language. Alternate translation: [Yahweh’s watchfulness]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('fgom', 'ZEC', 4, 10, '4:10', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-personification', 'הֵ֥מָּה מְשׁוֹטְטִ֖ים בְּ⁠כָל־הָ⁠אָֽרֶץ', 1, 'Yahweh is speaking of the eyes as if they were living things that could roam. If it would be helpful in your language, you could state the meaning plainly. Alternate translation: [they look throughout all the earth]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('y4rs', 'ZEC', 4, 10, '4:10', 'ISSUE:MATCH_FAIL', 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/grammar-connect-logic-result', 'כִּ֣י מִ֣י בַז֮ לְ⁠י֣וֹם קְטַנּוֹת֒ וְ⁠שָׂמְח֗וּ', 1, 'The word translated as **For** indicates that what follows is a reason for what came before. Use a connector in your language that makes it clear that what follows is a reason for what came before. Alternate translation: [Indeed, who would despise the day of small beginnings? It is certain that people will rejoice]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('ywyz', 'ZEC', 4, 11, '4:11', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-quotations', 'וָ⁠אַ֖עַן וָ⁠אֹמַ֣ר אֵלָ֑י⁠ו', 1, 'The term **and said** introduces a direct quotation. In your translation, use a natural way of introducing direct quotations in your language. It may not be necessary to represent this term explicitly.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('umaf', 'ZEC', 4, 12, '4:12', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/translate-ordinal', 'שֵׁנִ֔ית', 1, 'If your language would not represent a number in a form such as “second,” you could represent this number in a form that your language would use. Alternate translation: [again]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('wya7', 'ZEC', 4, 12, '4:12', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-pronouns', 'הַֽ⁠מְרִיקִ֥ים מֵ⁠עֲלֵי⁠הֶ֖ם הַ⁠זָּהָֽב', NULL, 'The pronoun **them** refers to the two olive branches. It may be helpful to clarify this for your readers. Alternate translation: [that are emptying the gold from upon the two branches]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('nyey', 'ZEC', 4, 12, '4:12', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metaphor', 'הַֽ⁠מְרִיקִ֥ים מֵ⁠עֲלֵי⁠הֶ֖ם הַ⁠זָּהָֽב', NULL, 'Here Zechariah is speaking as if the olive oil were gold because of its preciousness and golden color. Your language may have a comparable expression that you can use in your translation, or you could state the meaning plainly. Alternate translation: [emptying the olive oil from upon them]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('ruqk', 'ZEC', 4, 13, '4:13', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-pronouns', 'וַ⁠יֹּ֤אמֶר אֵלַ⁠י֙', 1, 'The pronoun **he** refers to the angel. It may be helpful to clarify this for your readers. Alternate translation: [And the angel said to me]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('vala', 'ZEC', 4, 13, '4:13', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-rquestion', 'הֲ⁠ל֥וֹא יָדַ֖עְתָּ מָה־אֵ֑לֶּה', 1, 'The angel is using the question form to express that Zechariah should already know what the items mean. If a speaker of your language would not use the question form for that purpose, you could translate this as a statement or as an exclamation. See how you translated the similar expression in [4:5](../04/05.md). Alternate translation: [You should know what these are.]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('y2rs', 'ZEC', 4, 14, '4:14', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-possession', 'אֲד֥וֹן כָּל־הָ⁠אָֽרֶץ', NULL, 'The angel is using the possessive form to describe a **Lord** who rules all the earth. If a speaker of your language would not use the possessive form for this, you could express this idea in another way. Alternate translation: [the Lord who rules all the earth]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('w1mw', 'ZEC', 4, 14, '4:14', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-idiom', 'שְׁנֵ֣י בְנֵֽי־הַ⁠יִּצְהָ֑ר', 1, 'The angel is using **sons of the fresh oil** as a common expression of the culture to mean the people who have been anointed to serve. If this phrase does not have that meaning for your readers, you could use a comparable expression from your language that does have that meaning, or you could state the meaning plainly. Alternate translation: [are the two servants who were anointed]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('x1zy', 'ZEC', 5, 0, '5:intro', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '# Zechariah 5 Introduction\n\n## Structure and Formatting\n\nThis chapter presents two [[rc://*/tw/dict/bible/other/vision]]s in which an [[rc://*/tw/dict/bible/kt/angel]] interprets what Zechariah sees. The first vision (verses 1–4) shows a flying [[rc://*/tw/dict/bible/other/scroll]] carrying a divine [[rc://*/tw/dict/bible/kt/curse]] against thieves and false swearers. The second vision (verses 5–11) shows [[rc://*/tw/dict/bible/kt/evil]] personified as a woman sealed inside an ephah and carried away to [[rc://*/tw/dict/bible/names/shinar]].\n\n## Religious and Cultural Concepts in This Chapter\n\n### Personification of Wickedness\n\nThe angel identifies the woman inside the ephah as “the wickedness,” using a human figure to represent the community’s sin. Translators should preserve this identification without reducing it to a mere symbol.\n\n### Ancient Measurements\n\nThe chapter refers to cubits (verse 2) and the ephah (verses 6–10). These measurement units may need explanatory notes for readers unfamiliar with ancient systems.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('h60w', 'ZEC', 5, 1, '5:1', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metaphor', 'וְ⁠הִנֵּ֖ה', 1, 'Zechariah is using the term **behold** to focus his listeners’ attention on what he is about to say. Your language may have a comparable expression that you can use in your translation. Alternate translation: [pay attention]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('kzag', 'ZEC', 5, 1, '5:1', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-idiom', 'וָ⁠אֶשָּׂ֥א עֵינַ֖⁠י', 1, 'Zechariah is using **I lifted up my eyes** as a common expression of the culture to mean “I raised my eyes to look.” If this phrase does not have that meaning for your readers, you could use a comparable expression from your language that does have that meaning, or you could state the meaning plainly. Alternate translation: [I raised my eyes]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('pm6l', 'ZEC', 5, 1, '5:1', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-newevent', 'וָ⁠אָשׁ֕וּב וָ⁠אֶשָּׂ֥א עֵינַ֖⁠י וָֽ⁠אֶרְאֶ֑ה', 1, 'Zechariah is using the phrase translated as **And I returned** to introduce a new event in the story. Use a word, phrase, or other method in your language that is natural for introducing a new event.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('unog', 'ZEC', 5, 2, '5:2', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/translate-bdistance', 'עֶשְׂרִ֣ים בָּֽ⁠אַמָּ֔ה & עֶ֥שֶׂר בָּ⁠אַמָּֽה', 1, 'A **cubit** was a unit of measurement corresponding to the distance between an average person’s elbow and middle fingertip, or about 46 centimeters or 18 inches. If it would be helpful to your readers, you could express the dimensions of the scroll in modern measurements, either in the text or in a footnote. Alternate translation: [9 meters … 4.5 meters]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('u6ln', 'ZEC', 5, 3, '5:3', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-abstractnouns', 'הָֽ⁠אָלָ֔ה', 1, 'If your language does not use an abstract noun for the idea of **curse**, you could express the same idea in another way. Alternate translation: [the words Yahweh spoke against them]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('ydib', 'ZEC', 5, 3, '5:3', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-explicit', 'כָל & כִּ֣י & הַ⁠גֹּנֵ֗ב', 1, 'The implication is that the word **for** introduces the specific content of the curse, explaining what it says about those who steal. You could include this information if that would be helpful to your readers. Alternate translation: [for, as the curse says, everyone who is stealing]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('fg5p', 'ZEC', 5, 3, '5:3', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-idiom', 'פְּנֵ֣י כָל־הָ⁠אָ֑רֶץ', 1, 'The angel is using **the face of all of the earth** as a common expression of the culture to mean “the surface of the whole land.” If this phrase does not have that meaning for your readers, you could use a comparable expression from your language that does have that meaning, or you could state the meaning plainly. Alternate translation: [the surface of the whole land]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('u5hz', 'ZEC', 5, 3, '5:3', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-activepassive', 'נִקָּ֔ה', 1, 'The expression **has been cleared** is a passive verbal form. If it would be unnatural to use that form, you could express the idea in active form or in another way that is natural in your language. Alternate translation: [Yahweh will punish them]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('orwm', 'ZEC', 5, 3, '5:3', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-activepassive', 'נִקָּ֔ה', 1, 'The expression **has been cleared** is a passive verbal form. If it would be unnatural to use that form, you could express the idea in active form or in another way that is natural in your language. Alternate translation: [Yahweh will punish them]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('gwuz', 'ZEC', 5, 3, '5:3', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-genericnoun', 'כָל & הַ⁠גֹּנֵ֗ב', 1, 'The angel is not referring to a specific person **who is stealing**. He means anyone who steals in general. If it would be helpful to your readers, you could use an expression that would be more natural in your language. Alternate translation: [anyone who steals]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('idi8', 'ZEC', 5, 3, '5:3', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-genericnoun', 'וְ⁠כָל־הַ⁠נִּ֨שְׁבָּ֔ע', 1, 'The angel is not referring to a specific person **who is swearing**. He means anyone who swears falsely in general. If it would be helpful to your readers, you could use an expression that would be more natural in your language. Alternate translation: [whoever swears falsely]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('zdoo', 'ZEC', 5, 3, '5:3', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-explicit', 'מִ⁠זֶּה֙', 1, 'The implication is that **from this** and **from this** refer to the two sides of the scroll, one side addressing those who steal and the other side addressing those who swear falsely. You could include this information if that would be helpful to your readers. Alternate translation: [on this side of the scroll … on the other side of the scroll]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('zvhg', 'ZEC', 5, 4, '5:4', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-pronouns', 'וּ⁠בָ֨אָה֙ & וְ⁠לָ֨נֶה֙ & וְ⁠כִלַּ֖תּ⁠וּ', 1, 'The pronoun **it** refers to the curse. It may be helpful to clarify this for your readers. Alternate translation: [the curse will come … the curse will spend the night … the curse will consume the house]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('gnwp', 'ZEC', 5, 4, '5:4', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-pronouns', 'בֵּית֔⁠וֹ', 1, 'The pronoun **his** refers to each person who steals or swears falsely, as mentioned earlier in the verse. It may be helpful to clarify this for your readers. Alternate translation: [the house of the one who sinned]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('h4dk', 'ZEC', 5, 4, '5:4', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-genericnoun', 'הַ⁠גַּנָּ֔ב & הַ⁠נִּשְׁבָּ֥ע בִּ⁠שְׁמִ֖⁠י לַ⁠שָּׁ֑קֶר', 1, 'Yahweh is not referring to a specific **thief** or a specific person **swearing by** his **name to falsehood**. He means any such person in general. If it would be helpful to your readers, you could use an expression that would be more natural in your language. Alternate translation: [people who steal & people who swear falsely by my name]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('rivq', 'ZEC', 5, 4, '5:4', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'בִּ⁠שְׁמִ֖⁠י', 1, 'Here, **my name** represents Yahweh’s person and authority. If it would be helpful in your language, you could use an equivalent expression or plain language. Alternate translation: [by my name and authority]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('xh9d', 'ZEC', 5, 4, '5:4', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-personification', 'וְ⁠כִלַּ֖תּ⁠וּ & עֵצָ֥י⁠ו & אֲבָנָֽי⁠ו', 1, 'Yahweh is speaking of the curse as if it were a living thing that could **consume** a house and **its timbers and its stones**. If it would be helpful in your language, you could state the meaning plainly. Alternate translation: [will destroy it, and its timbers and its stones]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('lp78', 'ZEC', 5, 4, '5:4', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-quotesinquotes', 'הוֹצֵאתִ֗י⁠הָ', 1, 'If it would be clearer in your language, you could translate this so that there is not a quotation within a quotation. Alternate translation: [Yahweh of Armies says that he has brought it out]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('jj34', 'ZEC', 5, 4, '5:4', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-ellipsis', 'עֵצָ֥י⁠ו & אֲבָנָֽי⁠ו', 1, 'Yahweh is leaving out some of the words that in many languages a sentence would need in order to be complete. You can supply these words from the context if that would be clearer in your language. Alternate translation: [and will consume its timbers and its stones]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('cwny', 'ZEC', 5, 4, '5:4', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-quotations', 'נְאֻם֙ יְהוָ֣ה צְבָא֔וֹת', 1, 'The phrase **declaration of Yahweh of Armies** identifies the speaker of the direct quotation. In your translation, use a natural way of indicating the speaker of a direct quotation in your language. It may not be necessary to represent this phrase as an interruption within the quotation.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('yrhf', 'ZEC', 5, 4, '5:4', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-personification', 'וְ⁠לָ֨נֶה֙ בְּ⁠ת֣וֹךְ בֵּית֔⁠וֹ', 1, 'Yahweh is speaking of the curse as if it were a living thing that could **spend the night in the midst of** someone’s **house**. If it would be helpful in your language, you could state the meaning plainly. Alternate translation: [it will remain in his house]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('nr6z', 'ZEC', 5, 4, '5:4', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-abstractnouns', 'לַ⁠שָּׁ֑קֶר', 1, 'If your language does not use an abstract noun for the idea of **falsehood**, you could express the same idea in another way. Alternate translation: [falsely swearing by my name]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('i4ym', 'ZEC', 5, 4, '5:4', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-personification', 'וּ⁠בָ֨אָה֙ אֶל־בֵּ֣ית הַ⁠גַּנָּ֔ב', 1, 'Yahweh is speaking of the curse as if it were a living thing that could **come** to someone’s house. If it would be helpful in your language, you could state the meaning plainly. Alternate translation: [it will reach the thief’s house]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('nof1', 'ZEC', 5, 5, '5:5', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-newevent', 'וַ⁠יֵּצֵ֕א הַ⁠מַּלְאָ֖ךְ הַ⁠דֹּבֵ֣ר בִּ֑⁠י', 1, 'Zechariah is using the word translated as **And** to introduce a new event in the story. Use a word, phrase, or other method in your language that is natural for introducing a new event.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('z1z9', 'ZEC', 5, 5, '5:5', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-idiom', 'שָׂ֣א נָ֤א עֵינֶ֨י⁠ךָ֙ וּ⁠רְאֵ֔ה', 1, 'The angel is using **Lift up now your eyes and see** as a common expression of the culture to mean “look up and pay attention.” If this phrase does not have that meaning for your readers, you could use a comparable expression from your language that does have that meaning, or you could state the meaning plainly. Alternate translation: [Look up now and pay attention to]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('xqzj', 'ZEC', 5, 6, '5:6', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-pronouns', 'עֵינָ֖⁠ם', 1, 'The pronoun **their** refers to the people of the land. It may be helpful to clarify this for your readers. Alternate translation: [the people’s eye]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('i65a', 'ZEC', 5, 6, '5:6', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'עֵינָ֖⁠ם בְּ⁠כָל־הָ⁠אָֽרֶץ', 1, 'Here, **their eye** may represent either their appearance, meaning the ephah represents what the people are doing throughout the land, or their iniquity, since the words for “eye” and “iniquity” are similar in the original language. If it would be helpful in your language, you could use an equivalent expression or plain language. Alternate translation: [what they are doing throughout all the earth]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('rduv', 'ZEC', 5, 6, '5:6', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/translate-alternativereadings', 'עֵינָ֖⁠ם', 1, 'The phrase **their eye** is a translation of the written text in the original language. Some ancient translations, however, read “their iniquity” instead. You may want to follow this alternative reading in your translation. Alternate translation: [their iniquity]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('cbwa', 'ZEC', 5, 6, '5:6', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/translate-bvolume', 'הָֽ⁠אֵיפָה֙', 1, 'An **ephah** was a unit of dry volume equivalent to about 22 liters or nearly two thirds of a bushel. Here it refers to a large measuring container. If it would be helpful to your readers, you could express this in terms of modern measurements, either in the text or in a footnote.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('wd2t', 'ZEC', 5, 7, '5:7', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metaphor', 'וְ⁠הִנֵּ֛ה', 1, 'See how you translated the similar expression in [5:1](../05/01.md).');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('rf4k', 'ZEC', 5, 7, '5:7', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-activepassive', 'נִשֵּׂ֑את', 1, 'The expression **was being lifted up** is a passive verbal form. If it would be unnatural to use that form, you could express the idea in active form or in another way that is natural in your language. Alternate translation: [was lifted up by someone]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('pnve', 'ZEC', 5, 7, '5:7', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-possession', 'כִּכַּ֥ר עֹפֶ֖רֶת', 1, 'Zechariah is using the possessive form to describe a **disk** that is made of **lead**. If a speaker of your language would not use the possessive form for this, you could express this idea in another way. Alternate translation: [a lead disk]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('l11r', 'ZEC', 5, 8, '5:8', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-abstractnouns', 'הָ⁠רִשְׁעָ֔ה', 1, 'If your language does not use an abstract noun for the idea of **wickedness**, you could express the same idea in another way. Alternate translation: [how wicked they are]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('x3vk', 'ZEC', 5, 8, '5:8', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-personification', 'הָ⁠רִשְׁעָ֔ה', 1, 'The angel is speaking of **wickedness** as if it were a living person who could sit inside a container. If it would be helpful in your language, you could state the meaning plainly. Alternate translation: [the wickedness of the people]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('djqn', 'ZEC', 5, 8, '5:8', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-idiom', 'פִּֽי⁠הָ', 1, 'Zechariah is using **its mouth** as a common expression of the culture to mean “its opening.” If this phrase does not have that meaning for your readers, you could use a comparable expression from your language that does have that meaning, or you could state the meaning plainly. Alternate translation: [its opening]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('wz0p', 'ZEC', 5, 8, '5:8', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-possession', 'אֶ֥בֶן הָ⁠עֹפֶ֖רֶת', 1, 'Zechariah is using the possessive form to describe a **stone** that is made of **lead**. If a speaker of your language would not use the possessive form for this, you could express this idea in another way. Alternate translation: [the lead stone]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('lb8q', 'ZEC', 5, 9, '5:9', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-newevent', 'וָ⁠אֶשָּׂ֨א עֵינַ֜⁠י וָ⁠אֵ֗רֶא', 1, 'Zechariah is using the word translated as **And** to introduce a new event in the story. Use a word, phrase, or other method in your language that is natural for introducing a new event.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('lzgf', 'ZEC', 5, 9, '5:9', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/translate-unknown', 'הַ⁠חֲסִידָ֑ה', 1, 'A **stork** is a kind of large bird with long legs, a long beak, and large, powerful wings. If your readers would not be familiar with what a stork is, you could use the name of a similar large bird that your readers would recognize, or you could use a more general term. Alternate translation: [a large bird]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('snbr', 'ZEC', 5, 9, '5:9', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-idiom', 'וָ⁠אֶשָּׂ֨א עֵינַ֜⁠י', 1, 'See how you translated the similar expression in [5:1](../05/01.md).');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('gd7p', 'ZEC', 5, 9, '5:9', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metaphor', 'וְ⁠הִנֵּה֩', 1, 'See how you translated the similar expression in [5:1](../05/01.md).');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('vwuv', 'ZEC', 5, 9, '5:9', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-idiom', 'בֵּ֥ין הָ⁠אָ֖רֶץ וּ⁠בֵ֥ין הַ⁠שָּׁמָֽיִם', 1, 'Zechariah is using **between the earth and between the heavens** as a common expression of the culture to mean “in the air between the ground and the sky.” If this phrase does not have that meaning for your readers, you could use a comparable expression from your language that does have that meaning, or you could state the meaning plainly. Alternate translation: [in the air between the ground and the sky]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('nf5n', 'ZEC', 5, 9, '5:9', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-simile', 'כְנָפַ֖יִם כְּ⁠כַנְפֵ֣י הַ⁠חֲסִידָ֑ה', 1, 'The point of this comparison is that just as **the wings of the stork** are large and powerful, so the wings of these two women are large and powerful. If it would be helpful in your language, you could make this point explicitly. Alternate translation: [wings as large and powerful as those of a stork]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('t6zq', 'ZEC', 5, 11, '5:11', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/grammar-connect-logic-goal', 'וַ⁠יֹּ֣אמֶר אֵלַ֔⁠י לִ⁠בְנֽוֹת־לָ֥⁠הֿ בַ֖יִת בְּ⁠אֶ֣רֶץ שִׁנְעָ֑ר וְ⁠הוּכַ֛ן וְ⁠הֻנִּ֥יחָה שָּׁ֖ם עַל־מְכֻנָתָֽ⁠הּ', 1, 'Here, **To build** marks building a house for the woman in the land of Shinar as the goal or purpose of taking the ephah there. Use a connector in your language that makes it clear that this is the purpose.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('x4t2', 'ZEC', 5, 11, '5:11', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-pronouns', 'לָ֥⁠הֿ', 1, 'The pronoun **her** refers to the woman who represents wickedness. It may be helpful to clarify this for your readers. Alternate translation: [for the woman who represents wickedness]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('qwm6', 'ZEC', 5, 11, '5:11', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-pronouns', 'עַל־מְכֻנָתָֽ⁠הּ', 1, 'The pronoun **her** refers to the ephah, that is, the measuring basket. It may be helpful to clarify this for your readers. Alternate translation: [on the base of the measuring basket]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('t7y2', 'ZEC', 5, 11, '5:11', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/translate-unknown', 'עַל־מְכֻנָתָֽ⁠הּ', 1, 'A **base** is a kind of platform or pedestal on which something is placed for support or display. If your readers would not be familiar with what a base is, you could use the name of a similar thing that your readers would recognize, or you could use a more general term. Alternate translation: [on her stand]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('ze5i', 'ZEC', 5, 11, '5:11', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-activepassive', 'וְ⁠הוּכַ֛ן', 1, 'The expression **it will be established** is a passive verbal form. If it would be unnatural to use that form, you could express the idea in active form or in another way that is natural in your language. Alternate translation: [they will establish it]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('w422', 'ZEC', 5, 11, '5:11', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-activepassive', 'וְ⁠הֻנִּ֥יחָה', 1, 'The expression **she will be set down** is a passive verbal form. If it would be unnatural to use that form, you could express the idea in active form or in another way that is natural in your language. If you need to say who does the action, the context indicates that it is the two women. Alternate translation: [they will set her down]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('z96r', 'ZEC', 6, 0, '6:intro', NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, '# Zechariah 6 General Notes\n\n## Structure and Formatting\n\nThis chapter is written mainly in prose and tells the last vision of the four chariots in the first part of the chapter.\n\nSome translations set each line of poetry farther to the right than the rest of the text to make it easier to read. The ULT does this with the poetic song in 6:12–13.\n\n## Translation Issues in This Chapter\n\n### Meaning of the visions\n\nThe visions are stated and even when the prophet asked for an explanation, their true meaning is often obscure. This uncertainty should remain in your translation. (See: [[rc://*/tw/dict/bible/kt/prophet]])');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('wvi1', 'ZEC', 6, 1, '6:1', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-synecdoche', 'lifted my eyes', 0, 'Here the word “eyes” represents the person who sees. Alternate translation: [looked up]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('zj81', 'ZEC', 6, 1, '6:1', NULL, NULL, 'between two mountains; and the two mountains were made of bronze', 0, 'Since the second phrase describes the mountains in the first phrase, the two phrases may be combined. Alternate translation: [between two bronze mountains]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('tw1y', 'ZEC', 6, 2, '6:2', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-explicit', 'The first chariot had red horses', 0, 'It is implicit that the horses were pulling the chariots. Alternate translation: [The first chariot had red horses pulling it] or “Red horses were pulling the first chariot”');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('j43m', 'ZEC', 6, 5, '6:5', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-symlanguage', 'These are the four winds of heaven', 0, 'The chariots symbolize the four winds of heaven, but they are not literally the four winds. Alternate translation: [These chariots represent the four winds of heaven]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('cai5', 'ZEC', 6, 5, '6:5', NULL, NULL, 'the four winds of heaven', 0, 'This phrase refers to the four directions from which the wind blows: north, east, south, and west. However, some modern versions interpret this Hebrew expression to mean “four spirits.”');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('u5ms', 'ZEC', 6, 5, '6:5', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-idiom', 'standing before the Lord of all the earth', 0, 'The idiom to “stand before” means to be in a person’s presence and to serve him. See how you translated this in [Zechariah 4:14](../04/14.md). Alternate translation: [serving the Lord of all the earth]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('v88q', 'ZEC', 6, 6, '6:6', NULL, NULL, 'the white horses are going out to the west country', 0, 'Some modern versions interpret this Hebrew phrase to mean “the white horses are going out after them,” that is, following the black horses to the north country.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('g5r6', 'ZEC', 6, 6, '6:6', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'the white horses are … the spotted gray horses are', 0, 'Here the horses represent the chariots that they pull. Alternate translation: [the chariot with the white horses is … the chariot with the spotted gray horses is]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('ny4a', 'ZEC', 6, 8, '6:8', NULL, NULL, 'he called out to me', 0, 'Alternate translation: [the angel called out to me]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('n3x1', 'ZEC', 6, 8, '6:8', NULL, NULL, 'Look at the ones', 0, 'Alternate translation: [Look at the black horses]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('fez9', 'ZEC', 6, 10, '6:10', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/translate-names', 'Heldai, Tobijah, and Jedaiah', 0, 'These are the names of men.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('m87p', 'ZEC', 6, 10, '6:10', NULL, NULL, 'this same day', 0, 'Alternate translation: [today]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('f66i', 'ZEC', 6, 11, '6:11', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/translate-names', 'Jehozadak', 0, 'This is the name of a man.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('x4hk', 'ZEC', 6, 11, '6:11', NULL, NULL, 'take the silver and gold, make a crown', 0, 'Alternate translation: [make a crown with the silver and gold]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('wn66', 'ZEC', 6, 12, '6:12', NULL, NULL, 'Speak to him and say', 0, 'Alternate translation: [Speak to Joshua and say]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('ihw2', 'ZEC', 6, 12, '6:12', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metaphor', 'his name is Branch', 0, 'The word “Branch” refers to a messianic figure that would serve as king over Yahweh’s people. Yahweh speaks of this person as if he were a branch that grows out from a tree. Since the word “Branch” is a title, it should be translated with an equivalent word in your language. See how you translated this name in [Zechariah 3:8](../03/08.md).');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('w53q', 'ZEC', 6, 12, '6:12', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metaphor', 'He will grow up where he is', 0, 'The phrase “grow up” refers to the growth of a plant, and so continues the metaphor of this person as a “Branch.” This likely refers to this person appearing or coming into power as the one who would supervise the rebuilding of the temple.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('lm52', 'ZEC', 6, 13, '6:13', NULL, NULL, 'He will be a priest on his throne', 0, 'This could mean: (1) the “Branch” will be both priest and king or (2) the “Branch” will be king, and another person will be a priest who will share the royal power. Alternate translation: [There will be a priest upon his throne]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('ea75', 'ZEC', 6, 14, '6:14', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-activepassive', 'The crown will given', 0, 'If your language does not use the passive form in this way, you can state this in active form or in another way that is natural in your language. Alternate translation: [You will give the crown]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('xn98', 'ZEC', 6, 14, '6:14', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/translate-names', 'Heldai, Tobijah, Jedaiah … Hen', 0, 'These are the names of men. See how you translated these in [Zechariah 6:10](../06/10.md).');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('e6jp', 'ZEC', 6, 15, '6:15', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-explicit', 'those who are far off', 0, 'This refers to the Israelites who remain in Babylon.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('u2bz', 'ZEC', 6, 15, '6:15', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-you', 'so you will know', 0, 'The word “you” is plural and refers to the people of Israel.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('zqz3', 'ZEC', 6, 15, '6:15', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'truly listen to the voice of Yahweh your God', 0, 'Here to “listen” means to obey and the word “voice” represents the words that Yahweh speaks. Alternate translation: [truly obey what Yahweh your God says]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('meb2', 'ZEC', 7, 0, '7:intro', NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, '# Zechariah 7 General Notes\n\n## Structure and Formatting\n\nThis chapter starts about two years after the previous chapter and is written in prose.\n\nSome translations prefer to set apart quotations. The ULT and many other English translations set the lines of 7:4–14, which is an extended quotation, farther to the right on the page than the rest of the text.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('v1rz', 'ZEC', 7, 1, '7:1', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/translate-ordinal', 'on the fourth day', 0, '“on day 4”');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('vut4', 'ZEC', 7, 1, '7:1', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/translate-hebrewmonths', 'Kislev (which was the ninth month)', 0, '“Kislev” is the ninth month of the Hebrew calendar. The fourth day of Kislev is near the end of November on Western calendars.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('sb2z', 'ZEC', 7, 2, '7:2', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/translate-names', 'Sharezer and Regem-Melek', 0, 'These are the names of men.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('y9hy', 'ZEC', 7, 2, '7:2', NULL, NULL, 'beg', 0, 'Here the word “beg” means to plead or ask urgently.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('b1wi', 'ZEC', 7, 2, '7:2', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'before the face of Yahweh', 0, 'Here “face” is a metonym for Yahweh’s presence. Alternate translation: [in the presence of Yahweh]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('kg2p', 'ZEC', 7, 3, '7:3', NULL, NULL, 'They spoke … they said', 0, 'The word “they” refers to Sharezer and Regem Melek.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('i8ej', 'ZEC', 7, 3, '7:3', NULL, NULL, 'by means of a fast', 0, 'Alternate translation: [by fasting]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('wdh2', 'ZEC', 7, 5, '7:5', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/translate-ordinal', 'in the fifth and in the seventh month', 0, '“in months 5 and 7”');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('v5v5', 'ZEC', 7, 5, '7:5', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-ellipsis', 'in the fifth', 0, 'The word “month” can be supplied in translation. Alternate translation: [in the fifth month]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('tfh8', 'ZEC', 7, 5, '7:5', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-explicit', 'in the seventh month', 0, 'The assumed knowledge is that the Jews mourned during a part of the seventh month of the Hebrew calendar because in this month the remaining Jews in Jerusalem fled to Egypt after the murder of Gedaliah, whom the king of Babylon appointed as governor over Judah.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('d7zd', 'ZEC', 7, 5, '7:5', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-explicit', 'for these seventy years', 0, 'The assumed knowledge is that the people of Israel had been slaves in Babylon for 70 years.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('n3dw', 'ZEC', 7, 5, '7:5', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-rquestion', 'were you truly fasting for me?', 0, 'This question is asked to make the people think about what their real reason for fasting had been. If it would be helpful in your language, you could express this question as a statement. Alternate translation: [you were not really fasting for me.]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('p43p', 'ZEC', 7, 6, '7:6', NULL, NULL, 'When you ate and drank', 0, 'This could mean: (1) when they feasted and drank when celebrating religious festivals or (2) when they ate and drank whenever they were not fasting.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('ax5v', 'ZEC', 7, 6, '7:6', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-rquestion', 'did you not eat and drink for yourselves?', 0, 'This question is used to make the people think about whether they were honoring Yahweh when they ate and drank. If it would be helpful in your language, you could express this question as a statement. Alternate translation: [it was for yourselves that you ate and drank.]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('qy27', 'ZEC', 7, 7, '7:7', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-rquestion', 'Were these not the same words … to the west?', 0, 'Yahweh uses a question to scold the people. If it would be helpful in your language, you could express this question as a statement. Alternate translation: [These are the same words … to the west.]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('dqw4', 'ZEC', 7, 7, '7:7', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'by the mouth of the former prophets', 0, 'Here “mouth” is a metonym for the words spoken by the mouth. Alternate translation: [by the words of the former prophets] or “through the former prophets”');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('n812', 'ZEC', 7, 7, '7:7', NULL, NULL, 'you still inhabited Jerusalem', 0, 'Alternate translation: [you still lived in Jerusalem]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('vp7q', 'ZEC', 7, 7, '7:7', NULL, NULL, 'foothills', 0, 'hills at the base of a mountain or mountain range');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('v17g', 'ZEC', 7, 9, '7:9', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-abstractnouns', 'Judge with true justice, covenant faithfulness, and mercy', 0, 'The abstract nouns “justice,” “faithfulness,” and “mercy” can be stated as adjectives. Alternate translation: [When you judge, be just, faithful to the covenant, and merciful]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('k9pm', 'ZEC', 7, 9, '7:9', NULL, NULL, 'Let each man do this', 0, 'The word “this” refers to how a person should judge.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('b2r9', 'ZEC', 7, 10, '7:10', NULL, NULL, 'widow', 0, 'a woman whose husband has died');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('za7v', 'ZEC', 7, 10, '7:10', NULL, NULL, 'orphan', 0, 'a child whose parents have died');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('ht31', 'ZEC', 7, 10, '7:10', NULL, NULL, 'foreigner', 0, 'someone who travels from his own land to a different land');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('jdb5', 'ZEC', 7, 10, '7:10', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'let none of you plot any harm against another in your heart', 0, 'Here “heart” represents the thoughts of a person. Alternate translation: [you must not make plans to do evil]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('l8vz', 'ZEC', 7, 11, '7:11', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metaphor', 'set their shoulders stubbornly', 0, 'This is an image of an ox refusing to allow its owner to put a yoke on its shoulders. This metaphor represents the people being stubborn. Alternate translation: [became stubborn]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('if1l', 'ZEC', 7, 11, '7:11', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metaphor', 'They stopped up their ears so they would not hear', 0, 'This is an image of people putting something into their ears so they would not hear the message from Yahweh. This metaphor represents the people not being willing to hear and obey. Alternate translation: [They refused to listen]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('ieh1', 'ZEC', 7, 12, '7:12', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-simile', 'They made their hearts as hard as rock so they would not hear the law or the words of Yahweh of hosts', 0, 'The people refusing to hear and obey Yahweh are compared to their being as unyielding as rock. Alternate translation: [They stubbornly refused to hear the law or the words of Yahweh of hosts]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('j76s', 'ZEC', 7, 12, '7:12', NULL, NULL, 'in earlier times', 0, 'Alternate translation: [in the past]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('z4q7', 'ZEC', 7, 12, '7:12', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'by the mouth of the prophets', 0, 'Here the “mouth of the prophets” is a metonym for the words that the prophets speak. Alternate translation: [through the words of the prophets]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('hga8', 'ZEC', 7, 14, '7:14', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metaphor', 'I will scatter them with a whirlwind', 0, 'Yahweh speaks of how he will scatter the people as if a whirlwind were scattering everything in its path. Alternate translation: [I will scatter them as a whirlwind scatters things]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('x4q6', 'ZEC', 7, 14, '7:14', NULL, NULL, 'whirlwind', 0, 'a strong wind that spins very quickly as it moves and can cause damage');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('c1xg', 'ZEC', 7, 14, '7:14', NULL, NULL, 'delightful land', 0, 'Alternate translation: [pleasant land] or “fruitful land”');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('uri7', 'ZEC', 8, 0, '8:intro', NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, '# Zechariah 8 General Notes\n\n## Structure and Formatting\n\nThis chapter is a series of sayings from Yahweh of hosts. Each saying is an encouraging note for those returning from the exile to the land of Judah and Jerusalem. (See: [[rc://*/tw/dict/bible/kt/yahwehofhosts]])');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('rx8t', 'ZEC', 8, 2, '8:2', NULL, NULL, 'I am passionate for Zion', 0, 'Alternate translation: [I have a strong desire to protect Zion]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('vc1c', 'ZEC', 8, 2, '8:2', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'for Zion', 0, 'Here “Zion” represents the people of Zion. Alternate translation: [for the people of Zion] or “for the people of Jerusalem”');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('w6qx', 'ZEC', 8, 2, '8:2', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-explicit', 'with great anger', 0, 'The implied information is that this anger is against the enemies of Zion. Alternate translation: [with great anger against her enemies]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('m9ri', 'ZEC', 8, 3, '8:3', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-explicit', 'the mountain of Yahweh of hosts', 0, 'The implied information is that this refers to Mount Zion, the location upon which the city of Jerusalem was built.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('nus3', 'ZEC', 8, 4, '8:4', NULL, NULL, 'be in the streets of Jerusalem', 0, 'Alternate translation: [be living in Jerusalem]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('z297', 'ZEC', 8, 4, '8:4', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-explicit', 'in his hand because he has grown so old', 0, 'People having the opportunity to grow old implies the city will be peaceful and prosperous for a long time.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('y52e', 'ZEC', 8, 5, '8:5', NULL, NULL, 'The streets of the city will be full', 0, 'The public areas of the city will be full of people in their normal activities.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('n3ga', 'ZEC', 8, 6, '8:6', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metaphor', 'If something seems impossible in the eyes of', 0, 'The eyes represent seeing, and seeing represents thoughts or judgment. Alternate translation: [If something does not appear to be possible to]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('d5cx', 'ZEC', 8, 6, '8:6', NULL, NULL, 'the remnant of this people', 0, 'Alternate translation: [the people of Judah who survive]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('c478', 'ZEC', 8, 6, '8:6', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metaphor', 'in my eyes', 0, 'The eyes represent seeing, and seeing represents thoughts or judgment. Alternate translation: [to me]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('f4bz', 'ZEC', 8, 7, '8:7', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-explicit', 'I am about to rescue my people', 0, 'The implied information is that the people are in exile. “I am about to rescue my people of Judah who went into exile”');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('x6hq', 'ZEC', 8, 7, '8:7', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-merism', 'from the land of the sunrise and from the land of the setting sun', 0, 'This is a merism that means from all directions. Alternate translation: [from all lands in every direction]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('bcy7', 'ZEC', 8, 8, '8:8', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-abstractnouns', 'I will be their God in truth and in righteousness', 0, 'This can be rewritten to remove the abstract nouns “truth” and “righteousness.” Alternate translation: [I will be their God. I will be faithful to them and act toward them in a just manner]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('h94j', 'ZEC', 8, 9, '8:9', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-idiom', 'Strengthen your hands', 0, 'This is an idiom that means to be courageous for the work. Alternate translation: [Be strong and courageous]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('h2cs', 'ZEC', 8, 10, '8:10', NULL, NULL, 'For before those days', 0, 'Here “those days” refers to the time the people of Judah started to rebuild the temple.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('gp8k', 'ZEC', 8, 10, '8:10', NULL, NULL, 'no crops were gathered in', 0, 'Alternate translation: [there were no crops to harvest]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('z6fg', 'ZEC', 8, 10, '8:10', NULL, NULL, 'there was no profit for either man or beast', 0, 'It was useless for people and their animals to farm the land, because they got no food from it.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('qe6a', 'ZEC', 8, 10, '8:10', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-merism', 'for anyone going or coming', 0, 'This merism refers to all of life’s activities everywhere that anyone went.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('uh2k', 'ZEC', 8, 10, '8:10', NULL, NULL, 'I had set every person each against his neighbor', 0, 'Alternate translation: [I had turned everyone against each other]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('cg9b', 'ZEC', 8, 11, '8:11', NULL, NULL, 'But now it will not be as in former days, I will be with the remnant of this people', 0, 'Alternate translation: [But I will not treat the remnant of this people now as I did in former days]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('pcv2', 'ZEC', 8, 11, '8:11', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-explicit', 'in former days', 0, '“in the past.” The implied information is that this refers to the time when the people started rebuilding the temple.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('k5pg', 'ZEC', 8, 11, '8:11', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-explicit', 'the remnant of this people', 0, 'The implied information is that this is the remnant of the people who returned from exile. Alternate translation: [the people who returned from exile]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('sdy1', 'ZEC', 8, 12, '8:12', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-activepassive', 'seeds of peace will be sown', 0, 'This can be expressed in active form. Alternate translation: [the people will safely sow seed]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('nk96', 'ZEC', 8, 12, '8:12', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metaphor', 'the earth will give its produce; the skies will give their dew', 0, 'The earth and skies are spoken of as if they were persons giving what is needed.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('gq8d', 'ZEC', 8, 12, '8:12', NULL, NULL, 'inherit all these things', 0, 'Alternate translation: [to have all these things]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('y21m', 'ZEC', 8, 13, '8:13', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-explicit', 'You were an example to the other nations of a curse', 0, 'The implied information is that the way Yahweh had allowed the temple to be destroyed and his people to be exiled had been used by other nations as an example of what it meant to be cursed by Yahweh. Alternate translation: [When I punished you, the other nations learned what happens when I curse a people]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('mk9i', 'ZEC', 8, 13, '8:13', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'house of Judah and house of Israel', 0, 'The word “house” is a metonym for the family that lives in the house. In this case it refers to the people in the kingdoms of Judah and Israel. Alternate translation: [people of Judah and Israel]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('msq7', 'ZEC', 8, 13, '8:13', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-idiom', 'let your hands be strong', 0, 'This is an idiom that means to be courageous for the work. Alternate translation: [be strong and courageous]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('v8du', 'ZEC', 8, 13, '8:13', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'house of Judah and house of Israel', 0, 'The word “house” is a metonym for the family that lives in the house. In this case it refers to the people in the kingdom of Judah. Alternate translation: [people of Judah]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('z32e', 'ZEC', 8, 14, '8:14', NULL, NULL, 'do harm to you', 0, 'Alternate translation: [punish you]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('ry4z', 'ZEC', 8, 14, '8:14', NULL, NULL, 'provoked my anger', 0, 'Alternate translation: [angered me]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('pw4j', 'ZEC', 8, 14, '8:14', NULL, NULL, 'did not relent', 0, 'Alternate translation: [did not decide to punish them less]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('tg1a', 'ZEC', 8, 15, '8:15', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'Jerusalem', 0, 'This is a metonym for the people of Jerusalem. Alternate translation: [the people of Jerusalem]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('r54n', 'ZEC', 8, 16, '8:16', NULL, NULL, 'that you must do', 0, '“You” refers to the people of Judah.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('iy65', 'ZEC', 8, 16, '8:16', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-abstractnouns', 'Speak truth, every person with his neighbor', 0, 'If your language does not use an abstract noun for the idea behind the word **truth**, you can express the same idea with an adjective such as “true.” Alternate translation: [Everyone must say only true things to his neighbor]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('m4ld', 'ZEC', 8, 16, '8:16', NULL, NULL, 'his neighbor', 0, 'Here “neighbor” means any person, not just someone who lives nearby.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('u5kf', 'ZEC', 8, 16, '8:16', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-abstractnouns', 'Judge with truth, justice, and peace in your gates', 0, 'This can be restated to remove the abstract nouns “truth,” “justice,” and “peace.” Alternate translation: [When you are making decisions in your gates, judge in a way that is true and just and causes people to live peacefully with each other]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('k4ez', 'ZEC', 8, 16, '8:16', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-explicit', 'in your gates', 0, 'The assumed knowledge is that this refers to the places where judgment took place. Alternate translation: [in your places of judgment]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('uuz1', 'ZEC', 8, 18, '8:18', NULL, NULL, 'came to me', 0, 'Here “me” refers to Zechariah.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('hr3x', 'ZEC', 8, 19, '8:19', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/translate-ordinal', 'The fasts of the fourth month, the fifth month, the seventh month, and the tenth month', 0, '“The fasts of months 4, 5, 7, and 10”');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('x9kp', 'ZEC', 8, 19, '8:19', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-explicit', 'The fasts of the fourth month', 0, 'The assumed knowledge is that the Jews mourned during a part of the fourth month of the Hebrew calendar because this is when the Babylonians broke through the walls of Jerusalem.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('je6q', 'ZEC', 8, 19, '8:19', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-explicit', 'the fifth month', 0, 'The assumed knowledge is that the Jewish people fasted during a part of the fifth month of the Hebrew calendar because this is when the Babylonians destroyed the temple in Jerusalem.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('h4zn', 'ZEC', 8, 19, '8:19', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-explicit', 'the seventh month', 0, 'The assumed knowledge is that the Jews mourned during a part of the seventh month of the Hebrew calendar because in this month the remaining Jews in Jerusalem fled to Egypt after the murder of Gedaliah, whom the king of Babylon appointed as governor over Judah.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('qk5a', 'ZEC', 8, 19, '8:19', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-explicit', 'the tenth month', 0, 'The assumed knowledge is that the Jews mourned during a part of the tenth month of the Hebrew calendar because this is when the Babylonians began their siege against Jerusalem. The tenth month is during the last part of December and the first part of January on Western calendars. (See also: [[rc://*/ta/man/translate/translate-hebrewmonths]])');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('v6ls', 'ZEC', 8, 19, '8:19', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-abstractnouns', 'times of joy, gladness, and happy festivals', 0, 'The abstract nouns “joy” and “gladness” can be translated using adjectives. Alternate translation: [joyful and glad times, with happy festivals]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('vyd5', 'ZEC', 8, 19, '8:19', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'the house of Judah', 0, 'The word “house” is a metonym for the family that lives in the house. In this case it refers to the people in the kingdom of Judah, which included the descendants of Judah and Benjamin. Alternate translation: [the people of Judah]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('c9gv', 'ZEC', 8, 19, '8:19', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-abstractnouns', 'love truth and peace', 0, 'The abstract nouns “truth” and “peace” can be translated using adjectives. Alternate translation: [love what is truthful and peaceful]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('r5qf', 'ZEC', 8, 20, '8:20', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-explicit', 'People will come again', 0, 'The implied information is that Jerusalem is where the people will come. Alternate translation: [People will come again to Jerusalem]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('rvs3', 'ZEC', 8, 21, '8:21', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'will go to another city', 0, 'This is a metonym for the people in the other city. Alternate translation: [will go to the people of another city]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('b98a', 'ZEC', 8, 21, '8:21', NULL, NULL, 'beg', 0, 'Here the word “beg” means to plead or ask urgently.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('k69q', 'ZEC', 8, 21, '8:21', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'before the face of Yahweh', 0, 'Here “face” is a metonym for Yahweh’s presence. See how you translated this in [Zechariah 7:2](../07/02.md). Alternate translation: [in the presence of Yahweh]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('szh9', 'ZEC', 8, 21, '8:21', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metaphor', 'seek Yahweh of hosts', 0, 'Those who want to know Yahweh and please him are spoken of as if they are literally seeking to find Yahweh.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('nz8j', 'ZEC', 8, 22, '8:22', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'mighty nations', 0, 'This is a metonym for the people in the mighty nations. Alternate translation: [people of mighty nations]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('vw6j', 'ZEC', 8, 23, '8:23', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-explicit', 'will grasp the hem of your robe', 0, 'The implied information is that the foreigners will grab their robe to get their attention. Alternate translation: [will grasp the hem of your robe to get your attention]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('ed1e', 'ZEC', 8, 23, '8:23', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-explicit', 'Let us go with you', 0, 'The implied information is that people of God are going to Jerusalem. Alternate translation: [Let us go to Jerusalem with you]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('wc2l', 'ZEC', 8, 23, '8:23', NULL, NULL, 'God is with you', 0, 'Alternate translation: [God is with you people]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('lyp2', 'ZEC', 9, 0, '9:intro', NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, '# Zechariah 9 General Notes\n\n## Structure and Formatting\n\nThis chapter is written mainly in prose about the cities and peoples around where Israel stood as a country until the exile.\n\nSome translations set each line of poetry farther to the right than the rest of the text to make it easier to read. The ULT does this with the poetic song in 9:9–10.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('gn78', 'ZEC', 9, 1, '9:1', NULL, NULL, 'This is a declaration of Yahweh’s word concerning', 0, 'Alternate translation: [This is Yahweh’s message about]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('fjj8', 'ZEC', 9, 1, '9:1', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'the land of Hadrak and Damascus', 0, 'Here “Hadrach” and “Damascus” refer to the people who live in those places. Alternate translation: [the people of the land of Hadrach and the city Damascus]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('xk5a', 'ZEC', 9, 1, '9:1', NULL, NULL, 'Hadrak', 0, 'The location of Hadrach is unknown today.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('q7lh', 'ZEC', 9, 1, '9:1', NULL, NULL, 'its resting place', 0, 'Alternate translation: [the resting place of the people of Hadrach]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('fi2z', 'ZEC', 9, 1, '9:1', NULL, NULL, 'for the eyes of all humanity and all the tribes of Israel are toward Yahweh', 0, 'Some versions translate this as “for Yahweh’s eye is on all mankind and on the tribes of Israel.”');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('b62m', 'ZEC', 9, 1, '9:1', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'the eyes of all humanity and all the tribes of Israel are toward Yahweh', 0, 'Here “eyes” refers to what they look at. Alternate translation: [all humanity and all the tribes of Israel look toward Yahweh]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('dbk5', 'ZEC', 9, 2, '9:2', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'Hamath', 0, 'This refers to the people who live in that land. Alternate translation: [the people of the land of Hamath]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('x51x', 'ZEC', 9, 2, '9:2', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'Tyre and Sidon', 0, 'This refers to the people who live in those cities. Alternate translation: [the people of Tyre and Sidon]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('z6mi', 'ZEC', 9, 2, '9:2', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-irony', 'for they are very wise', 0, 'This could mean: (1) the people are wise for looking at Yahweh for help or (2) Zechariah did not really mean that the people of Hamath were wise and was using irony. Alternate translation: [though they think they are very wise]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('vi9s', 'ZEC', 9, 3, '9:3', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-personification', 'built herself a stronghold', 0, 'Here the city of Tyre is pictured as a woman. Alternate translation: [built a strong fortress] or “built a high wall”');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('p2xv', 'ZEC', 9, 3, '9:3', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-hyperbole', 'heaped up silver like dust and refined gold like mud in the streets', 0, 'Yahweh exaggerates to emphasize how rich Tyre was. Alternate translation: [accumulated silver and gold as much as soil in the streets]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('ps4e', 'ZEC', 9, 4, '9:4', NULL, NULL, 'Look! The Lord will dispossess her', 0, 'Here “Look!” tells the reader to pay attention to the important statement that follows. Alternate translation: [Pay attention! The Lord will take away Tyre’s possessions]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('nf2a', 'ZEC', 9, 4, '9:4', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'destroy her strength on the sea', 0, 'Tyre’s “strength on the sea” refers to the ships that were used for commerce and conquest. Alternate translation: [destroy Tyre’s ships in which men fight on the sea]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('rk76', 'ZEC', 9, 4, '9:4', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-activepassive', 'so she will be devoured by fire', 0, 'If your language does not use the passive form in this way, you can state this in active form or in another way that is natural in your language. Alternate translation: [and enemies will burn the city to the ground]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('zx4k', 'ZEC', 9, 5, '9:5', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'Ashkelon … Gaza … Ekron, her hopes', 0, 'These cities each refer to the people who live in them. Alternate translation: [The people of Ashkelon … the people of Gaza … the hopes of the people of Ekron]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('ae33', 'ZEC', 9, 5, '9:5', NULL, NULL, 'will see', 0, 'Alternate translation: [will see Tyre be destroyed]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('fmu2', 'ZEC', 9, 6, '9:6', NULL, NULL, 'Strangers will make their homes in Ashdod', 0, 'Alternate translation: [Foreigners will take over Ashdod and live there]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('r481', 'ZEC', 9, 6, '9:6', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-idiom', 'I will cut off the pride of the Philistines', 0, 'Here “cut off” is an idiom that means to stop their pride. Alternate translation: [I will make the Philistines to be proud of themselves no longer]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('efh7', 'ZEC', 9, 7, '9:7', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'I will remove their blood from their mouths and their abominations from between their teeth', 0, 'Here “blood” is a metonym for meat with blood in it, and “abominations” is a metonym for meat offered to idols. Alternate translation: [I will no longer allow them to eat meat that still has blood in it, and I will forbid them to eat food that they offered to idols]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('l2f6', 'ZEC', 9, 8, '9:8', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metaphor', 'I will camp around my land', 0, 'God is speaking about himself as if he were an army that was protecting his land. Alternate translation: [I will protect my land]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('lp3e', 'ZEC', 9, 8, '9:8', NULL, NULL, 'for now', 0, 'Alternate translation: [For at that time]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('gnt8', 'ZEC', 9, 8, '9:8', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'I see with my own eyes', 0, 'Here “my own eyes” represent Yahweh’s personal attention. Alternate translation: [I will personally watch over my land]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('iqk3', 'ZEC', 9, 9, '9:9', NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, '# General Information:\n\nYahweh appears to be the speaker in verses 9–13.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('u6p1', 'ZEC', 9, 9, '9:9', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-parallelism', 'Shout with great joy, daughter of Zion! Shout with happiness, daughter of Jerusalem!', 0, 'These two sentences mean the same thing and intensify the command to rejoice.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('apz5', 'ZEC', 9, 9, '9:9', NULL, NULL, 'daughter of Zion … daughter of Jerusalem', 0, '“Zion” is the same as “Jerusalem.” The prophet speaks of the city as if it is a daughter. See how you translated “daughter of Zion” in [Zechariah 2:10](../02/10.md).');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('sey9', 'ZEC', 9, 9, '9:9', NULL, NULL, 'Behold!', 0, 'This alerts the reader to pay special attention to the surprising statement that follows. Alternate translation: [Pay attention!] or “Here is a surprising fact!”');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('ke7v', 'ZEC', 9, 9, '9:9', NULL, NULL, 'Your king is coming to you with righteousness and is rescuing you', 0, 'Alternate translation: [Your king is righteous and is coming to rescue you]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('kjw8', 'ZEC', 9, 9, '9:9', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-doublet', 'on a donkey, on the colt of a donkey', 0, 'These two phrases mean basically the same thing and refer to one animal. The second phrase clarifies that this is a young donkey. Alternate translation: [on a young donkey]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('ca4d', 'ZEC', 9, 10, '9:10', NULL, NULL, 'cut off the chariot from Ephraim', 0, 'Here “cut off” is an idiom that means to destroy. Alternate translation: [destroy the chariots in Israel that are used for battle]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('f5sv', 'ZEC', 9, 10, '9:10', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-explicit', 'the horse from Jerusalem', 0, 'The references to “chariot” and “bow” means that this refers to horses used in battle. This can be made explicit. Alternate translation: [the warhorses in Jerusalem]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('n8py', 'ZEC', 9, 10, '9:10', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-synecdoche', 'the bow will be cut off from battle', 0, 'Here the bow represents all weapons used in warfare. Alternate translation: [all weapons of war will be destroyed]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('xh6q', 'ZEC', 9, 10, '9:10', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'for he will speak peace to the nations', 0, 'Here the action of announcing peace represents the action of making peace. Alternate translation: [for your king will bring peace to the nations]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('m1ef', 'ZEC', 9, 10, '9:10', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-doublet', 'his dominion will be from sea to sea, and from the River to the ends of the earth!', 0, 'The phrases “sea to sea” and “from the River to the ends of the earth” mean the same thing and can be combined. Alternate translation: [his kingdom will be over all the earth!]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('rij4', 'ZEC', 9, 10, '9:10', NULL, NULL, 'the River', 0, 'This probably refers to the Euphrates River.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('w1wr', 'ZEC', 9, 11, '9:11', NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, '# General Information:\n\nYahweh appears to be the speaker in verses 9–13.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('tj3z', 'ZEC', 9, 11, '9:11', NULL, NULL, 'As for you', 0, 'Here “you” is singular, and continues to refer to the city of Jerusalem, also called “Zion.”');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('n83k', 'ZEC', 9, 11, '9:11', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metaphor', 'the pit where there is no water', 0, 'This dry pit represents the exile in Babylon.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('g5c5', 'ZEC', 9, 12, '9:12', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metaphor', 'Return to the stronghold', 0, 'Jerusalem is spoken of as a place of safety. Alternate translation: [Come back to your nation where you will be safe]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('v54r', 'ZEC', 9, 12, '9:12', NULL, NULL, 'prisoners of hope', 0, 'This expression refers to the Israelites in exile who were still trusting in God to rescue them. Alternate translation: [prisoners who still hope in Yahweh]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('xt6s', 'ZEC', 9, 12, '9:12', NULL, NULL, 'return double to you', 0, 'Alternate translation: [return to you twice as much as was taken from you]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('sjg3', 'ZEC', 9, 13, '9:13', NULL, NULL, 'Zion', 0, 'This refers to the city of Jerusalem, also called “Zion.”');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('mwe7', 'ZEC', 9, 13, '9:13', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metaphor', 'I have bent Judah as my bow', 0, 'The people of Judah are referred to as if they were a bow carried by God into battle. Alternate translation: [I will cause the people of Judah to be like my bow]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('ki73', 'ZEC', 9, 13, '9:13', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metaphor', 'filled my quiver with Ephraim', 0, 'Yahweh speaks of the people of Israel, the northern kingdom, as if they were arrows that he would shoot at his enemies. A quiver is a bag that holds a soldier’s arrows.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('es7k', 'ZEC', 9, 13, '9:13', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'I have roused your sons, Zion, against your sons, Greece', 0, 'God is speaking to the people of two different nations at the same time.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('h8w9', 'ZEC', 9, 14, '9:14', NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, '# General Information:\n\nIn verses 14–16, Zechariah describes how Yahweh will rescue Israel from their enemies.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('ms12', 'ZEC', 9, 14, '9:14', NULL, NULL, 'will appear to them', 0, 'The word “them” refers to God’s people. Alternate translation: [will be seen in the sky by his people] or “will come to his people”');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('j3mb', 'ZEC', 9, 14, '9:14', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-simile', 'his arrows will shoot out like lightning!', 0, 'The Israelites sometimes thought of lightning bolts as arrows that God shot.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('qh4y', 'ZEC', 9, 14, '9:14', NULL, NULL, 'blow the trumpet', 0, 'The trumpets were rams’ horns. People blew into them to give signals in battle and on other occasions. Here the trumpet is blown as a military signal.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('cdu9', 'ZEC', 9, 14, '9:14', NULL, NULL, 'will advance with the storms from Teman', 0, 'Team was located to the south of Judah. The Israelites sometimes thought of God as traveling on violent storms coming from the south. Alternate translation: [will march from Teman with the storm winds]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('rq95', 'ZEC', 9, 15, '9:15', NULL, NULL, 'they will devour them', 0, 'Alternate translation: [the people of Judah will devour their enemies]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('l59u', 'ZEC', 9, 15, '9:15', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metaphor', 'will devour', 0, 'To completely defeat enemies is spoken of as devouring them as a wild animal eats its prey. Alternate translation: [will completely defeat]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('fq6x', 'ZEC', 9, 15, '9:15', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'defeat the stones of the slings', 0, 'Slings to throw stones were a common weapon in the days of Zechariah. Here the “stones of the slings” represent the soldiers who were using them to attack Israel. Alternate translation: [defeat the enemies who attack them with slings and stones]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('ure5', 'ZEC', 9, 15, '9:15', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-simile', 'Then they will drink and shout like men drunk on wine', 0, 'The people of Judah will shout and celebrate their victory over their enemies as if they were noisy drunks. Alternate translation: [Then they will shout and celebrate their victory as loudly as if they were drunk]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('t8ng', 'ZEC', 9, 15, '9:15', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-simile', 'they will be filled with wine like bowls', 0, 'This probably refers to the bowls that the priests used to carry animal’s blood to the altar. Alternate translation: [they will be as full of wine as the basins with which priests carry blood to the altar]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('h8j2', 'ZEC', 9, 15, '9:15', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-simile', 'like the corners of the altar', 0, 'Altars had projecting corners that were drenched in animal blood. Alternate translation: [they will be drenched as the corners of the altar are covered in blood]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('i4qw', 'ZEC', 9, 16, '9:16', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-simile', 'God will rescue them … as the flock of his people', 0, 'The people of Israel are spoken of as if they are God’s sheep that he cares for and protects.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('kyv5', 'ZEC', 9, 16, '9:16', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metaphor', 'They are the jewels of a crown', 0, 'The people of Israel are spoken of as if they were the expensive jewels in the crown of a king that show how glorious he is. Alternate translation: [They will be like beautiful stones in a crown]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('udt9', 'ZEC', 9, 17, '9:17', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-exclamations', 'How good and how beautiful they will be!', 0, 'This is an exclamation, and not a question. Alternate translation: [They will be very good and beautiful!]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('rzm2', 'ZEC', 9, 17, '9:17', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-parallelism', 'The young men will flourish on grain and the virgins on sweet wine!', 0, 'This sentence uses a parallel structure to express that everyone will have plenty to eat and drink. If your readers might think that only the men ate and only the women drank, you may want to adjust the wording. Alternate translation: [All of the people, both men and women, will have plenty of grain to eat and sweet wine to drink!]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('uf1p', 'ZEC', 9, 17, '9:17', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-parallelism', 'The young men … the virgins', 0, 'These two phrases are parallel.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('x8zq', 'ZEC', 9, 17, '9:17', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-parallelism', 'grain … sweet wine', 0, 'These two phrases are parallel.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('jmh9', 'ZEC', 10, 0, '10:intro', NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, '# Zechariah 10 General Notes\n\n## Structure and Formatting\n\nThis chapter is written mainly in prose but still uses figurative language as the writer shares a message of redemption and hope for the exiles. (See: [[rc://*/tw/dict/bible/kt/redeem]])\n\nSome translations set each line of poetry farther to the right than the rest of the text to make it easier to read. The ULT does this with the poetic song in 10:1–2.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('ybt5', 'ZEC', 10, 1, '10:1', NULL, NULL, 'vegetation in the field', 0, 'Alternate translation: [causes plants to grow in the field]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('tc8c', 'ZEC', 10, 2, '10:2', NULL, NULL, 'diviners envision a lie', 0, 'Alternate translation: [diviners see false visions]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('e8gu', 'ZEC', 10, 2, '10:2', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-explicit', 'they tell deceitful dreams', 0, 'It is implied that they know these dreams are false. This can be made explicit. Alternate translation: [diviners lie about their dreams in order to deceive people]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('xi1f', 'ZEC', 10, 2, '10:2', NULL, NULL, 'empty comfort', 0, 'This refers to words that sooth temporarily, but do not provide any long-term help.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('nb46', 'ZEC', 10, 2, '10:2', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-simile', 'they wander like sheep', 0, 'The people who do not have true prophets who tell the truth are spoken of as sheep who do not have a shepherd to tell them where to go. Alternate translation: [the people who listen to the false prophets are like sheep who do not know which way to go]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('zr2e', 'ZEC', 10, 2, '10:2', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-simile', 'they … suffer because there is no shepherd', 0, 'The people who do not have true prophets are spoken of as sheep who suffer because they do not have a shepherd to tell them where to go. Alternate translation: [the people who listen to the false prophets … are suffering like sheep who do not have a shepherd to guide them]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('iq7u', 'ZEC', 10, 3, '10:3', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metaphor', 'My wrath burns against the shepherds', 0, 'Here “the shepherds” represent the leaders of God’s people. The intensity of Yahweh’s anger is spoken of as if it was a blazing fire. Alternate translation: [My anger toward the shepherds of my people is as intense as a fire] or “I am very angry with the leaders of my people”');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('ir6n', 'ZEC', 10, 3, '10:3', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metaphor', 'it is the male goats—the leaders—that I will punish', 0, 'Male goats are typically more dominant than female goats. Here “male goats” represents the oppressive leaders of God’s people.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('r33n', 'ZEC', 10, 3, '10:3', NULL, NULL, 'Yahweh of hosts will also attend to his flock, the house of Judah', 0, 'Here Yahweh’s care for his people is spoken of as a shepherd cares for his sheep. Alternate translation: [Yahweh of hosts will take care of the house of Judah as a shepherd cares for his sheep]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('t1tc', 'ZEC', 10, 3, '10:3', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'the house of Judah', 0, 'The word “house” is a metonym for the family that lives in the house. In this case it refers to the people of Judah, which included the descendants of Judah and Benjamin. Alternate translation: [Judah] or “the people of Judah”');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('dd5g', 'ZEC', 10, 3, '10:3', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metaphor', 'make them like his warhorse in battle', 0, 'Yahweh changes the metaphor for his people from defenseless sheep to a mighty war horse. Alternate translation: [will cause them to be strong like war horses in battle]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('se8u', 'ZEC', 10, 4, '10:4', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metaphor', 'From Judah will come the cornerstone', 0, '“The cornerstone will come from Judah.” The most important ruler is spoken of as if he where the main foundation stone of a building. Alternate translation: [One of the descendants of Judah will become the most important ruler]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('xep2', 'ZEC', 10, 4, '10:4', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-symlanguage', 'the cornerstone … the tent peg … the war bow', 0, 'This could mean: (1) they may be symbolic language that refers to the Messiah who will come from the tribe of Judah or (2) they may refer to different leaders who will come from Judah.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('q653', 'ZEC', 10, 4, '10:4', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metaphor', 'from him will come the tent peg', 0, '“the tent peg will come from him.” The tent pegs held the ropes that supported tents in which people lived. Here the most important ruler is spoken of as if he where the main peg that holds a tent in place. Alternate translation: [the leader who will hold the nation together will come from Judah]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('mgt1', 'ZEC', 10, 4, '10:4', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metaphor', 'from him will come the war bow', 0, '“the war bow will come from him.” Here the most important ruler is spoken of as if he where the a war bow that was used in battle. Alternate translation: [the military leader will come from Judah]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('cw1m', 'ZEC', 10, 4, '10:4', NULL, NULL, 'from him will come every ruler together', 0, 'Alternate translation: [every ruler will come from Judah]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('sg3z', 'ZEC', 10, 5, '10:5', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-simile', 'They will be like warriors … streets in battle', 0, 'The rulers from Judah are spoken of as if they were victorious warriors. Alternate translation: [They will be mighty in battle, trampling their enemies into the mud of the streets]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('f7n7', 'ZEC', 10, 5, '10:5', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-idiom', 'who trample their enemies into the mud of the streets in battle', 0, 'To trample them into the mud is an idiom that means to completely defeat them. Alternate translation: [who defeat their enemies completely]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('xrr5', 'ZEC', 10, 5, '10:5', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-idiom', 'Yahweh is with them', 0, 'Here “with them” is an idiom that means he is present to help them. Alternate translation: [Yahweh will help them]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('a47d', 'ZEC', 10, 5, '10:5', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'they will shame those who ride warhorses', 0, 'Here shame accompanies and represents defeat. Alternate translation: [they will defeat their enemies who ride warhorses]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('skk5', 'ZEC', 10, 6, '10:6', NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, '# General Information:\n\nIn verses 6–12, Yahweh is speaking to the people of Israel.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('tf8l', 'ZEC', 10, 6, '10:6', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'the house of Judah', 0, 'The word “house” is a metonym for the family that lives in the house. In this case it refers to the kingdom of Judah, which included the descendants of Judah and Benjamin. Alternate translation: [Judah] or “the kingdom of Judah” or “the people of Judah”');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('q4yn', 'ZEC', 10, 6, '10:6', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'the house of Joseph', 0, 'The word “house” is a metonym for the family that lives in the house. In this case it refers to the kingdom of Israel. Alternate translation: [Israel] or “the kingdom of Israel” or “the people of Israel”');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('b62v', 'ZEC', 10, 6, '10:6', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metaphor', 'I had not cast them off', 0, 'This speaks of the people as a torn or dirty garment that Yahweh took off and threw away. Alternate translation: [I had not rejected them]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('zfa5', 'ZEC', 10, 7, '10:7', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-simile', 'Ephraim will be like a warrior', 0, '“Ephraim” refers here to the northern kingdom of Israel. Alternate translation: [Ephraim will be very strong]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('pg8l', 'ZEC', 10, 7, '10:7', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-synecdoche', 'their hearts will rejoice as with wine', 0, 'Here “hearts” refers to the whole person. Alternate translation: [and they will be very happy]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('u9gr', 'ZEC', 10, 7, '10:7', NULL, NULL, 'their children will see and rejoice. Their hearts will rejoice in me!', 0, 'Alternate translation: [their children will see what has taken place and will be happy because of what Yahweh has done for them!]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('rt4z', 'ZEC', 10, 8, '10:8', NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, '# General Information:\n\nIn verses 6–12, Yahweh is speaking to the people of Israel.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('h3zu', 'ZEC', 10, 8, '10:8', NULL, NULL, 'I will whistle', 0, 'To whistle is to produce a high, shrill sound with air through narrowed lips. It is often done to give a signal to other people, as here.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('a419', 'ZEC', 10, 9, '10:9', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metaphor', 'I sowed them among the peoples', 0, 'The exile of the people is spoken of as if they were seed that Yahweh had planted in a distant land.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('qvy9', 'ZEC', 10, 10, '10:10', NULL, NULL, 'until there is no more room for them', 0, 'The people will continue to go back to Judah and it will become crowded with no room for any more people to live there. This can be stated in positive form. Alternate translation: [and they will completely fill the land]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('gh3n', 'ZEC', 10, 11, '10:11', NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, '# General Information:\n\nIn verses 6–12, Yahweh is speaking to the people of Israel.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('kec9', 'ZEC', 10, 11, '10:11', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metaphor', 'I will pass through the sea of their affliction', 0, 'Scripture often refers to the sea as an image of many troubles and hardships. Here Yahweh speaks of himself accompanying the people to help them go through these afflictions. Alternate translation: [I will go with them and help them as they go through their many afflictions]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('sq3e', 'ZEC', 10, 11, '10:11', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-idiom', 'I will strike the waves of that sea', 0, 'Here to “strike” the waves is an idiom that means he will stop the waves from forming. Alternate translation: [I will cause the waves of that sea of affliction to stop]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('ve5n', 'ZEC', 10, 11, '10:11', NULL, NULL, 'will dry up all the depths of the Nile', 0, 'Alternate translation: [I will cause the Nile River to lose all its water]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('h8a4', 'ZEC', 10, 11, '10:11', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'The majesty of Assyria will be brought down', 0, 'Here “the majesty of Assyria” probably refers to the Assyrian army. Alternate translation: [I will destroy Assyria’s proud army]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('g3sx', 'ZEC', 10, 11, '10:11', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'the scepter of Egypt will go away from the Egyptians', 0, 'Here “the scepter of Egypt” refers to the political power of Egypt. Alternate translation: [the power of Egypt to rule other nations will end]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('wnc7', 'ZEC', 10, 12, '10:12', NULL, NULL, 'I will strengthen them in myself', 0, 'Alternate translation: [I will cause them to be strong and to believe in me]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('up7e', 'ZEC', 11, 0, '11:intro', NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, '# Zechariah 11 General Notes\n\n## Structure and Formatting\n\nThis chapter unlike the previous one is a warning against the leaders amongst the exiles.\n\nSome translations set each line of poetry farther to the right than the rest of the text to make it easier to read. The ULT does this with the poetic song in 11:1–3, 17.\n\n## Translation Issues in This Chapter\n\n### Metaphor\n\nThis chapter uses an extended metaphor of sheep and shepherds to convey Yahweh’s dismay at the leaders during the exiles. (See: [[rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metaphor]])\n\n### Symbolism\n\nThe writer uses symbolism. Zechariah is told to become a shepherd. He uses two staffs and names them “Unity” and “Favor.” He does this very purposefully. In order to preserve this symbolism, it is important to pay attention to the specific words used. (See: [[rc://*/tw/dict/bible/kt/favor]])');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('d6vm', 'ZEC', 11, 1, '11:1', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metaphor', 'Open your doors, Lebanon, that fire may devour', 0, 'Not resisting what is about to happen is spoken of as if Lebanon were opening its doors. Alternate translation: [People of Lebanon, get ready, because fire will devour]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('kmf3', 'ZEC', 11, 1, '11:1', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metaphor', 'fire may devour your cedars', 0, 'Fire completely burning up the cedars is spoken of as if the fire would devour the cedars. Alternate translation: [fire may completely destroy your cedars] or “fire may completely burn up your cedars”');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('fu2k', 'ZEC', 11, 2, '11:2', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-personification', 'Lament, cypress trees, for the cedar trees have fallen', 0, 'Cypress trees are spoken of as if they could grieve like a human. Alternate translation: [If the trees were people, they would cry out in sorrow. The cypress trees stand alone because the cedars have burned and fallen]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('fq53', 'ZEC', 11, 2, '11:2', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-activepassive', 'What was majestic has been devastated', 0, 'If your language does not use the passive form in this way, you can state this in active form or in another way that is natural in your language. Alternate translation: [The majestic cedar trees are no more] or “The cedar trees were once majestic, but now they are ruined”');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('gbt2', 'ZEC', 11, 2, '11:2', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-personification', 'Lament, you oaks of Bashan, for the strong forest has gone down.', 0, 'The oaks of Bash are spoken of as if they could grieve like a human. Alternate translation: [If the oak trees in Bashan were people, they would wail, for their thick forests are gone]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('pb1q', 'ZEC', 11, 3, '11:3', NULL, NULL, 'The shepherds howl', 0, 'Alternate translation: [The shepherds cry out loudly]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('ji77', 'ZEC', 11, 3, '11:3', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'for their glory has been destroyed', 0, 'Here “their glory” probably represents the rich pastures that the shepherds led their sheep to. Alternate translation: [for their rich pastures are ruined]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('h9cl', 'ZEC', 11, 3, '11:3', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'for the pride of the Jordan River has been devastated', 0, 'Here “the pride” probably represents the forests that grew near the Jordan River. Alternate translation: [because the trees and shrubbery where they lived by the Jordan River are ruined]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('u48q', 'ZEC', 11, 4, '11:4', NULL, NULL, 'watch over the flock set aside for slaughter', 0, 'Alternate translation: [take care of a flock of sheep that the owners plan to slaughter]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('ip1w', 'ZEC', 11, 5, '11:5', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-activepassive', 'are not punished', 0, 'If your language does not use the passive form in this way, you can state this in active form or in another way that is natural in your language. Alternate translation: [no one punishes them]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('f3ps', 'ZEC', 11, 6, '11:6', NULL, NULL, 'See!', 0, 'Alternate translation: [Listen!] or “Pay attention!”');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('t499', 'ZEC', 11, 6, '11:6', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-rpronouns', 'I myself', 0, 'The word “myself” is used to emphasize that it is Yahweh who will do these things.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('qz87', 'ZEC', 11, 6, '11:6', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'turn over every person into the hand of his neighbor and into the hand of his king', 0, 'Here “hand” represents power or control. Alternate translation: [allow the people to harm each other and the king will oppress them]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('sr77', 'ZEC', 11, 6, '11:6', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'none of them will I deliver them from their hand', 0, 'Here “hand” represents power or control. Alternate translation: [I will not save them from those who are harming them] or “I will not rescue them”');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('jsk4', 'ZEC', 11, 7, '11:7', NULL, NULL, 'for those who dealt in sheep', 0, 'Alternate translation: [for those who bought and sold sheep]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('gy5l', 'ZEC', 11, 7, '11:7', NULL, NULL, 'Favor', 0, 'Other versions of the Bible translate this word as “grace,” “beauty,” or “pleasant.”');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('kqz7', 'ZEC', 11, 8, '11:8', NULL, NULL, 'I became impatient with them,', 0, 'This could mean: (1) “them” refers to the three shepherds or (2) “them” refers to the sheep owners.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('cnt4', 'ZEC', 11, 9, '11:9', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-activepassive', 'the sheep that are being destroyed—let them be destroyed', 0, 'If your language does not use the passive form in this way, you can state this in active form or in another way that is natural in your language. Alternate translation: [the sheep that are perishing—let them perish] or “the sheep that are to wander and get lost—let them get lost”');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('m881', 'ZEC', 11, 11, '11:11', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-activepassive', 'the covenant was broken', 0, 'If your language does not use the passive form in this way, you can state this in active form or in another way that is natural in your language. Alternate translation: [the covenant ended]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('ve5p', 'ZEC', 11, 11, '11:11', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-explicit', 'knew that Yahweh had spoken', 0, 'It is implied that those watching knew Yahweh was giving them a message through the breaking of the staff. Alternate translation: [knew that Yahweh had given them a message]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('x7fr', 'ZEC', 11, 12, '11:12', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-explicit', 'thirty pieces of silver', 0, 'It is implied that this was very little pay for the shepherd. Alternate translation: [only thirty pieces of silver]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('zf3a', 'ZEC', 11, 12, '11:12', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/translate-numbers', 'thirty pieces', 0, '“30 pieces”');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('dv1a', 'ZEC', 11, 13, '11:13', NULL, NULL, 'treasury', 0, 'This is the place in the temple of Yahweh where the priests kept the money. Many versions of the Bible translate this as “potter.” This is the person who would melt metal to make vessels out of it. Here Yahweh would mean that the payment is so small that the shepherd should have the silver melted to show how insulted he was.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('ye4f', 'ZEC', 11, 13, '11:13', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-irony', 'the excellent price', 0, 'Yahweh uses irony to say that this price was very small for a shepherd doing Yahweh’s work. Alternate translation: [the ridiculously small amount of money]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('js8t', 'ZEC', 11, 14, '11:14', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'between Judah and Israel', 0, 'Here “Judah” represents the people of the southern kingdom and “Israel” represents the people of the northern kingdom. Alternate translation: [between the people of Judah and the people of Israel]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('t1g5', 'ZEC', 11, 16, '11:16', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-idiom', 'I am about to set in place a shepherd in the land', 0, 'Here “set in place” is an idiom. Alternate translation: [I am about to appoint a shepherd in the land] or “I am about to put a shepherd in charge in the land”');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('qq2g', 'ZEC', 11, 16, '11:16', NULL, NULL, 'the fattened sheep', 0, 'Alternate translation: [the fattest sheep] or “the best sheep”');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('wwi6', 'ZEC', 11, 16, '11:16', NULL, NULL, 'will tear off their hooves', 0, 'This was probably done as an act of cruelty.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('wum9', 'ZEC', 11, 17, '11:17', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'May the sword', 0, 'Here “sword” represents enemies who will attack the shepherd. Alternate translation: [May enemies]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('zwk6', 'ZEC', 11, 17, '11:17', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-idiom', 'come against his arm and his right eye', 0, 'Here “come against” is an idiom. Alternate translation: [strike and wound his right arm and pierce his right eye]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('gqb9', 'ZEC', 11, 17, '11:17', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'his arm', 0, 'Here “arm” represents the power to fight.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('c27h', 'ZEC', 11, 17, '11:17', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-explicit', 'his right eye', 0, 'A soldier would use his right eye to look around the shield that he held with his left hand. If his right eye was wounded, he would not be able to see to fight in war.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('h47i', 'ZEC', 11, 17, '11:17', NULL, NULL, 'his arm wither away', 0, 'Alternate translation: [his arm waste away] or “his arm become completely useless”');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('cr4a', 'ZEC', 12, 0, '12:intro', NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, '# Zechariah 12 General Notes\n\n## Structure and Formatting\n\nSimilar to chapter 11, this chapter is written mainly in prose and is talking about Jerusalem.\n\n## Religious and Cultural Concepts in This Chapter\n\n### Prophecy\n\nVerses 10–11 are quoted in the New Testament and apply to Jesus’ death on the cross. (See: [[rc://*/tw/dict/bible/kt/cross]])');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('vy11', 'ZEC', 12, 1, '12:1', NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, '# General Information:\n\nThese verses begin a section that tells about the coming attack against Jerusalem and how God will rescue the city.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('mz3s', 'ZEC', 12, 1, '12:1', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metaphor', 'who stretched out the skies', 0, 'This is a metaphor that speaks of the sky as if it were like a scroll that is rolled up and needs to be stretched out. Alternate translation: [the one who created the sky]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('gzl6', 'ZEC', 12, 1, '12:1', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metaphor', 'laid the foundation of the earth', 0, 'This is a metaphor that speaks of the earth as if it were a building with a foundation. Alternate translation: [put all the earth into place]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('gnm5', 'ZEC', 12, 1, '12:1', NULL, NULL, 'fashions the spirit of mankind within man', 0, 'This is a metaphor that speaks of the spirit as if it were like clay that a potter shapes. Alternate translation: [creates the human spirit]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('ez4w', 'ZEC', 12, 2, '12:2', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metaphor', 'I am about to make Jerusalem into a cup … to stagger about', 0, 'Yahweh using Jerusalem to punish the surrounding peoples is spoken of as if Yahweh would make Jerusalem a cup full of an alcoholic drink that will cause the surrounding peoples to get drunk and stagger. Alternate translation: [Soon it will be like I make Jerusalem into a cup … to stagger about]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('s5lx', 'ZEC', 12, 2, '12:2', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'into a cup', 0, 'Here “cup” represents the cup and the contents within the cup. Alternate translation: [into a cup full of wine] or “into a cup full of an alcoholic drink”');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('h8sn', 'ZEC', 12, 2, '12:2', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-personification', 'surrounding her', 0, 'Here “her” refers to the city of Jerusalem. It was common in Hebrew to speak of a city or country as if it were a woman.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('u546', 'ZEC', 12, 3, '12:3', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metaphor', 'I will make Jerusalem a heavy stone for all the peoples', 0, 'Yahweh using Jerusalem to punish the surrounding peoples is spoken of as if he would make Jerusalem a heavy stone. Alternate translation: [It will be like I will make Jerusalem a heavy stone for all the peoples]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('h97f', 'ZEC', 12, 4, '12:4', NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, '# General Information:\n\nThese verses continue telling about the coming attack against Jerusalem and how God will rescue the city.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('w42z', 'ZEC', 12, 4, '12:4', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metaphor', 'Over the house of Judah I will open my eyes', 0, 'Opening eyes over someone here is a metaphor for wanting to do good things for that person. Alternate translation: [I will do good things for the house of Judah] or “I will protect the house of Judah”');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('jgj7', 'ZEC', 12, 4, '12:4', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'the house of Judah', 0, 'Here “house” represents people. Alternate translation: [the people of Judah]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('g3n8', 'ZEC', 12, 5, '12:5', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'say in their hearts', 0, 'Here “hearts” represents a person’s mind. Alternate translation: [think to themselves] or “say to themselves”');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('w95z', 'ZEC', 12, 5, '12:5', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-abstractnouns', 'are our strength', 0, 'If your language does not use an abstract noun for the idea behind the word **strength**, you can express the same idea with a verbal form such as “strong” or “encourage.” Alternate translation: [make us strong] or “encourage us”');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('u38m', 'ZEC', 12, 5, '12:5', NULL, NULL, 'Yahweh of hosts, their God', 0, 'Alternate translation: [Yahweh of hosts, the God they worship]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('zv3y', 'ZEC', 12, 6, '12:6', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-simile', 'like firepots among wood … standing grain', 0, 'This simile means Yahweh will enable the leaders of Judah to be strong and able to lead the people to defeat their enemies. Alternate translation: [like firepots among stacked firewood … unharvested stalks of grain standing in a field]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('cjb8', 'ZEC', 12, 6, '12:6', NULL, NULL, 'firepots', 0, 'clay pots in which ancient people often carried burning coals');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('vm57', 'ZEC', 12, 6, '12:6', NULL, NULL, 'flaming torch', 0, 'a wooden stick that is burning at one end which gives light as one travels or carries fire somewhere');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('iv6n', 'ZEC', 12, 6, '12:6', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metaphor', 'will consume all the surrounding peoples', 0, 'Completely destroying the peoples is spoken of as if the people of Judah will “devour” them. Alternate translation: [will destroy the surrounding peoples]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('l53t', 'ZEC', 12, 6, '12:6', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-merism', 'on their right and on their left', 0, 'Here “right” and “left” represent every direction. Alternate translation: [in every direction]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('hh2l', 'ZEC', 12, 6, '12:6', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'Jerusalem will again live in her own place', 0, 'Here “Jerusalem” represents the people who live there. Alternate translation: [The people of Jerusalem will again live in their own city]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('qxb1', 'ZEC', 12, 7, '12:7', NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, '# General Information:\n\nThese verses continue telling about the coming attack against Jerusalem and how God will rescue the city.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('nba7', 'ZEC', 12, 7, '12:7', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'the tents of Judah', 0, 'Here “tents” represents homes, and homes represent the people who live in them. Alternate translation: [the people of Judah]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('h87n', 'ZEC', 12, 7, '12:7', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'the house of David', 0, 'This could mean: (1) the descendants of David or (2) the ruling class of people.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('ys6n', 'ZEC', 12, 8, '12:8', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-simile', 'those who are weak among them will be like David', 0, 'This simile means those who are weak will be strong. Alternate translation: [those who are weak will be strong like David]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('zz25', 'ZEC', 12, 8, '12:8', NULL, NULL, 'the angel of Yahweh', 0, 'This is an angel sent by Yahweh to protect the people.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('f9d7', 'ZEC', 12, 10, '12:10', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metaphor', 'I will pour out a spirit of compassion and pleading on the house of David and the inhabitants of Jerusalem', 0, 'Causing the people to be compassionate and to plead is spoken of as if the spirit were a liquid that Yahweh would pour on them. Alternate translation: [I will cause the house of David and inhabitants of Jerusalem to have mercy on others and to pray to me for mercy]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('dtc6', 'ZEC', 12, 10, '12:10', NULL, NULL, 'a spirit of compassion and pleading', 0, 'Here this means to have a characteristic of compassion and pleading.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('c3sx', 'ZEC', 12, 10, '12:10', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'the house of David', 0, 'Here “house” represents descendants. Alternate translation: [the descendants of David]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('zpa3', 'ZEC', 12, 10, '12:10', NULL, NULL, 'the one they have pierced', 0, 'Alternate translation: [the one whom they stabbed to death]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('rxx7', 'ZEC', 12, 10, '12:10', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-ellipsis', 'for an only son', 0, 'It is understood that the “son” has died. Alternate translation: [for an only son who has died]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('mcu4', 'ZEC', 12, 11, '12:11', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/translate-names', 'the laments in Jerusalem will be like the laments at Hadad Rimmon', 0, 'Hadad Rimmon may have been the place where the good King Josiah died of battle wounds after the Battle of Megiddo. It appears that the custom arose to hold periodic mourning there for his death. Some people, however, think that Hadad Rimmon was the name of a false god who was believed to die every year, an event for which his worshipers would go into mourning. (See also: [[rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-explicit]])');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('qg93', 'ZEC', 12, 11, '12:11', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/translate-names', 'Megiddo', 0, 'This is the name of a plain in Israel.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('jj6q', 'ZEC', 12, 12, '12:12', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'The land will mourn', 0, 'This represents all the people living in the land of Judah. Alternate translation: [All the people in the land of Judah will mourn]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('qth7', 'ZEC', 12, 12, '12:12', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'The clan of the house of David … The clan of the house of Nathan', 0, 'Here “house” represents descendants. Alternate translation: [The descendants of David … The descendants of Nathan]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('r6fc', 'ZEC', 12, 13, '12:13', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'The clan of the house of Levi', 0, 'Here “house” represents descendants. Alternate translation: [The descendants of Levi]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('uxpd', 'ZEC', 13, 0, '13:intro', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '# Zechariah 13 Introduction\n\n## Structure and Formatting\n\nVerses 1–6 are a prose oracle about cleansing from sin and removing false [[rc://*/tw/dict/bible/kt/prophet|prophets]]. Verses 7–9 shift to poetry, announcing the striking of Yahweh’s [[rc://*/tw/dict/bible/other/shepherd|shepherd]] and the [[rc://*/tw/dict/bible/kt/purify|purifying]] of a surviving [[rc://*/tw/dict/bible/kt/remnant|remnant]].\n\n## Religious and Cultural Concepts in This Chapter\n\n### The Prophetic Cloak\n\nThe “cloak of hair” (verse 4) is the rough garment that identified [[rc://*/tw/dict/bible/kt/prophet|prophets]]. False prophets abandon this clothing to conceal their identity.\n\n## Translation Issues in This Chapter\n\n### Nested Quotations\n\nYahweh’s speech spans the entire chapter and contains embedded quotes from parents (verse 3), a false prophet (verses 5–6), and a covenant declaration (verse 9).');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('e5x6', 'ZEC', 13, 1, '13:1', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'לְ⁠בֵ֥ית דָּוִ֖יד', 1, 'Here, **the house of David** represents the descendants of David and the royal dynasty. If it would be helpful in your language, you could use an equivalent expression or plain language. Alternate translation: [the descendants of David]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('fa7t', 'ZEC', 13, 1, '13:1', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-newevent', 'הַ⁠ה֗וּא', 1, 'Zechariah is using the phrase On that day to introduce a new event in the story. Use a word, phrase, or other method in your language that is natural for introducing a new event.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('aano', 'ZEC', 13, 1, '13:1', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metaphor', 'מָק֣וֹר נִפְתָּ֔ח', 1, 'Here Zechariah is speaking as if the means of cleansing from sin were a fountain that would be opened. Your language may have a comparable expression that you can use in your translation, or you could state the meaning plainly. Alternate translation: [a source of cleansing will be made available]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('ocrk', 'ZEC', 13, 1, '13:1', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-activepassive', 'מָק֣וֹר נִפְתָּ֔ח', 1, 'The expression a fountain will be opened is a passive verbal form. If it would be unnatural to use that form, you could express the idea in active form or in another way that is natural in your language. If you need to say who does the action, the context indicates that it is God. Alternate translation: [God will open a fountain]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('k64y', 'ZEC', 13, 1, '13:1', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-merism', 'לְ⁠חַטַּ֖את וּ⁠לְ⁠נִדָּֽה', 1, 'Zechariah is referring to all types of uncleanness by naming two major components, sin and impurity. If it would be helpful in your language, you could use an equivalent expression or plain language. Alternate translation: [every kind of sin and uncleanness]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('swtm', 'ZEC', 13, 1, '13:1', 'at-fit', 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-abstractnouns', 'לְ⁠חַטַּ֖את וּ⁠לְ⁠נִדָּֽה', 1, 'If your language does not use abstract nouns for the ideas of sin and impurity, you could express the same ideas in other ways. Alternate translation: [sinning … being unclean]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('epd0', 'ZEC', 13, 2, '13:2', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'שְׁמ֤וֹת הָֽ⁠עֲצַבִּים֙', 1, 'Here, **the names of the idols** represents the memory and reputation of the idols. If it would be helpful in your language, you could use an equivalent expression or plain language. Alternate translation: [the memory of the idols]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('jj4z', 'ZEC', 13, 2, '13:2', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-newevent', 'וְ⁠הָיָה֩ & הַ⁠ה֜וּא', 1, 'Yahweh is using the phrase And it will be on that day to introduce a new event in the story. Use a word, phrase, or other method in your language that is natural for introducing a new event.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('obhm', 'ZEC', 13, 2, '13:2', 'ISSUE:MATCH_FAIL', 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-quotations', 'נְאֻ֣ם יְהוָ֣ה צְבָא֗וֹת', 1, 'The phrase the declaration of Yahweh of Armies is a parenthetical statement within Yahweh’s speech that identifies him as the speaker. In your translation, use a natural way of indicating the speaker of a direct quotation in your language. It may not be necessary to represent this phrase explicitly.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('e7dp', 'ZEC', 13, 2, '13:2', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-activepassive', 'יִזָּכְר֖וּ ע֑וֹד', 1, 'The expression they will no longer be remembered is a passive verbal form. If it would be unnatural to use that form, you could express the idea in active form or in another way that is natural in your language. Alternate translation: [no one will remember them anymore]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('fy69', 'ZEC', 13, 2, '13:2', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-possession', 'ר֥וּחַ הַ⁠טֻּמְאָ֖ה', 1, 'Yahweh is using the possessive form to describe a spirit that is characterized by uncleanness. If a speaker of your language would not use the possessive form for this, you could express this idea in another way. Alternate translation: [the unclean spirit]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('gikg', 'ZEC', 13, 2, '13:2', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-abstractnouns', 'הַ⁠טֻּמְאָ֖ה', 1, 'If your language does not use an abstract noun for the idea of uncleanness, you could express the same idea in another way. Alternate translation: [what is unclean]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('in59', 'ZEC', 13, 2, '13:2', 'at-fit', 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/grammar-connect-words-phrases', 'וְ⁠גַ֧ם', 1, 'Here, the words **And also** add a further action to the one just described. Yahweh will not only remove the idols but will additionally remove the false prophets and the unclean spirit. If the connection between this statement and the previous one is not clear, you may want to use a different connecting word to show how this statement relates to what comes before it. Alternate translation: [Furthermore,]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('m4l6', 'ZEC', 13, 3, '13:3', 'at-fit', 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'בְּ⁠שֵׁ֣ם יְהוָ֑ה', 1, 'Here, **in the name of Yahweh** represents the authority of Yahweh. If it would be helpful in your language, you could use an equivalent expression or plain language. Alternate translation: [with Yahweh’s authority behind you]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('yzml', 'ZEC', 13, 3, '13:3', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/grammar-connect-logic-reason', 'וְ⁠הָיָ֗ה כִּֽי־יִנָּבֵ֣א אִישׁ֮ עוֹד֒ וְ⁠אָמְר֣וּ אֵ֠לָי⁠ו אָבִ֨י⁠ו וְ⁠אִמּ֤⁠וֹ יֹֽלְדָי⁠ו֙ & תִֽחְיֶ֔ה כִּ֛י שֶׁ֥קֶר דִּבַּ֖רְתָּ בְּ⁠שֵׁ֣ם יְהוָ֑ה וּ⁠דְקָרֻ֜⁠הוּ אָבִ֧י⁠הוּ וְ⁠אִמּ֛⁠וֹ יֹלְדָ֖י⁠ו בְּ⁠הִנָּבְאֽ⁠וֹ', 1, 'The word translated as for indicates that what follows is a reason for what came before. Use a connector in your language that makes it clear that what follows is a reason for what came before. Alternate translation: [because you have spoken falsehood in the name of Yahweh]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('mzjh', 'ZEC', 13, 3, '13:3', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-newevent', 'וְ⁠הָיָ֗ה', 1, 'Yahweh is using the phrase And it will be to introduce a new event in the story. Use a word, phrase, or other method in your language that is natural for introducing a new event.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('td5k', 'ZEC', 13, 3, '13:3', 'at-fit', 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/grammar-connect-condition-hypothetical', 'כִּֽי־יִנָּבֵ֣א אִישׁ֮ עוֹד֒', 1, 'Yahweh is presenting a possible condition, that the parents will condemn and kill their son only if he still prophesies falsely. Use a natural form in your language for introducing a condition that could happen. It may be helpful to reorder this sentence so that the conditional statement is first. Alternate translation: [should a man still prophesy]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('ujl0', 'ZEC', 13, 3, '13:3', 'at-fit', 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-genericnoun', 'אִישׁ֮', 1, 'Yahweh is not referring to a specific man. He means any person who prophesies falsely in general. If it would be helpful to your readers, you could use an expression that would be more natural in your language. Alternate translation: [anyone who]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('iadz', 'ZEC', 13, 3, '13:3', 'at-fit', 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-quotesinquotes', 'כִּֽי & תִֽחְיֶ֔ה & שֶׁ֥קֶר דִּבַּ֖רְתָּ בְּ⁠שֵׁ֣ם יְהוָ֑ה', 1, 'If it would be clearer in your language, you could translate this so that there is not a quotation within a quotation. Alternate translation: [that he must not live, because he has spoken falsehood in the name of Yahweh]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('q982', 'ZEC', 13, 3, '13:3', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-litotes', 'תִֽחְיֶ֔ה', 1, 'The parents of the false prophet are emphasizing a positive meaning by using a negative word, not, together with a mild expression that is the opposite of the intended meaning. They mean that the false prophet will certainly die. If it would be helpful in your language, you could emphasize the positive meaning in a strong way. Alternate translation: [you will certainly die]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('q3xi', 'ZEC', 13, 3, '13:3', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-abstractnouns', 'שֶׁ֥קֶר', 1, 'If your language does not use an abstract noun for the idea of falsehood, you could express the same idea in another way. Alternate translation: [falsely]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('nrol', 'ZEC', 13, 4, '13:4', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/grammar-connect-logic-goal', 'וְ⁠הָיָ֣ה & הַ⁠ה֗וּא יֵבֹ֧שׁוּ הַ⁠נְּבִיאִ֛ים אִ֥ישׁ מֵ⁠חֶזְיֹנ֖⁠וֹ בְּ⁠הִנָּֽבְאֹת֑⁠וֹ וְ⁠לֹ֧א יִלְבְּשׁ֛וּ אַדֶּ֥רֶת שֵׂעָ֖ר לְמַ֥עַן כַּחֵֽשׁ', 1, 'Here, **in order to** marks **to deceive** as the goal or purpose of the false prophets putting on a cloak of hair. Use a connector in your language that makes it clear that this is the purpose.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('viav', 'ZEC', 13, 4, '13:4', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-newevent', 'וְ⁠הָיָ֣ה & הַ⁠ה֗וּא', 1, 'See how you translated the similar expression in [13:2](../13/02.md).');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('bl3f', 'ZEC', 13, 4, '13:4', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-possession', 'אַדֶּ֥רֶת שֵׂעָ֖ר', 1, 'Zechariah is using the possessive form to describe a cloak that is made of hair. If a speaker of your language would not use the possessive form for this, you could express this idea in another way. Alternate translation: [a cloak made of hair]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('w2py', 'ZEC', 13, 5, '13:5', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-pronouns', 'וְ⁠אָמַ֕ר', 1, 'The pronoun he refers to the false prophet described in the previous verse. It may be helpful to clarify this for your readers. Alternate translation: [And the false prophet will say]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('u35b', 'ZEC', 13, 5, '13:5', 'at-fit', 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-abstractnouns', 'מִ⁠נְּעוּרָֽ⁠י', 1, 'If your language does not use an abstract noun for the idea of youth, you could express the same idea in another way. Alternate translation: [when I was young]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('g3wn', 'ZEC', 13, 5, '13:5', 'at-fit', 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/grammar-connect-logic-reason', 'וְ⁠אָמַ֕ר לֹ֥א נָבִ֖יא אָנֹ֑כִי אִישׁ־עֹבֵ֤ד אֲדָמָה֙ אָנֹ֔כִי כִּ֥י אָדָ֖ם הִקְנַ֥⁠נִי מִ⁠נְּעוּרָֽ⁠י', 1, 'The word translated as for indicates that what follows is a reason for what came before. Use a connector in your language that makes it clear that what follows is a reason for what came before. Alternate translation: [And he will say, ‘I {am} not a prophet. I {am} a man working the ground. The reason is that a man acquired me from my youth.’]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('jihj', 'ZEC', 13, 5, '13:5', 'at-fit', 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-quotesinquotes', 'נָבִ֖יא אָנֹ֑כִי אִישׁ־עֹבֵ֤ד אֲדָמָה֙ & כִּ֥י אָדָ֖ם הִקְנַ֥⁠נִי מִ⁠נְּעוּרָֽ⁠י', 1, 'If it would be clearer in your language, you could translate this so that there is not a quotation within a quotation. Alternate translation: [he is not a prophet but a man working the ground, for a man acquired him from his youth]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('hbua', 'ZEC', 13, 6, '13:6', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-idiom', 'בֵּ֣ין יָדֶ֑י⁠ךָ', 1, 'The false prophet is using between your hands as a common expression of the culture to mean “on your chest” or “on your body.” If this phrase does not have that meaning for your readers, you could use a comparable expression from your language that does have that meaning, or you could state the meaning plainly. Alternate translation: [on your chest]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('yicj', 'ZEC', 13, 6, '13:6', 'at-fit', 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-quotesinquotes', 'אֲשֶׁ֥ר הֻכֵּ֖יתִי בֵּ֥ית מְאַהֲבָֽ⁠י', 1, 'If it would be clearer in your language, you could translate this so that there is not a quotation within a quotation. Alternate translation: [that those wounds came from being struck in the house of those who loved him]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('iqc7', 'ZEC', 13, 6, '13:6', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-activepassive', 'הֻכֵּ֖יתִי', 1, 'The expression I was struck is a passive verbal form. If it would be unnatural to use that form, you could express the idea in active form or in another way that is natural in your language. Alternate translation: [they struck me]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('jrn0', 'ZEC', 13, 6, '13:6', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-nominaladj', 'מְאַהֲבָֽ⁠י', 1, 'The false prophet is using the participle the ones loving me as a noun to mean people who love him. Your language may use adjectives in the same way. If not, you can translate this with an equivalent phrase. Alternate translation: [those who love me]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('svbi', 'ZEC', 13, 6, '13:6', 'at-fit', 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-quotesinquotes', 'מָ֧ה & הָ⁠אֵ֖לֶּה בֵּ֣ין יָדֶ֑י⁠ךָ', 1, 'If it would be clearer in your language, you could translate this so that there is not a quotation within a quotation. Alternate translation: [why he has those wounds between his hands]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('uui4', 'ZEC', 13, 6, '13:6', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-pronouns', 'וְ⁠אָמַ֣ר אֵלָ֔י⁠ו', 1, 'The word someone is an indefinite subject that does not refer to a specific person. It refers to anyone who might ask the false prophet this question. It may be helpful to clarify this for your readers. Alternate translation: [And if anyone asks him]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('t5ny', 'ZEC', 13, 6, '13:6', 'at-fit', 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'בֵּ֥ית מְאַהֲבָֽ⁠י', 1, 'Here, **the house of the ones loving me** represents the home or dwelling place of the people who love the speaker. If it would be helpful in your language, you could use an equivalent expression or plain language. Alternate translation: [the dwelling place of those who love me]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('a74s', 'ZEC', 13, 7, '13:7', 'at-fit', 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-apostrophe', 'חֶ֗רֶב עוּרִ֤י עַל־רֹעִ⁠י֙', 1, 'Yahweh is speaking to a **sword** that he knows cannot hear him. He is doing this to communicate to the people listening to him that he feels very strongly about the judgment he is about to bring. If it would be helpful in your language, you could translate these words as if he were speaking directly to the people about the sword. Alternate translation: [Let the sword awake against my shepherd]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('k27o', 'ZEC', 13, 7, '13:7', 'at-fit', 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metaphor', 'רֹעִ⁠י֙', 1, 'Here Yahweh is speaking as if the leader he appointed were **my shepherd**. Your language may have a comparable expression that you can use in your translation, or you could state the meaning plainly. Alternate translation: [the leader I care for]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('qo9m', 'ZEC', 13, 7, '13:7', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-quotations', 'נְאֻ֖ם יְהוָ֣ה צְבָא֑וֹת', 1, 'The phrase **the declaration of Yahweh of Armies** is a parenthetical statement within Yahweh’s speech that identifies him as the speaker. In your translation, use a natural way of indicating the speaker of a direct quotation in your language. It may not be necessary to represent this phrase explicitly.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('tz6c', 'ZEC', 13, 7, '13:7', 'at-fit', 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metaphor', 'וּ⁠תְפוּצֶ֣יןָ הַ⁠צֹּ֔אן', 1, 'Here Yahweh is speaking as if the people were **the flock** that **will be scattered**. Your language may have a comparable expression that you can use in your translation, or you could state the meaning plainly. Alternate translation: [the people will scatter]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('lcl4', 'ZEC', 13, 7, '13:7', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'עַל & וַ⁠הֲשִׁבֹתִ֥י יָדִ֖⁠י', 1, 'Here, **my hand** represents Yahweh’s power and action. If it would be helpful in your language, you could use an equivalent expression or plain language. Alternate translation: [I will direct my power against]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('k6l3', 'ZEC', 13, 7, '13:7', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-nominaladj', 'הַ⁠צֹּעֲרִֽים', 1, 'Yahweh is using the adjective **little** as a noun to mean the weak and vulnerable people. Your language may use adjectives in the same way. If not, you can translate this adjective with an equivalent phrase. Alternate translation: [the weak and vulnerable ones]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('tblb', 'ZEC', 13, 8, '13:8', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-newevent', 'וְ⁠הָיָ֤ה בְ⁠כָל־הָ⁠אָ֨רֶץ֙', 1, 'Yahweh is using the phrase **And it will be** to introduce a new event in the story. Use a word, phrase, or other method in your language that is natural for introducing a new event.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('az59', 'ZEC', 13, 8, '13:8', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-quotations', 'נְאֻם־יְהוָ֔ה', 1, 'The phrase **the declaration of Yahweh** is a parenthetical statement within Yahweh’s speech that identifies him as the speaker. In your translation, use a natural way of indicating the speaker of a direct quotation in your language. It may not be necessary to represent this phrase explicitly.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('k23g', 'ZEC', 13, 8, '13:8', 'at-fit', 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-activepassive', 'שְׁנַ֣יִם בָּ֔⁠הּ יִכָּרְת֖וּ', 1, 'The expression **two parts in it will be cut off** is a passive verbal form. If it would be unnatural to use that form, you could express the idea in active form or in another way that is natural in your language. If you need to say who does the action, the context indicates that it is Yahweh. Alternate translation: [Yahweh will cut off two parts in it]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('s0bi', 'ZEC', 13, 8, '13:8', 'at-fit', 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-activepassive', 'בָּ֔⁠הּ & וְ⁠הַ⁠שְּׁלִשִׁ֖ית יִוָּ֥תֶר', 1, 'The expression **the third will be left in it** is a passive verbal form. If it would be unnatural to use that form, you could express the idea in active form or in another way that is natural in your language. If you need to say who does the action, the context indicates that it is Yahweh. Alternate translation: [Yahweh will leave the third in it]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('qorx', 'ZEC', 13, 8, '13:8', 'at-fit', 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-doublet', 'יִכָּרְת֖וּ יִגְוָ֑עוּ', 1, 'The expressions **will be cut off** and **will expire** mean similar things. Yahweh is using the two terms together for emphasis. If it would be clearer for your readers, you could express the emphasis with a single phrase. Alternate translation: [will perish completely]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('u6rh', 'ZEC', 13, 8, '13:8', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/translate-fraction', 'שְׁנַ֣יִם & וְ⁠הַ⁠שְּׁלִשִׁ֖ית', 1, 'Here, **two parts** means two parts out of three equal parts, and **the third** means one part out of three equal parts.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('qauq', 'ZEC', 13, 9, '13:9', 'ISSUE:MATCH_FAIL', 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metaphor', 'וְ⁠הֵבֵאתִ֤י הַ⁠שְּׁלִשִׁית֙ בָּ⁠אֵ֔שׁ', 1, 'Here Yahweh is speaking as if the trials and suffering he would bring upon the people were **the fire**. Your language may have a comparable expression that you can use in your translation, or you could state the meaning plainly. Alternate translation: [I will bring the third through great suffering]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('kna5', 'ZEC', 13, 9, '13:9', 'ISSUE:MATCH_FAIL', 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/writing-pronouns', 'ה֣וּא יִקְרָ֣א בִ⁠שְׁמִ֗⁠י', 1, 'The pronoun **He** refers to the remaining third of the people, spoken of collectively as a single group. It may be helpful to clarify this for your readers. Alternate translation: [That remaining third will call on my name]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('wf21', 'ZEC', 13, 9, '13:9', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'בִ⁠שְׁמִ֗⁠י', 1, 'Here, **my name** represents Yahweh himself. If it would be helpful in your language, you could use an equivalent expression or plain language. Alternate translation: [me]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('s6bq', 'ZEC', 13, 9, '13:9', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-possession', 'אֱלֹהָֽ⁠י', 1, 'The speaker is not using this possessive form **my God** to indicate that he possesses or controls Yahweh. Rather, he is using these words to indicate that Yahweh is the God whom he worships. If a speaker of your language would not use the possessive form for this, you could express this idea in another way. Alternate translation: [the God I worship]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('psie', 'ZEC', 13, 9, '13:9', 'at-fit, ISSUE:MATCH_FAIL', 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-parallelism', 'וּ⁠צְרַפְתִּי⁠ם֙ כִּ⁠צְרֹ֣ף הַ⁠כֶּ֔סֶף וּ⁠בְחַנְתִּ֖י⁠ם כִּ⁠בְחֹ֣ן הַ⁠זָּהָ֑ב', 1, 'These two phrases **I will refine them as one refines the silver** and **I will test them as one tests the gold** mean basically the same thing. The second emphasizes the meaning of the first by repeating the same idea with different words. If it would be helpful to your readers, you could combine them and express the emphasis in another way. Alternate translation: [I will thoroughly purify and test them as a metalworker refines silver and gold]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('hy5b', 'ZEC', 13, 9, '13:9', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-quotesinquotes', 'ה֣וּא & אָמַ֨רְתִּי֙ עַמִּ֣⁠י & וְ⁠ה֥וּא יֹאמַ֖ר יְהוָ֥ה אֱלֹהָֽ⁠י', 1, 'If it would be clearer in your language, you could translate this so that there is not a quotation within a quotation. Alternate translation: [I will say that he is my people, and he will say that Yahweh is his God.]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('artl', 'ZEC', 13, 9, '13:9', 'at-fit, ISSUE:MATCH_FAIL', 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-simile', 'וּ⁠צְרַפְתִּי⁠ם֙ כִּ⁠צְרֹ֣ף הַ⁠כֶּ֔סֶף', 1, 'The point of this comparison is that just as **silver** is refined by fire to remove impurities, so Yahweh will purify his people through trials. If it would be helpful in your language, you could make this point explicitly. Alternate translation: [I will purify them of impurities, just as fire purifies silver]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('bvm9', 'ZEC', 13, 9, '13:9', 'ISSUE:MATCH_FAIL', 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-simile', 'וּ⁠בְחַנְתִּ֖י⁠ם כִּ⁠בְחֹ֣ן הַ⁠זָּהָ֑ב', 1, 'The point of this comparison is that just as **gold** is tested by fire to prove its genuineness, so Yahweh will test his people through trials. If it would be helpful in your language, you could make this point explicitly. Alternate translation: [I will test them to prove they are genuine, just as gold is tested by fire to prove its genuineness]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('ljq3', 'ZEC', 14, 0, '14:intro', NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, '# Zechariah 14 General Notes\n\n## Structure and Formatting\n\nThis chapter is written in prose about Jerusalem during the last days. (See: [[rc://*/tw/dict/bible/kt/lastday]])\n\n## Religious and Cultural Concepts in This Chapter\n\n### Last days\n\nZechariah often speaks of the last days by using the phrase “that day” or “in that day.” When referencing a future “day,” the translator should be aware that it is possible that the author is speaking about the last days.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('zs1r', 'ZEC', 14, 1, '14:1', NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, '# General Information:\n\nThis chapter describes the final war for the city of Jerusalem and how God will save it.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('a7h2', 'ZEC', 14, 1, '14:1', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metaphor', 'A day for Yahweh is coming when your plunder will be divided in your midst', 0, 'A future time is spoken of as if “a day is coming.” The phrase “will be divided” can be stated in active form. Alternate translation: [Soon Yahweh will judge you, and he will allow your enemies to take all of your possessions and divide if for themselves while you watch] (See also: [[rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-activepassive]])');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('q4hu', 'ZEC', 14, 2, '14:2', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-hyperbole', 'I will gather every nation against Jerusalem for battle', 0, 'Here “every nation” is a generalization that means “many nations.” Alternate translation: [I will cause many nations to attack Jerusalem]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('qi2n', 'ZEC', 14, 2, '14:2', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-activepassive', 'the city will be captured', 0, 'If your language does not use the passive form in this way, you can state this in active form or in another way that is natural in your language. Alternate translation: [your enemies will capture the city]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('lk8a', 'ZEC', 14, 2, '14:2', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-activepassive', 'The houses will be plundered and the women raped', 0, 'If your language does not use the passive form in this way, you can state this in active form or in another way that is natural in your language. Alternate translation: [Enemies will plunder the houses and rape the women]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('cej1', 'ZEC', 14, 2, '14:2', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-activepassive', 'the remainder of the people will not be cut off from the city', 0, 'Not removing people from the city is spoken of as if the people will not be “cut off.” If your language does not use the passive form in this way, you can state this in active form or in another way that is natural in your language. Alternate translation: [your enemies will allow the remaining people to stay in the city]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('l9z1', 'ZEC', 14, 3, '14:3', NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, '# General Information:\n\nThese verses continue the description of the final war for the city of Jerusalem and of how God will save it. In this prophecy, Yahweh is described as a warrior who will come and fight in battle.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('m5ez', 'ZEC', 14, 3, '14:3', NULL, NULL, 'as when he wages war on the day of battle', 0, 'Alternate translation: [just as he fought battles in the past]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('v1g4', 'ZEC', 14, 4, '14:4', NULL, NULL, 'On that day', 0, 'Alternate translation: [At that time]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('ak3r', 'ZEC', 14, 4, '14:4', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-synecdoche', 'his feet will stand on the Mount of Olives', 0, 'Here “feet” represents Yahweh. Alternate translation: [he will stand on the Mount of Olives]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('kpm4', 'ZEC', 14, 4, '14:4', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-activepassive', 'The Mount of Olives will be split … by a very great valley', 0, 'If your language does not use the passive form in this way, you can state this in active form or in another way that is natural in your language. Alternate translation: [The presences of Yahweh will split the Mount of Olives … causing there to be a very great valley]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('x9i7', 'ZEC', 14, 5, '14:5', NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, '# General Information:\n\nThese verses continue the description of the final war for the city of Jerusalem and of how God will save her.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('u952', 'ZEC', 14, 5, '14:5', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-you', 'you will flee', 0, 'Here “you” is plural and refers to the people of Jerusalem.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('n974', 'ZEC', 14, 5, '14:5', NULL, NULL, 'between Yahweh’s mountains', 0, 'This refers to the mountains created after the Mount of Olives split in half.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('q9u5', 'ZEC', 14, 5, '14:5', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/translate-names', 'Azel', 0, 'This is the name of a town or village east of Jerusalem.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('d8ly', 'ZEC', 14, 5, '14:5', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-explicit', 'You will flee just as you fled', 0, 'Here “You will” refers to the people of Jerusalem. But, “you fled” refers to their ancestors since this describes an event that happened many years earlier. Alternate translation: [You will flee just as your ancestors fled]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('n1lh', 'ZEC', 14, 5, '14:5', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-idiom', 'in the days of Uzziah, king of Judah', 0, 'Here “in the days” is an idiom that refers to the time when Uzziah was king. Alternate translation: [when Uzziah was king of Judah]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('mw1g', 'ZEC', 14, 5, '14:5', NULL, NULL, 'the holy ones', 0, 'This probably refers to God’s angels.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('g29k', 'ZEC', 14, 6, '14:6', NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, '# General Information:\n\nThese verses continue the description of the final war for the city of Jerusalem and of how God will save her.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('qjd1', 'ZEC', 14, 6, '14:6', NULL, NULL, 'On that day', 0, 'Alternate translation: [At that time]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('z2kn', 'ZEC', 14, 6, '14:6', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-explicit', 'there will be no light', 0, 'It is implied that there will be no light from the sun. Alternate translation: [there will be no light from the sun]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('yli2', 'ZEC', 14, 7, '14:7', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-activepassive', 'a day known only to Yahweh', 0, 'If your language does not use the passive form in this way, you can state this in active form or in another way that is natural in your language. Alternate translation: [only Yahweh knows when that day will begin] or “only Yahweh knows when that time will begin”');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('v254', 'ZEC', 14, 8, '14:8', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-idiom', 'living waters', 0, 'This normally means running or flowing water, rather than still or stagnant water.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('wpw5', 'ZEC', 14, 8, '14:8', NULL, NULL, 'the eastern sea', 0, 'This refers to the Dead Sea, which is east of Jerusalem.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('uks5', 'ZEC', 14, 8, '14:8', NULL, NULL, 'the western sea', 0, 'This refers to the Mediterranean Sea.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('k9gf', 'ZEC', 14, 9, '14:9', NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, '# General Information:\n\nThese verses continue the description of the final war for the city of Jerusalem and of how God will save her.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('r6ni', 'ZEC', 14, 9, '14:9', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'there will be Yahweh, the one God, and his name alone', 0, 'Here “name” represents Yahweh’s reputation or character. Alternate translation: [people will know that Yahweh is the only true God] or “people will only worship Yahweh, the one true God”');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('wmv3', 'ZEC', 14, 10, '14:10', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-explicit', 'All the land', 0, 'It is implied that this is the land of Judah. Alternate translation: [All the land of Judah]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('sj4y', 'ZEC', 14, 10, '14:10', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/translate-names', 'Arabah', 0, 'This is the name of a plain in the Jordan River Valley.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('sxq5', 'ZEC', 14, 10, '14:10', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/translate-names', 'Geba', 0, 'This is the name of a town on the northern border of Judah.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('rz4c', 'ZEC', 14, 10, '14:10', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/translate-names', 'Rimmon', 0, 'This is the name of a town south of Jerusalem.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('uk8u', 'ZEC', 14, 10, '14:10', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/grammar-connect-words-phrases', 'Jerusalem will continue to be raised up', 0, 'This contrasts Jerusalem, which will remain at a higher elevation, to the surrounding area, which is lower in elevation. The contrast can be indicated by adding the word “but.” This can also be stated in active form. Alternate translation: [But, Jerusalem will remain high up] (See also: [[rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-activepassive]])');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('eay1', 'ZEC', 14, 10, '14:10', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/translate-names', 'the Benjamin Gate … the first gate … the Corner Gate', 0, 'These are names of gates in the northeast part of city wall of Jerusalem. This could mean: (1) “the first gate” and “the Corner Gate” refer to the same gate or (2) “the first gate” and “the Corner gate” are separate gates. (See also: [[rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-explicit]])');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('t1rw', 'ZEC', 14, 10, '14:10', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/translate-names', 'the Tower of Hananel', 0, 'This refers to a strong point in the city defenses on the northern wall. It was probably built by a man named Hananel.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('rki8', 'ZEC', 14, 10, '14:10', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-explicit', 'the king’s winepresses', 0, 'This probably refers to the place where wine was made for the royal family. It was located in the southwest part of Jerusalem.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('gbk1', 'ZEC', 14, 11, '14:11', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'Jerusalem will live in safety', 0, 'Here “Jerusalem” represents the people. Alternate translation: [The people will live safely in Jerusalem]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('qiz5', 'ZEC', 14, 12, '14:12', NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, '# General Information:\n\nThese verses continue the description of the final war for the city of Jerusalem and of how God will save her.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('wg9q', 'ZEC', 14, 12, '14:12', NULL, NULL, 'even as they are standing on their feet', 0, '“while they are still standing up.” This emphasizes how quickly their flesh will rot away. They will not even have time to lie down.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('w6fr', 'ZEC', 14, 13, '14:13', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-abstractnouns', 'that great fear from Yahweh will come among them', 0, 'If your language does not use an abstract noun for the idea behind the word **fear**, you can express the same idea with a verbal form such as “terrified.” Alternate translation: [Yahweh will cause the people to be very terrified]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('yl73', 'ZEC', 14, 13, '14:13', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-idiom', 'Each one will seize the hand of another, and the hand of one will be raised up against the hand of another', 0, 'These are idioms that refer to being hostile towards another person. Alternate translation: [Each person will grab someone, and they will fight each other]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('jps4', 'ZEC', 14, 14, '14:14', NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, '# General Information:\n\nThese verses continue the description of the final war for the city of Jerusalem and of how God will save her.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('n8dy', 'ZEC', 14, 14, '14:14', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metonymy', 'Judah will also fight against Jerusalem', 0, 'Here “Judah” and “Jerusalem” represent the people that live there. Alternate translation: [Even the other people in Judah will fight against the people of Jerusalem]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('h6q8', 'ZEC', 14, 14, '14:14', NULL, NULL, 'Judah will also fight against Jerusalem', 0, 'Some versions of the Bible read, “Judah will also fight at Jerusalem.”');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('up2x', 'ZEC', 14, 14, '14:14', NULL, NULL, 'They will gather the wealth', 0, 'Alternate translation: [They will capture all the valuable possessions]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('q411', 'ZEC', 14, 14, '14:14', NULL, NULL, 'in great abundance', 0, 'Alternate translation: [in great quantities]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('wx98', 'ZEC', 14, 16, '14:16', NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, '# General Information:\n\nThese verses continue the description of the final war for the city of Jerusalem and of how God will save her.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('rf9t', 'ZEC', 14, 16, '14:16', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-idiom', 'that came against Jerusalem', 0, 'Here “came against” is an idiom. Alternate translation: [that attacked Jerusalem]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('y2h6', 'ZEC', 14, 16, '14:16', NULL, NULL, 'will instead go up from year to year', 0, 'Alternate translation: [will instead go to Jerusalem every year]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('ryt4', 'ZEC', 14, 16, '14:16', NULL, NULL, 'the Festival of Shelters', 0, 'Alternate translation: [the Festival of Tabernacles] or “the Festival of Booths” or “the Festival of Tents”');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('q1tm', 'ZEC', 14, 18, '14:18', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-metaphor', 'A plague from Yahweh will attack the nations', 0, 'Causing people to suffer from a plague is spoken of as if the plague would attack the people like an army. Alternate translation: [Yahweh will cause a plague among the people of the nations]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('ai96', 'ZEC', 14, 19, '14:19', NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, '# General Information:\n\nThese verses continue the description of the final war for the city of Jerusalem and of how God will save her.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('q1hq', 'ZEC', 14, 20, '14:20', NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, '# General Information:\n\nThese verses continue the description of the final war for the city of Jerusalem and of how God will save her.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('j9sd', 'ZEC', 14, 20, '14:20', NULL, NULL, 'the bells of the horses will say', 0, 'Alternate translation: [the inscription on the bells of the horses will say]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('ez1i', 'ZEC', 14, 20, '14:20', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-explicit', 'the basins in Yahweh’s house', 0, 'These basins were used for boiling meat in the courtyard of the temple. Alternate translation: [the cooking pots in the courtyard of the temple]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('c8cd', 'ZEC', 14, 20, '14:20', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-explicit', 'will be like the bowls before the altar', 0, 'It is implied that the basins will be sacred like the bowls used for catching the blood of the sacrifices. Alternate translation: [will be as sacred as the bowls used at the altar]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('q299', 'ZEC', 14, 21, '14:21', NULL, NULL, 'every pot in Jerusalem and Judah will be set apart to Yahweh of hosts', 0, 'Various types of pots and utensils were made especially to be used in the temple for the worship of Yahweh and for the sacrifices. These were considered special, not to be used for anything else.');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('qfn5', 'ZEC', 14, 21, '14:21', NULL, 'rc://*/ta/man/translate/figs-explicit', 'traders will no longer be in the house of Yahweh', 0, 'It was the custom for traders to sell the people things they needed in order to make proper sacrifices to Yahweh in the temple. Alternate translation: [people will no longer buy or sell things in the courtyard of the temple of Yahweh]');
INSERT INTO tn_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, support_reference, quote, occurrence, note) VALUES ('hw3t', 'ZEC', 14, 21, '14:21', NULL, NULL, 'traders', 0, 'Some versions of the Bible translate “traders” as “Canaanites.”');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('bab5', 'ZEC', 1, 1, '1:1', NULL, NULL, 0, 'During whose reign did Zechariah prophesy?', 'Zechariah prophesied during the reign of Darius.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('ft2k', 'ZEC', 1, 1, '1:1', NULL, NULL, 0, 'Who was Zechariah?', 'Zechariah was the son of Berechiah, the son of Iddo the prophet.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('ywqh', 'ZEC', 1, 3, '1:3', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What did Yahweh of hosts say he would do if the people would turn to him?', 'Yahweh of hosts said if the people would turn to him, he would return to them.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('x8i8', 'ZEC', 1, 4, '1:4', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What did their fathers do when Yahweh told them to turn from their evil ways and wicked practices?', 'Their fathers would not hear and did not pay attention to Yahweh.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('mey1', 'ZEC', 1, 6, '1:6', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What did the people say when they repented?', 'When they repented the people said, “Yahweh of hosts’s plans are made in keeping with his word and practice, and he has carried them out.”');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('cz8o', 'ZEC', 1, 8, '1:8', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What did Zechariah see when the word of Yahweh came to him in the night?', 'Zechariah saw a man riding on a red horse among the myrtle trees in the valley. Behind him were red, reddish-brown, and white horses.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('x97f', 'ZEC', 1, 10, '1:10', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What were the horses that Zechariah saw?', 'The horses were those Yahweh had sent out to roam throughout the earth.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('dc9e', 'ZEC', 1, 11, '1:11', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What did the horses who roamed throughout the earth find?', 'The horses found all the earth sitting still and at rest.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('lnvy', 'ZEC', 1, 12, '1:12', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What question did the angel of Yahweh have for Yahweh concerning Jerusalem and the cities of Judah?', 'The angel of Yahweh asked Yahweh how long he would show no compassion to Jerusalem and the cities of Judah.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('xaeg', 'ZEC', 1, 16, '1:16-17', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What did Yahweh of hosts say concerning Jerusalem and the cities of Judah?', 'Yahweh said he had returned to Jerusalem with mercies, that his house would be built within her and the measuring line would be stretched out over Jerusalem. Yahweh also said his cities would once again overflow with goodness and Yahweh would again comfort Zion and once again choose Jerusalem.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('p5hm', 'ZEC', 1, 19, '1:19', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What were the four horns that Zechariah saw?', 'The four horns were those who had scattered Judah, Israel, and Jerusalem.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('cnte', 'ZEC', 1, 20, '1:20-21', NULL, NULL, 0, 'Who were the four blacksmiths that Zechariah saw and what were they going to do?', 'The blacksmiths were people who were going to drive out and cast down the horns of the nations who had lifted up any horn against the land of Judah to scatter her.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('x9oe', 'ZEC', 2, 2, '2:2', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What was the young man going to do with the measuring line in his hand?', 'He was going to measure Jerusalem, to determine its width and its length.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('jwwr', 'ZEC', 2, 4, '2:4', NULL, NULL, 0, 'Why did the second angel say that Jerusalem would sit in the open country?', 'The second angel said this because of the multitudes of men and beasts that would be within her.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('fp96', 'ZEC', 2, 5, '2:5', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What did Yahweh say he would become for Jerusalem?', 'Yahweh said he would become a wall of fire around her and he would be the glory in her midst.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('jdy2', 'ZEC', 2, 7, '2:7', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What was Yahweh’s declaration to those who lived with the daughter of Babylon?', 'Yahweh told them to escape to Zion.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('mqz5', 'ZEC', 2, 9, '2:9', NULL, NULL, 0, 'How were they supposed to know that Yahweh of hosts had sent the second angel?', 'The second angel said Judah and Israel would know Yahweh had sent him when he shook his hand over the nations that plundered them and when the nations that plundered Judah and Israel were plundered for their slaves.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('jgyb', 'ZEC', 2, 11, '2:11', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What will happen when Yahweh comes and encamps in Zion?', 'When that happens great nations will join themselves to Yahweh and those of Zion will become his people.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('kl8l', 'ZEC', 2, 13, '2:13', NULL, NULL, 0, 'Why is all flesh told to be silent before Yahweh?', 'All flesh is told to be silent before Yahweh because Yahweh has been roused from out of the heavens.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('nol0', 'ZEC', 3, 1, '3:1', NULL, NULL, 0, 'Who was near Joshua the high priest?', 'Joshua was standing before Yahweh and Satan was standing at his right hand.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('dxwx', 'ZEC', 3, 1, '3:1', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What was Satan doing at Joshua’s right hand?', 'Satan was accusing Joshua of sin.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('dmzy', 'ZEC', 3, 3, '3:3', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What was Joshua wearing as he stood before the angel?', 'Joshua was dressed in filthy garments.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('qq8z', 'ZEC', 3, 4, '3:4', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What did the angel of Yahweh say he had done for Joshua?', 'The angel said he had caused Joshua’s iniquity to pass from Joshua.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('wgpe', 'ZEC', 3, 4, '3:4-5', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What happened concerning Joshua’s clothing?', 'The angel commanded the filthy garments to be removed from Joshua and for Joshua to be clothed with fine clothing; a clean turban and clean garments.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('ij2h', 'ZEC', 3, 7, '3:7', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What did Yahweh promise Joshua, the high priest, if he would walk in Yahweh’s ways and keep his commandments?', 'Yahweh promised Joshua that he would govern Yahweh’s house and keep Yahweh’s courts. Yahweh also promised that he would allow Joshua to come and go before those who stand before Yahweh.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('mkox', 'ZEC', 3, 8, '3:8', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What was the servant called that Yahweh himself was going to bring up?', 'That servant was called “the Branch.”');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('g7om', 'ZEC', 3, 9, '3:9', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What was the first part of the message to be engraved on the seven sided stone?', 'The first part of the message was that Yahweh would remove the sin from that land in one day.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('u83v', 'ZEC', 3, 10, '3:10', NULL, NULL, 0, 'According to Yahweh when will each man invite his neighbor to relax under his vine and under his fig tree?', 'Yahweh said this would occur “in that day.”');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('uuuj', 'ZEC', 4, 2, '4:2-3', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What did Zechariah see when he was roused?', 'Zechariah saw a gold lampstand with a bowl on top, with seven lamps and two olive trees by the bowl.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('oiop', 'ZEC', 4, 4, '4:4-5', NULL, NULL, 0, 'Did Zechariah understand what the things in the vision meant?', 'No, Zechariah told the angel who was talking with him that he did not understand the meaning of those things in the vision.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('qmgu', 'ZEC', 4, 6, '4:6', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What was the word of Yahweh to Zerubbabel about how things were going to get done?', 'The word of Yahweh to Zerubbabel was, “Not by might nor by power, but only by my Spirit.”');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('ihie', 'ZEC', 4, 7, '4:7', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What will be shouted when Zerubbabel brings out the top stone?', 'They will shout, “It is beautiful! May God bless it!”');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('h3yr', 'ZEC', 4, 9, '4:9', NULL, NULL, 0, 'How will the people know that Yahweh sent Zechariah to them?', 'The people will know when they see the prophecy fulfilled; the hand of Zerubbabel lay the foundation of that house and his hands finish it.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('k12j', 'ZEC', 4, 10, '4:10', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What will the people see in the hand of Zerubbabel?', 'The people will see the plumb stone in Zerubbabel’s hand.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('ftxp', 'ZEC', 4, 10, '4:10', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What did the the seven lamps mean?', 'The seven lamps are the eyes of Yahweh that roam over the whole earth.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('g1h2', 'ZEC', 4, 14, '4:14', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What are the two olive branches?', 'The two olive branches are the two sons of oil who stand beside the Lord of the whole earth.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('n7y0', 'ZEC', 5, 2, '5:2', NULL, NULL, 0, 'How big was the scroll that Zechariah saw?', 'The scroll was twenty cubits long and ten cubits wide.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('smfd', 'ZEC', 5, 3, '5:3', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What did the angel say the flying scroll was?', 'The angel said the flying scroll was the curse that goes out over the face of the whole land.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('m1bx', 'ZEC', 5, 3, '5:3', NULL, NULL, 0, 'Who did the scroll curse?', 'The scroll was a curse to every thief and to everyone who swears a false oath.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('u5dw', 'ZEC', 5, 4, '5:4', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What did the curse do to the thief and to the one who swears falsely by Yahweh’s name?', 'The curse will enter their houses and remain there and consume the timber and stones of their houses.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('qqpf', 'ZEC', 5, 6, '5:6', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What was in the basket that Zechariah saw and what did the angel say it was?', 'An ephah was in the basket that Zechariah saw, and the angel said the ephah “is their iniquity in the whole land.”');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('ahim', 'ZEC', 5, 8, '5:8', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What did the angel say the woman in the basket was?', 'The angel said of the woman in the basket, “This is Wickedness!”');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('zng4', 'ZEC', 5, 9, '5:9', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What did the two women, who had wings like a stork’s wings, do with the basket?', 'The two women lifted up the basket between earth and heaven.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('p7r9', 'ZEC', 5, 11, '5:11', NULL, NULL, 0, 'Where were the women taking the basket and for what purpose?', 'The women took the basket to build a temple in Shinar for it, so that when the temple is ready, the basket will be set there on its prepared base.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('ppm8', 'ZEC', 6, 1, '6:1', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What did Zechariah see coming out from between two bronze mountains?', 'Zechariah saw four chariots coming out from between two bronze mountains.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('v6ca', 'ZEC', 6, 2, '6:2-3', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What color were the horses of each chariot?', 'The first chariot had red horses, the second had black horses, the third had white horses, and the fourth had spotted gray horses.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('bm9t', 'ZEC', 6, 5, '6:5', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What did the angel say the chariots were?', 'The angel said the chariots were the four winds of heaven.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('ukr2', 'ZEC', 6, 5, '6:5', NULL, NULL, 0, 'Where had these four chariots been?', 'These four chariots had been standing before the Lord of all the earth.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('f19w', 'ZEC', 6, 6, '6:6', NULL, NULL, 0, 'Where were the three chariots with the black, the white and the spotted gray horses going?', 'The chariot with the black horses went out to the north country. The chariot with white horses went out to the west country. The chariot with the spotted gray horses went out to the south country.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('r61x', 'ZEC', 6, 8, '6:8', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What was the chariot with the black horses that went out to the north country going to accomplish?', 'That chariot with the black horses was going to appease the angel’s spirit concerning the north country.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('scuu', 'ZEC', 6, 10, '6:10-11', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What was Zechariah supposed to do with the offering he collected from Heldai, Tobijah, and Jedaiah?', 'Zechariah was told to take the offering into the house of Josiah, son of Zephaniah. Zechariah was to take the silver and gold, make a crown and set it upon the head of Joshua the son of Jehozadak, the high priest.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('jo12', 'ZEC', 6, 12, '6:12-13', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What did Yahweh of hosts say Joshua son of Jehozadak, the high priest, would do?', 'Yahweh said Joshua would grow up where he is and build the temple of Yahweh, raise up its splendor, and then sit and rule on his throne.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('p99n', 'ZEC', 6, 14, '6:14', NULL, NULL, 0, 'Why was a crown to be placed in the temple of Yahweh?', 'A crown was to be placed in the temple of Yahweh to Heldai, Tobijah, and Jedaiah and as a memorial to the generosity of the son of Zephaniah.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('mf0f', 'ZEC', 6, 15, '6:15', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What must the people do for these prophetic events to come true?', 'Yahweh said these events would happen “if you truly listen to the voice of Yahweh your God!”');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('jw8y', 'ZEC', 7, 2, '7:2', NULL, NULL, 0, 'Why did the people of Bethel send Sharezer, Regem Melech, and their men?', 'The people of Bethel sent them to beg for Yahweh’s favor.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('x726', 'ZEC', 7, 3, '7:3', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What did Sharezer, Melech, and their men ask the priest and the prophets?', 'They asked, “Should I mourn in the fifth month by means of a fast, as I have done these many years?”');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('k6ub', 'ZEC', 7, 5, '7:5-6', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What two questions did Yahweh ask the people of the land and the priests through Zechariah concerning fasting, eating and drinking?', 'The first question Yahweh asked was, “When you fasted and mourned in the fifth and seventh month for these seventy years, were you truly fasting for me?” The second question was, “And when you ate and drank, did you not eat and drink for yourselves?”');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('g0py', 'ZEC', 7, 7, '7:7', NULL, NULL, 0, 'Briefly, what was the last question Yahweh asked the priests and people of the land?', 'In brief, Yahweh asked if these were not the same words Yahweh told the people while they still inhabited Jerusalem, the surrounding cities, the Negev, and the western foothills.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('pfi3', 'ZEC', 7, 8, '7:8-10', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What did Yahweh through Zechariah tell the people to do?', 'Yahweh said to judge with true justice, covenant faithfulness, and mercy. He said not to oppress the widow, the orphan, the foreigner or the poor person and not to do evil to one another.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('xh89', 'ZEC', 7, 11, '7:11', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What was the response of the people to Yahweh’s instructions?', 'The people refused to pay attention to Yahweh’s words.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('p1i5', 'ZEC', 7, 13, '7:13-14', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What did Yahweh say he would do when those who formerly refused to listen to Yahweh called out to him?', 'Yahweh said he would not listen to them and, furthermore, he would scatter those people with a whirlwind to all the nations they had not seen.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('u4cn', 'ZEC', 8, 2, '8:2', NULL, NULL, 0, 'How does Yahweh express his passion for Zion?', 'Yahweh expresses his passion for Zion with great zeal and great anger.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('o1eu', 'ZEC', 8, 3, '8:3', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What will Jerusalem and the mountain of Yahweh be called when Yahweh returns to live in the midst of Jerusalem?', 'Jerusalem will be called “The City of Truth” and the mountain of Yahweh will be called “The Holy Mountain” when Yahweh returns to live in the midst of Jerusalem.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('aphi', 'ZEC', 8, 4, '8:4-5', NULL, NULL, 0, 'Who will again be found in the streets of Jerusalem?', 'Old men and old women will be in the streets, and the streets will be full of boys and girls playing in them.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('mjoq', 'ZEC', 8, 7, '8:7', NULL, NULL, 0, 'Where was Yahweh going to rescue his people from?', 'Yahweh was going to rescue his people from the land of the sunrise and from the land of the setting sun.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('zofm', 'ZEC', 8, 9, '8:9', NULL, NULL, 0, 'Why did Yahweh want the people to strengthen their hands?', 'Yahweh wanted the people to strengthen their hands so the temple could be rebuilt.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('j9tu', 'ZEC', 8, 10, '8:10', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What happened before those days when the foundation of Yahweh’s house was laid?', 'In those days, no crops were gathered in, there was no profit, and there was no peace from enemies. Yahweh set every person each against his neighbor.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('hew2', 'ZEC', 8, 11, '8:11-12', NULL, NULL, 0, 'How did Yahweh say it would be during Zechariah’s time?', 'Yahweh said it would not be as in former days. He said seeds of peace would be sown. The climbing vine would give its fruit, and the earth would give its produce. The skies would give their dew. Yahweh would make the remnant of that people inherit all those things.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('uuz0', 'ZEC', 8, 16, '8:16-17', NULL, NULL, 0, 'How does Yahweh command the people to behave and why?', 'Yahweh said the people must all speak truth with his neighbor, and judge with truth, justice, and peace in their gates. He said let no one plot evil in their heart against their neighbor nor be attracted to false oaths. Yahweh commanded these things because they were things he hates.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('fyjz', 'ZEC', 8, 19, '8:19', NULL, NULL, 0, 'In light of the fact that the fasts of the fourth, fifth, seventh and tenth months were going to be times of joy, gladness and happy festivals for the house of Judah, what were they told to do by Yahweh?', 'They were told to love truth and peace.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('ly5h', 'ZEC', 8, 20, '8:20-22', NULL, NULL, 0, 'Who did Yahweh say would come to seek him and beg his favor?', 'Yahweh said many people from many different cities and mighty nations would come to seek Yahweh and beg his favor.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('qx8r', 'ZEC', 8, 23, '8:23', NULL, NULL, 0, 'In those days, why will ten men from every language and nation ask to go up to Jerusalem with Yahweh’s people?', 'They will ask to go up to Jerusalem with Yahweh’s people for they will have heard that God is with them.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('m4vl', 'ZEC', 9, 1, '9:1-2', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What does Yahweh’s declaration concern?', 'Yahweh’s declaration concerns the land of Hadrach and Damascus, Hamath, and Tyre and SIdon.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('vnm2', 'ZEC', 9, 4, '9:4', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What does Yahweh say the Lord will do to Tyre?', 'Yahweh says, “The Lord will dispossess her and destroy her strength on the sea, so she will be devoured by fire.”');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('uu2i', 'ZEC', 9, 6, '9:6-7', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What did Yahweh say he would do to the Philistines and what would become of them?', 'Yahweh said he would cut off the pride of the Philistines. Yahweh also said they would become a remnant for God like a clan in Judah.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('yyba', 'ZEC', 9, 8, '9:8', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What is one reason Yahweh gives for camping around his land?', 'Yahweh said he would camp around his land against enemy armies so no one could pass through or return, for he said no oppressor would pass through it any more.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('yvwy', 'ZEC', 9, 9, '9:9', NULL, NULL, 0, 'Why is the daughter of Zion told to shout with great joy and the daughter of Jerusalem told to shout with happiness?', 'They are told to do this because their king is coming to them with righteousness and is going to rescue them.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('fp5q', 'ZEC', 9, 9, '9:9', NULL, NULL, 0, 'How will their king come to them?', 'Their king will be humble and will ride on a donkey, on the colt of a donkey.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('fh96', 'ZEC', 9, 10, '9:10', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What will this king speak to the nations?', 'That king will speak peace to the nations.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('zic3', 'ZEC', 9, 10, '9:10', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What will be the extent of that king’s dominion?', 'That king’s dominion will be from sea to sea, and from the river to the ends of the earth.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('hyk5', 'ZEC', 9, 11, '9:11', NULL, NULL, 0, 'Why has Yahweh set free their prisoners from the pit where there is no water?', 'Yahweh says he has done this because of the blood of his covenant with them.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('qcrr', 'ZEC', 9, 13, '9:13', NULL, NULL, 0, 'Against whom has Yahweh roused the sons of Zion?', 'Yahweh has roused the sons of Zion against the sons of Greece.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('fbw1', 'ZEC', 9, 13, '9:13', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What has Yahweh made Zion like?', 'Yahweh has made Zion like a warrior’s sword.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('oryd', 'ZEC', 9, 16, '9:16', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What will Zion be on that day when Yahweh, their God, rescues them?', 'On that day, Zion will be the jewels of a crown raised up over Yahweh’s land.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('acur', 'ZEC', 10, 1, '10:1', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What will Yahweh do for Zion?', 'Yahweh will provide rain showers for Zion when they ask him, and plants in the field.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('j3l1', 'ZEC', 10, 2, '10:2', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What causes the people to wander like sheep and suffer?', 'The people wander like sheep and suffer because the household idols speak falsely, the diviners envision a lie, they tell empty dreams and give empty comfort. The people also have no shepherd.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('zs12', 'ZEC', 10, 3, '10:3', NULL, NULL, 0, 'Who did Yahweh say he would punish?', 'Yahweh said he would punish the male goats, meaning the leaders.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('ihag', 'ZEC', 10, 4, '10:4', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What did Yahweh say would come from the house of Judah?', 'Yahweh said the cornerstone, the tent peg, the war bow, and every leader would come from the house of Judah.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('bd9g', 'ZEC', 10, 6, '10:6', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What did Yahweh say he would do for the houses of Judah and Joseph?', 'Yahweh said he would strengthen the house of Judah and save the house of Joseph. Yahweh said he would restore them, have mercy on them.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('oljg', 'ZEC', 10, 9, '10:9', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What will Judah and Ephraim do when they remember Yahweh in the distant countries where Yahweh has sown them?', 'They and their children will live and return when they remember Yahweh in the distant countries where he has sown them.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('seoo', 'ZEC', 10, 11, '10:11', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What did Yahweh say he would do to Egypt and Assyria after he gathers those of the house of Judah from those places?', 'Yahweh said he would bring down the majesty of Assyria and make the scepter of Egypt go away from the Egyptians.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('jgdz', 'ZEC', 11, 3, '11:3', NULL, NULL, 0, 'Why do the shepherds howl?', 'The shepherds howl because their glory has been destroyed.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('bnph', 'ZEC', 11, 4, '11:4', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What did Yahweh tell Zechariah to do?', 'Yahweh told Zechariah to, “Shepherd the flock meant for slaughter!”');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('xlaj', 'ZEC', 11, 6, '11:6', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What did Yahweh say he would do to the inhabitants of Judah?', 'Yahweh said he would no longer pity them but cause each man to fall into his shepherd’s hands and into his king’s hands, and they would crush the land.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('x38p', 'ZEC', 11, 7, '11:7', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What were the names of the two staffs that Zechariah used to shepherd the flock meant for the slaughter?', 'The names of the two staffs were “Favor” and “Unity.”');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('mov6', 'ZEC', 11, 8, '11:8', NULL, NULL, 0, 'Why did Zechariah destroy three shepherds in one month?', 'Zechariah did this because he grew weary with the shepherds and they also hated him.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('ad34', 'ZEC', 11, 10, '11:10', NULL, NULL, 0, 'Why did Zechariah break his staff, “Favor”?', 'He broke it to break the covenant that he had made with all his tribes.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('gluo', 'ZEC', 11, 12, '11:12', NULL, NULL, 0, 'How much was Zechariah paid?', 'Zechariah was paid thirty pieces of silver.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('nlba', 'ZEC', 11, 13, '11:13', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What did Yahweh tell Zechariah to do with his thirty pieces of silver?', 'Zechariah was told to deposit the silver in the treasury.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('l3sr', 'ZEC', 11, 14, '11:14', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What did breaking the second staff, “Unity,” do?', 'Breaking the second staff broke the brotherhood between Judah and Israel.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('xjbi', 'ZEC', 11, 16, '11:16', NULL, NULL, 0, 'Yahweh said he would raise up a shepherd in the land. What will that shepherd do?', 'That shepherd will not care for the sheep. He will not seek the sheep who have gone astray, nor heal the crippled sheep. He will not feed the steadfast sheep, but will eat the fattened sheep and tear off their hooves.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('ausn', 'ZEC', 11, 17, '11:17', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What curse is pronounced upon the worthless shepherd who forsakes the flock?', 'This is the curse: “May the sword come against his right arm and his right eye! May his right arm wither away and his right eye be blind!”');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('zcjz', 'ZEC', 12, 1, '12:1', NULL, NULL, 0, 'Who is Yahweh who makes this declaration concerning Israel?', 'Yahweh is the one who stretched out the skies and laid the foundation of the earth, who fashions the spirit of mankind within him.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('j0nc', 'ZEC', 12, 3, '12:3', NULL, NULL, 0, 'Who is going to gather against Jerusalem?', 'All the nations of the earth are going to gather against Jerusalem.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('czny', 'ZEC', 12, 4, '12:4', NULL, NULL, 0, 'On the day when all the nations gather against Judah, what specific things did Yahweh say he would do to the horses and riders of the enemy armies?', 'Yahweh said he would strike every horse with terror and each rider with madness. Yahweh also said he would strike every horse of the armies blind.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('lx80', 'ZEC', 12, 6, '12:6', NULL, NULL, 0, 'In that day, what will the leaders of Judah be like?', 'In that day, the leaders will be like fire pots among wood and like a flaming torch to standing grain.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('h3m1', 'ZEC', 12, 7, '12:7', NULL, NULL, 0, 'Why will Yahweh save the tents of Judah first?', 'Yahweh will save the tents of Judah first so that the honor of the house of David and the honor of those who live in Jerusalem may not be greater than the rest of Judah.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('t4bq', 'ZEC', 12, 9, '12:9', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What is Yahweh determined to do on that day?', 'Yahweh said that on that day he is determined to destroy all the nations who come against Jerusalem.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('bxsd', 'ZEC', 12, 10, '12:10', NULL, NULL, 0, 'On that day, what will Yahweh pour out on the house of David and the inhabitants of Jerusalem?', 'Yahweh will pour out a spirit of compassion and supplication.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('fgp7', 'ZEC', 12, 10, '12:10', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What will the house of David and the inhabitants of Jerusalem do when they look upon him whom they have pierced?', 'When they look on him whom they have pierced, they will lament and mourn for him as one mourns and laments for an only son or over the death of a firstborn son.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('n6zf', 'ZEC', 12, 12, '12:12-14', NULL, NULL, 0, 'How will the land mourn in that day?', 'In that day, each family will mourn separately from other families and in each family they will mourn separately, their wives will be separate from the men.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('fjvz', 'ZEC', 13, 1, '13:1', NULL, NULL, 0, 'For what will the spring be that is opened for the house of David on that day?', 'The spring will be for their sin and impurity.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('zpv8', 'ZEC', 13, 2, '13:2', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What will Yahweh cut off from the land and why?', 'Yahweh will cut off the names of idols from the land so they will no longer be remembered.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('arab', 'ZEC', 13, 2, '13:2', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What will Yahweh cause to pass out of the land?', 'Yahweh will cause the false prophets and their unclean spirits to pass out of the land.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('feft', 'ZEC', 13, 3, '13:3', NULL, NULL, 0, 'If any man continues to prophesy, what will his father and mother do to him?', 'His father and mother who bore him will impale him when he prophesies.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('eym6', 'ZEC', 13, 4, '13:4', NULL, NULL, 0, 'In that day, why will he who prophesies no longer wear a hairy cloak?', 'He who prophesies will no longer wear a hairy cloak so that he might deceive the people.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('hb24', 'ZEC', 13, 7, '13:7', NULL, NULL, 0, 'Who is the shepherd?', 'The shepherd is “the man who stands close to me.”');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('w1ey', 'ZEC', 13, 7, '13:7', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What will happen to the flock when the shepherd is killed?', 'When the shepherd is killed the flock will scatter.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('g0ja', 'ZEC', 13, 8, '13:8', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What does Yahweh declare will happen throughout all the land?', 'Yahweh declares that two portions of it will be cut off. They will perish; only a third will remain there.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('ewbc', 'ZEC', 13, 9, '13:9', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What will happen to the third that remain there?', 'The third that remain there will be brought through the fire, refined and tested.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('y99s', 'ZEC', 13, 9, '13:9', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What will the third that remain there say?', 'The third that remain there will say, “Yahweh is my God!”');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('wsbh', 'ZEC', 14, 2, '14:2', NULL, NULL, 0, 'Why will Jerusalem’s plunder be divided in their midst?', 'Jerusalem’s plunder will be divided in their midst because Yahweh will gather every nation against Jerusalem for battle, and the city will be captured. The houses will be plundered.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('jotw', 'ZEC', 14, 3, '14:3', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What will happen to the nations that fought against Jerusalem?', 'Yahweh will go out and wage war against those nations as when he wages war on the day of battle.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('sigk', 'ZEC', 14, 4, '14:4', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What will happen to the Mount of Olives when Yahweh stands on it?', 'The Mount of Olives will be split in half with a very great valley between the two halves.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('tvuu', 'ZEC', 14, 5, '14:5', NULL, NULL, 0, 'When will Yahweh and the holy ones come?', 'Yahweh and the holy ones will come after the inhabitants of Jerusalem flee down the valley between Yahweh’s mountains.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('bd5v', 'ZEC', 14, 8, '14:8', NULL, NULL, 0, 'Where will the running water go that flows from Jerusalem?', 'Half of the water will go to the eastern sea, and half will flow toward the western sea.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('as3w', 'ZEC', 14, 9, '14:9', NULL, NULL, 0, 'Who will be king over all the earth?', 'Yahweh will be king over all the earth.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('se7d', 'ZEC', 14, 11, '14:11', NULL, NULL, 0, 'Will God destroy Jerusalem?', 'There will be no more destruction from God against them; Jersusalem will live in safety.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('pdzm', 'ZEC', 14, 12, '14:12', NULL, NULL, 0, 'With what plague will Yahweh attack all the peoples that waged war against Jerusalem?', 'The flesh, eyes, and tongues of all the people that waged war against Jerusalem will rot.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('du3t', 'ZEC', 14, 13, '14:13', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What will happen when that great fear from Yahweh comes among them?', 'Each man will seize his neighbor’s hand; each hand will be raised against its neighbor’s hand.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('opgl', 'ZEC', 14, 16, '14:16', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What will all who remain in those nations that came against Jerusalem do?', 'All those who remain in those nations will go up from year to year to worship the king, Yahweh of hosts, and to keep the Festival of Shelters.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('gsnx', 'ZEC', 14, 17, '14:17-18', NULL, NULL, 0, 'What will happen if anyone from all the nations of the earth does not go up to Jerusalem to worship the king, Yahweh of hosts?', 'If anyone does not go up to Jerusalem, Yahweh will not bring rain on them. A plague from Yahweh will attack the nations that do not go up to keep the Festival of Shelters.');
INSERT INTO tq_rows (id, book, chapter, verse, ref_raw, tags, quote, occurrence, question, response) VALUES ('t0xs', 'ZEC', 14, 21, '14:21', NULL, NULL, 0, 'On that day who will no longer be in the house of Yahweh of hosts?', 'On that day traders will no longer be in the house of Yahweh of hosts.');
